Vaccine induced rash; One infant younger than 12 months;  Information has been received from author concerning to one infant younger than 12 months that had been exposed to measles in authors pediatric emergency department (ED), resulting in his receipt of the Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (manufacturer unknown) (strength, lot number and expiration date not reported) in accordance with protocol 3 days after exposure. He returned to the pediatric ED on 2 occasions thereafter for fever and febrile seizure, and during his second visit developed a rash. This was 12 days after his original exposure, a timeline that would be consistent with contracting measles. This initiated a full postexposure investigation of 80 children who were considered at risk of measles exposure during either of his 2 visits. Ultimately, through polymerase chain reaction sequencing, he was determined to have vaccine-induced rash, a reaction that occurs in approximately 5% of individuals immunized. The sequencing results were not available until after the exposure investigation was completed. The time for sequencing in the vaccine-associated rash was 8 days, and in this time frame, critical decisions on prophylaxis needed to be made regarding suspected measles exposure. The patient's outcome was not reported.  This report is linked to case US-009507513-2009USA001403 from the same literature article.

Patient received 2 doses of Varivax and immunity level is not achieved; This spontaneous report as received from a physician via company representative, referring to a female patient of unknown age. The patient had no pertinent medical history neither drug reactions or allergies. Information regarding the patient's concurrent conditions and concomitant therapies was not provided. It was reported that the patient did not have previous varicella vaccinations and a titer was checked and was low.  On 11-JUN-2019, the patient was vaccinated with an initial booster of varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck) (VARIVAX), subcutaneously (dose, route of administration, vaccination scheme frequency, anatomical site of vaccination, lot number and expiration date were not reported) as prevention of varicella. Subsequently, another titer was drawn and remained low. Therefore, on 30-MAY-2020, the patient was vaccinated with a second booster of varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck) (VARIVAX), subcutaneously (dose, route of administration, vaccination scheme frequency, and anatomical site of vaccination were not reported; lot number S030244 as been verified to be valid, expiration date reported and validated as 26-SEP-2021).  On 22-AUG-2020, subsequent serologic testiong-titers was drawn after second booster of varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck) (VARIVAX) and still remained low (antibody test negative). Pituitary tumor; Diagnosed with Polycystic ovary syndrome; diagnosed with  non-determined viral infection; Mononucleosis; shingles; H1N1 immediately following the first dose of Gardasil 9; This spontaneous report as received from a 13 year old female patient referring to herself. Information regarding the patient's medical history, drug reactions or allergies, and concurrent conditions was not provided. Concomitant therapies included cabergoline. It was reported that the patient had zero health issued up until the hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast)(GARDASIL 9) vaccination.   On 31-AUG-2010, the patient was vaccinated with the first dose of hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast)(GARDASIL 9) intramuscularly (strength, dose, frequency, anatomical location, lot # and expiration date were not provided) for prophylaxis. Immediately, after vaccination, the patient presented H1N1 with a fever that lasted for 34 days.  On 13-OCT-2010, the patient was vaccinated with the second dose of hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast)(GARDASIL 9) intramuscularly (strength, dose, frequency, anatomical location, lot # and expiration date were not provided) for prophylaxis. Then, on 30-AUG-2011, the patient was vaccinated with the third dose of hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast)(GARDASIL 9) intramuscularly (strength, dose, frequency, anatomical location, lot # and expiration date were not provided) for prophylaxis.  On an unspecified date in January 2013, the patent experienced shingles (herpes zoster). On an unspecified date in September 2013, the  patient developed mononucleosis (infectious mononucleosis) and was symptomatic for 6 months. On an unspecified date in September 2014, the patient was diagnosed with a non determined viral infection which lasted for 6 months. On an unspecified date in May 2020, the patient was diagnosed with polycistic ovary syndrome.  On an unspecified date in June 2020, the patient had a pituitary tumour and received cabergoline as treatment. Antibody tests were performed but results were not reported. The outcome of pituitary tumour, polycystic ovaries, infectious mononucleosis, herpes zoster and h1n1 influenza was reported as not resolved. The outcome of viral infection was reported as resolved. The reporter considered h1n1 influenza, pituitary tumour, polycystic ovaries, viral infection, infectious mononucleosis and herpes zoster to be related to HPV rL1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 VLP vaccine (yeast)(GARDASIL 9).     Upon internal review, pituitary tumour was determined to be medically significant.  This is one of two cases from the same reporter.; Sender's Comments:  US-009507513-2009USA000340:

Herpes zoster; Postherpetic Neuralgia.; Information has been received regarding a case in litigation regarding a male patient (pt) of unknown age. There was no information about the pt's concurrent conditions, medical history or concomitant medication.  On or around 11-SEP-2017, the pt was vaccinated zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster) (dose, route of administration, lot number and expiration date were not reported).  Shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt suffered herpes zoster and postherpetic neuralgia. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, the pt's symptoms resulted in physical limitations not presented prior to using the vaccine. The pt also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of his condition. The pt suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. The pt suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the events was not reported.

ENCOURAGED TO GET SOMETHING TO EAT WITH PROTEIN/CARBS, TAKE IT EASY TODAY AND CONTACT DOCTOR IF FURTHER PROBLEMS. STATES THIS HAPPENED 2 TIMES BEFORE WHEN YOUNGER AFTER BEE STING AND WHEN DEHYDRATED.

Site pain which was usual for me ever year taking a flu shot; but then headache behind the eyes and left side of the head and nausea not usual. Continued for the day of the injection then sleep. Woke in the middle of the night with higher than usual blood pressure for me: 155/79 with a 92 pulse. No fever.  Called nurse line at insurance and took Tylenol which helped.  The next day when Tylenol wore off headache returned with nausea, dry mouth some body aches. Contacted my PCP who said the symptoms may last into tomorrow and I will report back to him. I am reporting because this is the first time a vaccine has disrupted my routine at all, and not my first time taking  the over 65 dose. I hope my reporting may be helpful even though it did not cause an emergency.

Close to twenty four hours post vaccination, I began to have severe swelling, redness and heat at the injection site. Fever and body aches. I felt as though I actively had the flu. Very weak and sore. This lasted for 3 days and got so severe I was unable to even move my arm. I began to have relief Sunday 9/6/2020. Today ( 9/8/2020) it is bruised still and has a small mass right at the injection site. I feel back to normal today. I felt i should report this for the purpose I don't think the vaccination was studied in people who have actually had shingles and at my age as well. I have had shingles 11 times from the age if 18-30.

First, I was given the high-dose flu vaccine (they said it was for over age 50) at the same time as the SHINGRIX vaccine, so I'm not sure if my side effects were due to an interaction, etc. That said, my Sx were extreme fatigue (starting about 10:30 am and  lasting 3-4 days), but the worst AEs started about 2:00 pm that day, and included dizziness (couldn't sit up), tingling/numbness and shakiness in hands, sweating/hot feeling (but no fever), heavy chest, fast/hard heartbeat - all of which lasted about 3 hours.. I was never warned that I could experience these (or any) side effects, and so I called the nurse, and she said these were all expected side effects and that I should only worry if I got a rash around the injection site. I feel like these were pretty severe, not to mention scary, and worth reporting.
OTHER_MEDS: Armour thyroid, multivitamin, Vitamin D, magnesium/calcium supplement

A contract employee came in on 8/18/20 for both an MMR and a Varicella Zoster shot, since he was not immune to Mumps, Rubella nor Varicella when his titers were checked, and he did not have immunization records. After receiving the MMR shot and then the VARIVAX shot, the employee started feeling lightheaded. Had him lower his head down between his knees, applied an icepack to his neck and had him breathe slowly in through his nose and out his mouth. After about 10 minutes, the employee did not feel any better and thought he might pass out, so the RN assisted him to the floor of the clinic and raised his legs up onto the seat of a chair.  A few minutes later, his legs started shaking (tremors).  He stated he had never had a seizure nor this type of reaction.  A few minutes later, his arms then also started shaking (tremors). . All along this RN kept asking if he was experiencing trouble breathing, swelling of his tongue or throat, or itching., which he denied throughout.  RN continued to check his vitals and at 1005: BP (132/80), heart rate (92) and pulse ox (88%). RN called the ER charge RN at 1007, who recommended RN call a MET, which was called at 1008. The MET arrived within a couple of minutes and assessed the EE and took him by wheelchair to the ED.

Patient arrived to drop-in immunization clinic with mother. Patient was due for TDaP booster per his historical record. Immunization reviewed with mother, mother gave verbal consent. Immunization screening questions were reviewed, and no contraindications noted. 5 rights reviewed. TDaP vaccine administered per protocol in patient's right deltoid. Approximately 15 seconds after administration, patient postured backward rigidly while seated in his chair. He then slumped over to his right side, and was caught by me. Patient did not fall out of his chair, did not hit the floor, and did not hit his head. Patient was placed seated back in his chair and was A&O x4, but stated he felt "funny and dizzy," and stated he had positive LOC. Skin pale, cool, and clammy. VS taken immediately, all WNL except for BP which was low. Patient was placed onto exam table to lay down and VS were reassessed q5 minutes. Pt was given juice and crackers, and given O2 at 8LPM via face mask. BP did not normalize despite supine positioning, O2, and juice. Pt stated he felt "a little better" after juice and crackers, but still felt dizzy, and that his "head felt funny." Charge nurse was unavailable, but resource RN notified. Pt still A&O x4 but very slow to respond, and skin signs had not improved. Paramedics called, and patient was transported to medical center with mother's consent. All communication assisted with public health staff. Public health RN supervisor notified.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 9/3 went from dental office to pharmacy in the afternoon to fill prescriptions for amoxicillin and ibuprofen. Decided to get shots for flu and pneumonia while there. Went back to hotel and took the medications twice before going to bed. Slept well and woke up feeling good on 9/4.   Continued taking medications, but began to develop a fever in the evening which soon became very high (didn't have a thermometer).   The next day (9/5) the fever continued to run very high and my arm which was already sore at the spot of the injections (upper left arm) became much sorer and aches spread to my back and down my arm to elbow. Continued taking the amoxicillin until the end of day and then decided to discontinue.   Next day (9/6) the fever subsided and muscle soreness got steadily better. Large light red "bruise" color appeared visible on my inner left arm covering most of the biceps down to the elbow. As the fever subsided, I felt a general allergic response that felt like it was taxing my adrenals (as a lifelong asthmatic, allergy, eczema sufferer I know this feeling, except this felt stronger than normal and made me weak).   On 9/7, the skin on back of my hands and fingers became very thick and swollen (both hands). By the end of the day, small blisters were forming all over the swollen areas. They did not itch like eczema, though there was a slight burning sensation so I iced them down periodically and continued taking ibuprofen to control inflammation.  On 9/8, the blistered areas started to ooze liquid that has a distinct odor (almost smells like industrial oil or lubricant). The ares are starting to dry out a bit and the burning is getting more pronounced. I presume this is part of the healing process. I can still feel a bit of overall allergy response (that adrenal feeling) but less than before.  Finally, I want to add that I get the flu shot every year (for past two decades) and have received many other vaccines including previous ones for pneumonia, hepatitis, and pretty much everything else that was available. I have NEVER had a reaction before to any of them. Usually I barely even experience any soreness at the site of the injection let alone anywhere else.
OTHER_MEDS: None, but I had a dental implant placed in my jaw that day and was at the Pharmacy picking up prescriptions for amoxicillin and ibuprofen, which I started taking soon after the vaccinations.

Seen in office 9/2/20 - complaints of bilateral leg pain - "Patient is a 10-year-old girl here with father for evaluation of leg pain that has been going on for last couple of days . On Monday child went to park and did way more walking than she is used to. She started complaining of leg pain Monday night.  She had trouble bearing weight and walking on Tuesday morning.  She called the office and was advised to take ibuprofen for pain and if it does not get better they should call for further evaluation.  She comes today on crutches.  She was not able to bear weight.  She complains of bilateral leg pain from thighs to her ankles.  She has been drinking okay and her urine color is normal without any red tinges.  She is eating and drinking well.  Does not complain of belly pain or nausea or vomiting.  She is otherwise a healthy girl." - sent to ER for further work-up - diagnosed with Myalgia 1. Myalgia - "No specific identifiable etiology for bilateral leg pain on visit to the emergency department today.  All labs and x-rays normal.  Continue with increased oral hydration with clear, non-sugary fluids throughout the day.  Children's Motrin every 6-8 hours as needed for discomfort.  Rest while remaining active.  Follow-up with your PCP this week for continued symptoms.  Return the emergency department immediately for any worsening symptoms or additional concerns." -  Follow-up on 9/4/20 - "Patient is a 10-year-old girl with bilateral lower leg myalgia.  She has been evaluated extensively including creatinine kinase, CBC, S CRP, ESR, renal function test and x-ray of the hips.  All the labs have been normal.  Her pain is not getting any significant better.  But the pain is also not getting any worse.  I added prednisone 50 mg twice a day for 5 days in addition to ibuprofen.  I have advised her to take with food to prevent gastric irritation.  I also advised her to drink plenty of fluid.  Per parents concerns, we have reported vaccine adverse reaction form and send it to CDC.  She had gotten her HPV 11 days before." - Seen at orthopedics on 9/8/20 - "Knee pain, bilateral - I ordered and reviewed bilateral knee x-rays as well as reviewed the prior x-rays and labs, all which appeared normal.  I discussed with the mother she is likely having reactive arthritis that should improve in the coming weeks.  I recommended continuing NSAIDs, modifying activities to tolerance, resting, warm soaks, icing as needed, and have written a note keep around gym class for the next 3 weeks.  I will have her follow-up at that point to her monitor her progress.  I discussed the possibility of rheumatoid or other autoimmune disorder, but the general recommendation is against ordering labs for such issues at this point in the presentation of pediatric patients give most will improve without it and the labs will be negative."

SYMPTOM_TEXT: A couple days to about a week after receiving these vaccines, my son developed a cough and trouble breathing. I notified his doctor and we came in for a check-up. She said there wasn?t anything to be concerned about and to monitor the cough to make sure it didn?t last longer than a month and to come back if he had any fevers or other symptoms associated with it.   My son never developed any other symptoms besides this persistent cough. He coughs especially in the morning when he wakes up and it has been 3 months since the cough developed following the vaccinations. The cough is the same, with labored breathing, and no other symptoms.   We relocated to another area and my son was checked by another doctor, with whom I brought up my concern for this cough. She told me she would check his lungs but instead gave him a coronavirus test and sent us home. He does not, nor did he ever have coronavirus and his cough/labored breathing is still persistent.

One injection every 3 to 5 years; One injection every 3 to 5 years; "blacking out"; fell and hit his head/gash on head; perspiring profusely; he had flu-like symptoms; feeling lethargic; left arm was very sore after the injection; generally felt bad the entire day; feeling light-headed/ incredibly dizzy; began feeling light-headed and nauseous; This spontaneous report was received from a consumer concerning to himself as a 54-years-old male patient. The patient's medical history included quadruple bypass surgery. The patient concurrent conditions were unknown, drug allergies reported as none. Concomitant therapies included vitamins (unspecified), isosorbide, aspirin, metoprolol and atorvastatin.     On 05-SEP-2020 (also reported as on Saturday around 12:30pm), the patient was vaccinated with one injection of pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23), for prophylaxis (one injection every 3 to 5 years) (inappropriate schedule of product administration (+) circumstance or information capable of leading to a medication error) and with influenza virus vaccine (unspecified) (strengths, routes of administrations, formulations, lot numbers, and expiration dates were not reported) both in the left arm.   On 06-SEP-2020 at approximately 1:00 am on Sunday, the patient woke up and went to use the restroom and began feeling light-headed (dizziness) and nauseous; he was "blacking out" (loss of consciousness) and fell and hit his head (head injury). Subsequently, his wife came into the bathroom and helped him stand up and go back to bed. At approximately 2 and a half hours later, he woke up again and went to the restroom and the same thing happened again. However, when he began feeling light-headed (dizziness), he laid down on the floor, so he did not fall again.   He also reported that he was perspiring profusely (hyperhidrosis) and being incredibly dizzy (dizziness) for approximately 15 minutes. Moreover, he had flu-like symptoms including feeling "achy," having a low-grade fever, feeling tired (influenza like-illness) and lethargic and generally felt "bad the entire day" (feeling abnormal). Also, the patient's left arm was very sore after the injection (pain in extremity) (also reported as "soreness at site pain")  By Monday morning he felt better and by Monday evening (07-SEP-2020), he was fully recovered other than "gash on head" (head injury) which was a result of the fall. It was stated that the patient did not received any treatment and did not performed any laboratories or studies for the events. However, the patient saw his cardiologist.   The causal relationship between the events and the suspect vaccine was not provided.  Upon internal review, the event loss of consciousness was determined to be medically significant.

Anemic; Fever of 103�F perhaps higher because of the chills; Fever of 103�F perhaps higher because of the chills; High/Elevated lactic acid; The patient does not remember anything/Amnesica (she didn't remember getting the flu shot); Got confused; This spontaneous case was received on 01-Sep-2020 from a physician via agency (reference number SEQW-01120) and concerned a 66-year-old, female patient.  The patient's concurrent conditions included high blood pressure and diabetes. The patient had no known allergies. The patient's concomitant medications included metformin and lisinopril, both used for unreported indications. It was reported that patient got vaccinated with other vaccines in the past years and she had no adverse events.   On 31-Aug-2020, the patient was vaccinated with Flucelvax QIV (influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: deltoid) for flu prevention. The batch number reported was 10283849, expiry date: 30-Jun-2021.   On the same day, four hours after receiving Flucelvax QIV, the patient developed fever of 103 degrees Fahrenheit (F), perhaps higher because of the chills. The patient was advised to go to the emergency room (ER) for medical assistance. The patient got confused and amnesica (as reported) (she didn't remember getting the flu shot).   On 31-Aug-2020, the patient was admitted to the hospital. At the hospital she had been given intravenous (IV) fluids.   On the same date, a lab test revealed high/elevated lactic acid.    On 01-Sep-2020, the patient was found to be a little anemic. The patient was still confused and did not remember anything from yesterday.   At the time of initial reporting on 01-Sep-2020, the patient did not recover from the events and was still at the hospital.   The reporter assessed the events to be related to Flucelvax QIV. Physician stated that she did not feel Flucelvax Quadrivalent is safe and because of that she wanted to return the vaccines she had bought, after a serious adverse event on her patient following administration of the product.   The reported assessed the events as serious due to hospitalization.  Company comment: Blood lactic acid increased, amnesia, confusional state, anaemia, chills and pyrexia were associated with the use of the suspect product Flucelvax QIV for flu prevention. The events: chills, pyrexia, amnesia and confusional state occurred 4 hours after vaccination making chronology highly suggestive, while for remaining events was assessed as plausible, except for anaemia for which temporal association is unsuggestive. The patient's concurrent conditions included high blood pressure and diabetes while concomitant medications included metformin and lisinopril, both used for unreported indications. It was reported that patient got vaccinated with other vaccines in the past years and she had no adverse events. With information presented, causality is assessed as possibly related for pyrexia, unlikely related for chills since pyrexia was present. For amnesia, confusional state and blood lactic acid increased causality is assessed as unrelated due to reported diabetes. Uncontrolled diabetes may increase the risk of experiencing cognitive problems, such as memory loss. Higher than normal blood glucose levels can damage nerve cells, supportive glial cells, and blood vessels in both peripheral nerves of the body and the brain. Causality for anaemia is also assessed as unrelated due to unsuggestive temporal association and reported diabetes and concomitant drugs. Monitored client for 15 minutes after vaccination administration.  Client reported she was feeling well.  No adverse reactions noted.  She was released back to her job duties.  Client called front desk receptionist at approximately 11:15 AM.  She stated that she was feeling dizzy, weird, and not ?feeling right?  Front desk receptionist informed me of client?s status.  I went to assess client and she was laying back.  She stated that she felt like she was going to pass out.  I had her put her head in-between her legs with a cool rag behind her neck.  The overhead lights were turned off and the room dimmed.  She stated that she started to feel better but felt pressure in her head, her nose, and tingling in her ears.  She stated that she had breakfast but had not taken her blood pressure pills.  Wheat Thins and water given to her.  She tolerated it well.  At 11:25 her blood pressure was obtained and was 163/98.  She took her prescribed 20 mg Lisinopril and 1000mg of Tylenol.  Continued monitoring client and reassessed blood pressure at 11:40 AM and was 151/88.  Client ambulated with assistance back to clinic.  She was advised to lay down with lights off.  Client rested for approximately 35 minutes, ambulated to restroom and back to room.  Blood pressure reassessed and was 195/91.  Client education given on the risks for heart disease and other complications due to extremely high blood pressure.  Client was immediately referred to her PCP for follow-up. Client verbalized understanding and said she would have another employee follow her to her PCP. It was reiterated again the importance of going immediately, to ask for a cardiac referral because of extensive family history of heart disease. She was also advised to ask her PCP about her current blood pressure medication; however, she explained that her ?PCP had just recently changed her blood pressure medication about 2 weeks ago?. Client was able to ambulate back to her desk to pick up her belongings and left the building with another employee accompanying her. A follow-up phone call was made at 1502 and client stated that ?she went to her doctor, and they made a referral for a cardiologist, they gave me a shot to help lower my blood pressure and it helped?. She was asked about her blood pressure at her PCP, she stated ?the top number was 172, and after the shot was given the top number was 153. Client stated she was feeling better and was resting. A follow-up call will be made 9/11/2020 to check on her status.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After the nurse gave me the shot, my arm was immediately very sore. I told her this and she replied stating something along the lines of "yeah, that can happen with this one." As I drove home, it was difficult to keep my arm propped onto the steering wheel due to the pain, so I decided to just drive with my right hand. When I got home, I expressed my discomfort to my wife. I would rotate my arm in circles to try and circulate the blood and hopefully help the pain go away. It hurt very bad to lift my arm, especially above shoulder height. I was nervous because I was scheduled to work my warehouse job the next day and wasn't sure I would be able to complete my work properly. The next morning, my arm was still very sore but I decided to go to work anyway and thought moving it around more and using it would help. I limited my use of my left arm, but it was still very sore throughout the day. This pain lasted for about 5 days before it started to subside slightly. It would still be very painful to lift my arm over shoulder height. After another week, it got to the point where I could lift my arm over my shoulder without any initial sharp pain, but if I lifted it up or moved it around a certain way there would be a very uncomfortable deep tissue pinching type sensation, almost like my muscles were catching onto each other. This sensation has slowly faded, but I still have hints of it to this day.

Past vaccination included Fluzone High Dose (every year for the last 10 years).  Medical history, medical treatment and family history were not provided. On 01-Sep-2020 01:00, the patient developed a non-serious feeling moderate to severe myalgia (myalgia) 7 hours following the administration of INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE SUBVIRION VACCINE.  On 01-Sep-2020 01:00, the patient developed a non-serious sweating (hyperhidrosis), abdominal cramps (abdominal pain), gastrointestinal motility (gastrointestinal motility disorder), nausea, tired (fatigue) and presyncopy (presyncope) 10 hours following the administration of INFLUENZA USP TRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE SUBVIRION VACCINE. Patient accidentally received a fifth injection of Ipol after already completing the four dose series before/No AE; Initial information received on 04-Sep-2020 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case received from a nurse.  This case involves a 12 years old male patient who on 03-Sep-2020 accidentally received a fifth injection of IPV (VERO) [IPOL] after already completing the four dose series before (extra dose administered).  The patient's medical history, past medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided.  Concomitant medications included HPV VACCINE VLP RL1 4V (YEAST) (GARDASIL HP) and MENINGOCOCCAL VACCINE B (MENINGOCOCCAL VACCINE B) for Immunisation.  On an unknown date the patient received first, second, third and fourth dose of suspect IPV (VERO) (lot number and expiry date not reported) via unknown route at an unknown administration site and on 03-Sep-2020, the patient received a 0.5 mL fifth  dose of same vaccine (injection, lot R1B251M and expiry date 13-Mar-2021) via subcutaneous route in the right arm for prophylactic vaccination.  It was an actual medication error case due to extra dose administered.  Case details: It was reported by the nurse that a fill in data entry clerk accidentally pulled up the wrong brother's name (they had very similar names) and the vaccines that were scheduled were given to the wrong brother. Because of this, Ipol was inadvertently given to a 12 year old patient who already had completed the four Ipol injection series and this was an unnecessary dose. The patient did not experience any adverse events due to this.  At the time of reporting, patient did not experience any adverse event. Foetal exposure during pregnancy; Birth weight was 4196 g; This is a retrospective study case, received from other health professional on 04-Sep-2020, concerned a male neonate, whose mother was 24-year-old, pregnant, female subject of body weight: 133.5 lbs, height: 63.5 inches and body mass index (BMI): 23.3, enrolled in a prospective observational safety study.  The neonates' mother's medical history was not reported. The neonates' mother's concomitant medications included Prenatal vitamins (unspecified vitamins and minerals) for pregnancy and iron supplement as health supplement.  The neonates' mother had no obstetrical history. The neonates' mother did not have a history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM). The neonates' mother had no relevant maternal and paternal medical history with MCM.   The neonates' mother's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 13-Nov-2019. The type of pregnancy was singleton. The estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 20-Aug-2020 and the corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was 19-Aug-2020. The neonates' mother did not use tobacco, illicit drug or alcohol during pregnancy.  On 09-Mar-2020, at gestational age of 16 weeks (calculated per LMP), the subject was vaccinated with Afluria QIV (Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL) [influenza vaccine, dose, route of administration, anatomical location: not reported] (explicitly coded as 'Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for an influenza immunisation.  The batch number reported was P100126099.  On the same day, the neonates' mother underwent ultrasound scan and no MCM was noted.  On 23-Mar-2020, the neonates' mother underwent ultrasound scan and no MCM was noted.  On 21-Apr-2020, approximately one month after vaccination, the neonates' mother developed anemia.  At gestational age of 41 weeks (as reported), the mother vacuum-assisted vaginally delivered live birth, male neonate. The neonate's birth weight was 4196 grams, body length: 55.9 cm and head circumference: 36 cm. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) score was at one minute 7, at five minutes 9 and at ten minutes was not reported. No MCM was identified at birth.   The outcome of the event of �large for dates baby' was not reported.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.  The event of �large for dates baby' was considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus's Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  The case is linked to case 202003411 (the corresponding mother's case).  Company comment: The neonate's mother was administered the suspect product, Afluria QIV at approximately 16 weeks of gestation (explicitly coded as �Foetal exposure during pregnancy'). Reportedly, at 41 weeks of gestation, the subject vacuum-assisted vaginally delivered live birth, male neonate whose birth weight was 4196 grams (coded as large for dates baby). For the event large for dates baby, causal role of the suspect product is assessed as not related due to biological implausibility. Per some sources, the range of normal is between 2.5 and 4.5 kilograms. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I came into the ER on 7/3/2020 due to a cellulitis infection on my foot, as a complication of a bee sting from a week before that. I was given a pill and two shots--one in my hip, and a tetanus shot in my shoulder. The tetanus shot was not to treat the cellulitus; they asked me when I last had a tetanus shot and I didn't remember, so they (hastily) recommended that I get one.  The shot was administered into my left arm, high up near my shoulder. It pinched like any other vaccine, and immediately after was sore which was to be expected? but I also noticed I could not lift or extend my arm too far or at certain angles, because it felt weak and caused pain. My shoulder also hurt.  I expected the pain to disappear or at least lessen within the next few days, but it did not. A week later, it still hurt just as much and I had the same limited mobility, plus general weakness that affected my whole arm (especially while lifting/extending it) and in my fingers.  The new pain and mobility issues in my arm were interfering with daily tasks such as taking a shower (trying to scrub my back hurt), getting dressed, and working at my computer (typing). It got worse at night when I was trying to sleep, and I had pain or discomfort in most sleeping positions but it was worse if I slept on my left side. It also got worse when I moved it too much. Sometimes rest or exercise helped but sometimes it just made it worse.  I should mention that these symptoms are not normal for me, which I found concerning.  About 1.5 weeks after the vaccine, I started experiencing pain in my left hand. I also noticed that after waking up, my left hand would be numb and tingly. Ever since I developed these arm/shoulder symptoms, my left hand was very numb in comparison to my right upon waking up, especially when sleeping on my left side. Like when legs fall asleep, moving my hand around made the numbness go away after a few minutes.  I know that in most cases, pain from vaccines goes away after 2-3 days. So I did some research and my symptoms seem to match something called SIRVA, or Shoulder Injury Related to Vaccine Administration. Symptoms often include arm and shoulder pain, shoulder dysfunction, limited range of motion, tingling or loss of feeling, and weakness. If untreated it can cause issues like frozen shoulder or nerve injury. It?s typically caused by an incorrect method in giving a vaccine, for instance, by putting the needle in too high on the arm or too deep into the muscle.  The pain persisted for about 3 weeks, and gradually lessened. I still could not lift anything heavy, sleep on my left side, or extend my left arm in certain directions without a range of mild discomfort or pain... like when I reach to scratch my back or attempt to put on a tight shirt (getting my arms in requires specific movement). My mobility is still limited, but not quite as much as it was in the first week. My mobility is definitely more limited than it was before I got the vaccine.  I still have these symptoms currently (9/12/20), which have somewhat (but not entirely) lessened with treatment (steroid shot in my shoulder (9/01/2020). I have been seeking testing and treatment with a bone & joint doctor  who confirmed via X-Ray (7/21/2020) and MRI (8/27/20) that I have tendonitis in my shoulder. I started with the X-Rays and returned for an MRI when I saw no improvement in symptoms after following through with ice and exercises, and got the steroid shot during my follow up visit after the MRI.
LAB_DATA: X-Rays (7/21/2020) = Tendonitis of left rotator cuff (M75.82) MRI (8/27/2020) = Tendonitis of left rotator cuff (M75.82)

*The first time I filled out form & submitted it, it said error, so this is 2nd attempt.* I was not sure if I was supposed to report this here on VAERS, but to be safe I filed report. 15yo patient came with mother and brother to get flu shot. Mother received flu shot, then pt received flu shot. Pt seemed slightly nervous about receiving vaccine and seeing needle, but remained calm and was answering my questions during immunization. Temperature slightly warm at 98.9 but not feverish. Pt did fine during vaccine, which was received while sitting in chair, and I kneeled on floor to administer, to be eye level. Then pt switched chairs, while brother received shot. But instead of pt sitting down in other chair, he stood up on his feet behind me, out of my view, close to mother. 1-2 minutes later, while I gave flu shot to brother, pt fainted and hit head on the floor. Mother partially caught him. He was unconcious between 30 seconds to 1.5 minutes. Had pulse. Regained consiousness. Paramedics arrived. Besides being dazed, pt seemed ok. Blood sugar was low in 50's per mom/paramedic at that point. Drank some gatorade. Did not go to hospital. Paramedics walked him out to mother's car to go home. Followed up 3 hours later and patient still doing ok besides slight headache from fall. Did not have visible injury to head. Just slightly red on cheek. Mom said pt ate a little bit and doing well so far.
LAB_DATA: The paramedics measured certain things when they came, but I don't have official info. It seems all the stats were good other than blood sugar was low, quoted by mom to be in 50s at that time.

It?s been 10 years since I got a flu shot, and out of fear I got one 9/9/20.  Less than 24 hours later, as I was finishing an online yoga practice with a client, strange joint pain began (wrist, thoracic spine)  While I?m saying goodbye to my client, the chills begin along my arms. The  A/C was off which is usually the reason. BUT then the shaking and convulsions started. Within a matter of seconds, my entire body was uncontrollably shaking. It felt as if I was submerge in an ice bath ~ I was so cold, yet no fever. Temp was around 97 F. My words cannot describe how horrible this felt.  Had enough strength to go downstairs and get Hubby?s help. He got me in bed with a heating pad, my thermal blanket, hot massage rocks, and my night guard ~ I was chattering so violently, I thought I would break a few teeth.  Then the pain in my hips began. Felt similar to Labor pain, only 10x worse. I rolled to my side, along with the heating pad, and luckily that dissipated quickly.  Once the shaking stopped, I slept for a solid hour, yet woke to feel like I got run over by a truck. Was weak to rest of the evening and slept fairly well. The next day, Friday 9/11/20 I was sore, weak, and had what felt like a "flu headache" in my forehead area al day/night. Had a terrible night's sleep and woke up feeling as if I had a mild case of the flu. My temperature was 99.6 F most of day until bedtime, with chills, muscle joint ache, headache, fatigue, and no appetite.  I feel better today, although there is a lingering weakness, soreness, and faint headache.

I was one month away from birth. I was healthy with a healthy baby to be born on. On 08/06/19 I was given the Tdap shot.  One week later I began to notice bruises up and down my legs, arms and my pregnant belly. Over the next two weeks I was experiencing daily nose bleeds which I had never had before. I would go to sleep and then wake up with these sudden bruises that were not there the night before. After the two weeks of symptoms, I told my OB who ordered a CBC. I was admitted to the hospital right away with a platelet count of 12. I was diagnosed with ITP. Doctors ruled out HELLP, pre-eclampsia, or infections. I was given two platelet transfusions and four day course of Dexamethasone because my platelet count was critically low and unsafe to have my planned c section. Those treatments were able to get me to a count of 47. The ITP continued to worsen after birth with a count of 7. I began high does Prednisone 70mg with a taper over 5 months. I had four Rituximab chemo infusions. I had to stop breastfeeding which was crushing  and overwhelmingly sad due to the Rituximab. It wasn't safe for baby. I had about nine IVIG infusions. Nothing was working. IVIG would last about two weeks. This went on for several months. I continued to bruise on my arms and legs, and have petechia. I was fatigued. The numbers continued below 20 even after all theses treatments. I then had to have a splenectomy on 01/02/20 and remove a perfectly healthy organ. I lost hair. Gained almost 40 pounds on steroids, continuing to gain weight even after the baby.
LAB_DATA: Multiple CBCs, HIV testing, H. pylori testing with stool sample, CT chest, CT abdomen, chest x ray for blood clots,
OTHER_MEDS: iron supplement prescribed by doctor in June, however due to stomach discomfort it was discontinued

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 8/20 2:00 pm pain in right buttock, like a deep bruise; 8:30 pm noticed rash forming on right buttock 8/21 7:00 am rash grew in patches overnight on buttock and into crotch area, right side.  11:00 am called GYN due to area of rash, informed of rash.  GYN thought I might have had a bad reaction to Shingrix vaccine and prescribed Balacyclovir HCI 1 gm tab nort 2x/day for 5 days.  Began meds 5:30 pm after returning home from moving child into college dorm.  Noticed blisters formed throughout the day on right labia.  In pain throughout Saturday and went to Urgent Care Sunday ~3 pm. 8/23 doctor increased Valacyclovir  to 3x/day and prescribed Gabapentin 300 mg cap nort for pain/discomfort/itching and Asperacream topical for non-rash areas. ~8 pm received some relief from Gabapentin and mild relief from Asperacream.   8/24 Continued all meds as prescribed and increased Gabapentin to 2 doses then 3 for the next 2-3 days then back down to 2 does undtil 8/31 then 1 dose for 3 days then every other day and every 2 days until 9/9 for last dose. 9/3 saw my PCP for a follow up: still have rash, blisters seem to have gone away, right side of torso continues to hurt to touch, both front and back.  Advised to take advil. 9/13 still have some burning in crotch area on right side and rash has not gone away all of the way on right buttock.

inadequate response to the Pneumococcal vaccine; Literature Report.  This literature marketed report has been received from the authors of a published literature article and was presented for the long-term safety and efficacy of short-course immune tolerance induction (ITI) in a relatively large cohort of cross-reactive immunologic material (CRIM)-negative and CRIM-positive infantile Pompe disease (IPD) patients by evaluating anti-rhGAA IgG antibody titers, absolute neutrophil count (ANC), aspartate aminotransferase (AST), alanine aminotransferase (ALT), B cell and T cell quantitation, vaccination history and titers against vaccines, left ventricular mass index (LVMI), and overall and ventilator-free survival. Vaccine titers were available and adequate humoral response was observed in all except an inadequate response to the Pneumococcal vaccine in two CRIM-positive IPD patients which was as following.  This literature report refers to a male patient, who was currently 5.9-years-old (reported as 70.9 months). The patient's relevant medical history was not reported. Concurrent condition included CRIM-positive infantile Pompe disease. Concomittant therapies were not reported. On and unknown date, the patient had received a short-course of ITI with rituximab, methotrexate (dose, frequency, route, batch/lot# was not reported) in enzyme replacement therapy (ERT) for infantile Pompe disease and was subsequently vaccinated with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (manufacturer unknown) (dose, frequency, anatomical location, batch/lot# were unknown) for prophylaxis.  The patient received 1 round of immune tolerance induction. Cross-reactive immunologic material (CRIM) status on an unknown date was positive.  On an unknown date, the CRIM-positive IPD patient demonstrated an inadequate response to certain serotypes of the pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (manufacturer unknown) (reported as "pneumococcal vaccine") (therapeutic response decreased).  It was reported that the patient was vaccinated prior to enzyme replacement therapy. The patients B cell reconstitution, vaccination status at baseline and after ITI, and titers against routine vaccines were collected. On an unknown date, gene encoding acid alpha-glucosidase (GAA) disease-associated variants for allele 1 was c.2457_246delCTG and for allele 2 was c.2560C greater than T. Enzyme replacement therapy (ERT) dose at the time of initiation 20 milligram per kilogram (mg/kg) every other week (EOW). Patient was initiated on or subsequently received ERT at a higher dose than the recommended dose of 20 mg/kg EOW. B Cell recovery was found 13 weeks post rituximab (RTX). Weeks post-RTX at last CD19 percentage was 248 weeks. Anti-rhGAA IgG antibody titers at peak titers was 0, at last titers was 0 (171 weeks on ERT) and was immune tolerant. The patient's humoral response to routine vaccinations was reviewed and response to tetanus, measles, mumps, rubella was found adequate and response to Pneumoccocal strain was confirmed to be inadequate.   Efficacy of ERT and ITI: Left ventricular mass index (LVMI) baseline was at 186 and final assessment was 61 (81 weeks on ERT).  Motor Status was reviewed: Baseline revealed good muscle strength, tone. Minimal head lag, lifts head up and Final assessment revealed to be not ambulatory, does not move legs in supine, requires assistance for head control in supported sitting (274 weeks on ERT). Ventilation Status: Baseline revealed no support and final assessment was reported as invasively ventilated (27weeks on ERT).  Feeding Status: At Baseline via nasogastric tube (NG) and at final assessment with gastrostomy tube (G Tube) (274 weeks on ERT)  Action taken with the co-suspect therapies rituximab and methotrexate was unknown. The outcome of the event was unknown. The Author considered the event therapeutic response decreased to be related to the suspect therapy. It was also reported that it is not clear if the lack of response to polysaccharide vaccines in this patient was due to immunosuppression or normal variability in response to pneumococcal vaccines.  A copy of the published article is attached as further documentation of the patient's experience.  This is one of two reports received via same literature article.; Sender's Comments:  US-009507513-2009USA003961:

Efficacy of ERT and ITI: Left ventricular mass index (LVMI) baseline was at 194 and final assessment was 62 (70 weeks on ERT). Motor Status was reviewed: Baseline observations was reported as rolling supine to left, right, side lying and Final assessment was ambulatory (137 weeks on ERT). Ventilation Status: Baseline observations was reported as no support and final assessment was reported as no support (137 weeks on ERT).  Feeding Status: At Baseline was reported as oral and at final assessment was reported as orally (137 weeks on ERT)  Action taken with the co-suspect therapies rituximab and methotrexate was unknown. The outcome of the event was unknown. The Author considered the event to be related to the suspect therapies. It was also reported that it was not clear if the lack of response to polysaccharide vaccines in this patient was due to immunosuppression or normal variability in response to pneumococcal vaccines.  A copy of the published article is attached as further documentation of the patient's experience. Vaccine administered on 08/24/2020. Symptoms appeared on 09/10 with "acute onset massive onset trembling and chills." Wife called 911 at that time (due to low oxygenation via pulse oximeter). Fever of 101.2 F upon evaluation with EMTs. EMTs evaluated and offered transportation to local hospital. EMTs were okay with patient staying home at that time. Patient declined due to COVID-19 concerns. A few hours later, patient's fever up to 103.5. PCP was contacted; if patient's condition changed or worsened, patient was advised to go to urgent care or hospital. Patient declined. After a nap and observation for a few hours, patient's fever was down to around 101 without fever reducing medications. On 09/11 in the morning, no symptoms observed except fatigue. On 09/12 in the evening, fever went up to 101.8 and patient described flu-like symptoms. Went to hospital on 09/12 in evening. Patient was tested for COVID, had labs drawn, blood culture then discharged home. Approximately 24 hours later, hospital physician called and informed patient and wife that blood culture came back positive for gram negative rods. Physician elaborated with "probably E. coli." Patient was instructed to return to hospital for admission and IV antibiotics (unknown duration of treatment at this time). RN at hospital confirmed that E. coli was grown in blood culture.
OTHER_MEDS: Xarelto 20mg (once daily); metoprolol 100mg (1 tab BID); Losartan 50mg (1 tab PO BID); multi-vitamin (1 tab daily)

Today (tues) pain is mild and swelling has subsided a lot, still not back to normal.

I got my annual flu shot like I do every year. I did not have any previous illness, signs or symptoms previous to being injected. My arm was unusually swollen and tender at the injection site. About 3 hours after receiving the vaccine, I started getting severe dizziness, photosensitivity and my heart was beating  rapidly like I had just run 5 miles. The dizziness was relentless and I could barely stand up. I decided to lay in bed in hopes that the dizziness would subside. After about 8 hours the dizziness finally went away and my heart had calmed down. My eyes were still extremely sensitive to light for about 24 hours. I did not report this to my doctor because the dizziness went away and I didn't feel as though I needed to bug my doctor about it. I now understand that I should have reported it ASAP because it is important public health information.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This is actually an administration error. Typing up patient's flu shot on 9/15/20 i realized that I had given patient a egg free flu shot (flublok)(on 9/14/20 clinic) due to his discovered allergy to eggs at the clinic when i asked him even though his sheet stated he wasnt. Flublok was chosen to minimize his reaction to the flu shot due to his potential egg allergy. When entering in his RX on 9/15 I noticed that Flublok is only indicated for ages 18+. upon doing research, newer studies show that Flublok is actually just as safe and efficacious as fluarix in ages 7-17 so there was minimal need for concern. I spoke with patient's mom on 9/15/20 at 5:00 PM and explained the situation and asked how patient was doing. Both of her sons had gotten the flu shot that day and both were feeling a little under the weather but besides that they were fine. She was understanding of the situation and thanked me for explaining and telling her what i had discovered. I told her that I would let the provider know as well since the vaccine was technically off label for his age group still. I called Dr's office on 9/15/20 at 5:08 pm and spoke with his nurse and explained the entire situation again. The nurse was ok with what had happened and told me she would pass on the information to Dr as well so that he could be made aware and document this as well. I will make a dispensing error report and VAERS form tonight just to cover what happened and keep this documented. 9/15/20 at 5:19pm

The patient was given the second dose of the Shingrix vaccine but was initially injection only the adjuvant into the left arm, deltoid region. The batch number for Shingrix antigen (batch number H2HM2, expiry date 29th August 2021) and Adjuvant (batch number NE3TG, expiry date 10th August 2021) reported only for recovery dose (corrective action). The patient explained he used a subcutaneous diabetic syringe and needle to inject Shingrix into her right deltoid. She reported while he was injecting, he pinched the skin.  The patient was concerned he gave her a subcutaneous injection and was concerned about absorption and efficacy, which led to inappropriate route of vaccination. The reporter consented to follow up. Follow up received from consumer on 19th February 2019: There was no physician involved in vaccination with Shingrix. Consumer was a Registered nurse and she know a good injection when she seen it. And the reporter concern was whether the vaccine took. It was the second of the series and it was done in December at the pharmacy. The pharmacist who given the injection was not trained properly. She understand that this was an intramuscular injection but he used an insulin needle. He laid against my deltoid and pushed it in. Then, in the middle of the procedure, he pinched the skin. He was not very sure of himself and she think that's why he pinched the skin. Nevertheless, he did it all wrong. This was why the reporter concerned. Did she get enough of the vaccine if it was given in the fatty area of my deltoid? She did get a bad itch. She had almost no reaction the 1st time a different pharmacist. She had some edema that time. This time it caused redness and the itching continued for a number of weeks. This was my complaint. In addition, my question was did she get enough of my 2nd injection Also, who was training the pharmacists to give injections? (Hire me and the reporter would teach them the proper way to do an injection.) Within a week or two after immunization, I developed urethral spasms and urinary dribbling. This occurred for the next 8 weeks or so. I am a physician myself so I sought the evaluation from a urologist (Dr) who evaluated my condition. SYMPTOM_TEXT: My son is having redness and hot area to the touch on both thighs in the area given the vaccine. My son was evaluated by the pediatrician on September 15, 2020.

On August 20th my toes started going numb by the 22nd my entire foot was numb as well as my hands. I saw my primary care provider on the 24th where they diagnosed me with a pinched nerve giving me a 6-day dose of prednisone as well as an anti-inflammatory and prescribed PT which I did through Saturday Aug 29th when I became unable to barely walk on my own. I saw a spine Ortho on the 31st who immediately diagnosed it as being neurological and sent me straight to the emergency room where the attending ER doctor immediately suspected Gillian Barre syndrome. I was admitted. At that point I had numbness in my tongue and around my mouth.  The next day I was given a spinal tap to confirm GBS my protein level was over 400. A port was inserted into my neck and I started plasma pharesis that afternoon and it continued for 5 days. After completion of plasmapheresis I was discharged after being in the hospital for 6 days to outpatient PT. Since leaving the hospital on a walker I progressed to a cane and can now walk on my own short distances. I still have numbness and tingling in my feet and just a little in my hands.
burning, tingling of b/l UE and LE,  progressively worse and also occurred on other areas of his body, no weakness, no rash or numbness.
LAB_DATA: EMG, neurology evaluation, MRI of lumbar spine

Within those first few days of being sick, other symptoms arose and still experiencing:  Pain in arm with lump, arm goes completely numb if any pressure applied to it while in bed...can not even lean a little to my left side less alone sleep on left side. SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Sept 30, 2019, I received the flu injection by a temporary staff person, working at the clinic. Waited to be released for possible reaction.  Went home and within a couple hours upper arm became very painful, never had that much pain from previous flu injections) so placed ice on upper arm and took Tylenol.  By 5 pm I could not lift my arm and had extreme pain running down arm and into the fingers. When I took my shower later that evening I noticed the bandage was placed high up shoulder near joint. I found that very unusual. Took more pain reliever and another ice pack and went to bed. Continued ice and pain reliever throughout Sat, Oct. 1.  At 9:07 pm I contacted Dr., my  primary physician, via the messaging system and relayed what I was experiencing and my fear there was a possible injury to my shoulder.  His response: Having a bad reaction, which is not unusual. Ice and take Tylenol; pain should be gone within 3 days. See immune responses like this quite often.  Rest assure the shoulder joint is fine.  Sunday there was swelling and redness.  On Monday, Oct 5 I called the clinic and appointment was scheduled to see NP, as Dr. was on vacation.  Appointment was scheduled for Oct. 9 @ 2:20 pm.  NP and the staff manager, both examined the arm and stated injection was definitely given in or near the joint.  An ultrasound was scheduled for the next morning at the Medical Center, Results:  ultrasound was normal, no signs of fluid collection, no foreign body. Should resolve in a week.  Pain continued and I decided to get appointment with my Orthopedic Doctor. Appt:  Oct. 28, 2019.  X-ray was taken.  Diagnoses:  Inflammation of shoulder and Frozen Shoulder.  Referred to Physical Therapist for the Frozen shoulder.  Physical therapy began Oct. 29 with PT  (seven days).  Returned for follow-up visit with Dr. (Nov 11)  with continued pain.  Ordered MRI . MRI was done on Nov 21 and follow up visit on Nov 25 with Dr., diagnoses Torn Rotator Cuff.  Referred to Dr. specialist in shoulder problems at same clinic with appointment on Dec. 3, 2019.  Was given a cortisone injection, which helped some.  Pain continued to get worse again and Mar 3, 2020 another injection was given and surgery was recommended.  Then COVID 19 stopped all elective surgeries.  Another injection given on May 26 to help with pain until surgery could be done.  Finally, elective surgeries could be done and on July 2 saw Dr. again for pre-surgery visit and scheduled surgery for July 22, 2020.  July 14, 2020, Pre-Op Clearance Exam completed.  July 22, 2020 surgery was performed.  July 28 visit with PA for suture removal and PT instructions to be performed at home.  Aug 18 first post-op exam and continued At-home PT with additional instructions.  Next appointment set for Oct. 19, 2020 for evaluation of shoulder.
LAB_DATA: UltraSound, Medical Center, 10/10/19; Normal X-ray, Center, 10/28/19, Inflammation of Bursa MRI, Center, 11/21/19, Torn Rotator Cuff
OTHER_MEDS: Estradiol .5mg; Imipramine 25 mg; Fluticasone 50 mcg, Losartan Hydrochorothiazide 100 25 mg;  Omega 3 Fish Oil; Multivitamin, Women's One-A-Day; Probiotic 5 billion cell Cpsp

At 6:30 pm on the date of injection, I became cold with chills and shivering.  Soon after, I had intense muscular pain in my upper, middle, and lower back.  My spine and rib cage also hurt immensely.  I took 1000mg of Tylenol and my usual dose of 10mg oxycodone and went to bed.  My fever was about 100.4 and rose to 101.6 within a couple hours but never went higher.  At 8:00 am, I woke up with very little pain and no fever, but did have the dry heaves for about 10 minutes.  As the day went on, the symptoms pretty much disappeared and I was eating normally with no side effects from the day before.  Within one day, September 3, I had completely gone back to my regular schedule.

The reporter was guilt for allowing pediatrician to give the patient that shot. In 2014, the patient started having seizures. The event of seizures caused hospitalization. The reporter did not inform Merck at the time. The reporter stated that the patient was up to date on vaccines, including the meningitis shot. The reporter stated that human papillomavirus (HPV) was a sexually transmitted disease that could be detected and treated. Limiting sexual partners (what a novel idea!) and having regular physicals and living in a healthy way was so much more sensible than injecting this poison. The healthy young patient had his dreams of playing college sports and going away to college stepped on due to unexpected, vicious seizures was not how preventative medicine was supposed to work. The patient was strapped to electroencephalogram (EEG)s waiting to see if a seizure happens, paid over $1800 out of pocket with insurance just to drive him 2 blocks from the emergency room (ER) to the best epilepsy unit, paid $1000/month for a name brand medication that worked the best because insurance won't pay because "there was another anti-seizure medication, just use it". The reporter stated that the healthy, smart young man was a victim of hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9). The reporter wished that Merck would take that money and help some family that has also been damaged by hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9). Medical attention was sought. Treatment was given to the patient. The outcome of the event was unknown. The causality assessment was related.  Upon internal review, the event of seizure was determined to be medically significant.

-See attached chart notes for neuromuscular weakness & resultant intubation, hospitalization. 9/11/2020. Patient is a 78 y.o. female on whom I have been asked to consult for evaluation and treatment of probable GBS. She did yard work on 9/8/20 which made her tired. That afternoon she began noticing numbness and tingling of her fingers and toes. That evening she could not get off the toilet; she was too weak in the legs. She needed to use a medical alert device to get help. Normally she used a walker. She notified EMS, who transported her to the hospital. In the ED she was found to hypertensive (190s), O2 sats 87%, urine with possible infection, and CXR with possible pneumonia vs aspiration but normal procalcitonin. She has required bipap. Admitted 9/9/20. Yesterday she reported improved sensation in her limbs. On exam for hospitalist, she was areflexic and weak. She had LP, which showed Prot 75. Decision was last night to delay IVIG to see how she looks today. She reports numbness now rising up to her lower abdomen. She is still requiring bipap and has air hunger when it is turned off. Of note, she had a VZV vaccine on or about 9/1/20. 9/16/2020. Unfortunate 78-year-old lady with morbid obesity, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, recently vaccinated for varicella zoster virus who developed a rapidly progressive Guillain-Barre on 09/10. Currently intubated. She is status post a completed dose of IVIG. NIF remains low and she has no muscular function in her lower extremities. Neurology is recommending pain control for the neuropathy and no further therapies for the Galbraith. Time and physical therapy may allow for recovery. She will likely need a protracted vent wean. We will put her on 10/5 pressure support today. She also need protracted rehab but she is now bedbound until she potentially regains functional status. We will therefore try to have her placed in LTAC to assist with both the ventilator weaning and rehabilitation from yellow-gray syndrome. Regarding other active medical issues she is still slightly hypervolemic we will continue Lasix and Diamox. Regarding her A. fib this is well controlled with her current dose of diltiazem. She is on anticoagulation for this. Regarding her pneumonia she is completed a course of antibiotics. She is still has MRSA in his sputum culture. This may be colonized endotracheal tubes there is no convincing signs of bacterial pneumonia on chest x-ray imaging or clinical exam (no white count no fever etc.). We will continue to monitor and have low threshold to institute anti-MRSA coverage should she develop worsened respiratory failure but for now she is off antibiotics.

My left arm was very sore within an hour of the vaccinator.  Stiffness in my right knee began two days later on Sept. 10th in the evening.  The day of Sept. 11th I awoke with severe stiffness in both knees and my wrists and shoulders.  The stiffness and pain became so intense I needed assistance to get up after sitting.  Walking was reduced to short distances at a very slow pace.  The extreme stiffness and swelling progressed to my elbows, both hands (knuckles initially and then thumbs), and shoulders.  The knees proved to be most debilitating.  I visited my Primary Care physician on Monday afternoon and was prescribed Ibuprofen, 800mg tablets; previously I had been taking over the counter Tylenol and Ibuprofen.  I took these until Wednesday when I again contacted my Primary Care physician and requested steroids as the Ibuprofen wasn't having much effect.  I am presently on the third day of the Methylprednisolone 4mg DosPak 21s and am improving.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was sitting and was injected with the vaccine. Mother was in the room with her. Prior to the injection the mother was asked if the patient has had vaccines in the past and if there were any problems such as anaphylaxis, seizures, passing out etc. The mother stated that she got vaccines all the time at the pediatricians office with no issue. When the  injection was complete the band aid was placed and when I do this I feel for any bumps and observe the skin. She was normal, no rise in fever either. The patient said that was a "painless" vaccine and rotated with her mom where I gave her mom the vaccine as well. With the history of having received and no issues I sent the patients to check out to receive the prescription during which the patient seemed okay. Roughly 15-20 minutes went by and then I see the mom hurrying towards me with the patient running with her as well. I instruct them to reenter the room where the patient was sat down and the mother said the patient complained of feeling dizzy and hot then fell over in the isle. I observed patient for any signs of anaphylaxis, there was none. Then the patient started to gag so I gave her the trash can to throw up in which she did. Then I asked my technician to get me a blood pressure cuff and an soaked paper tower with an ice brick along with the thermometer because the patient was burning up.  After the patient threw up she quickly felt better and we continued to monitor. I checked her blood pressure and it was 88/66. The heat was dissipated and the patient said she no longer felt dizzy and could see. We monitored for a few minutes. At this point the scare seemed to have pass. I explained to the mother that what likely occurred is that she passed out which can occur post injections. After roughly 15 minutes the patient felt better and  the mother asked if they could walk around. I said yes just stay close to make sure she is okay. The patient had energy again and when she stood up and walked around felt fine. After a few more minutes the patient said she was okay again and the mother took her home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: POST VACCINATION SYNCOPE: Patient had 3:30pm appt.  Flu vaccination administered first, followed by Bexsero (both in right arm at request of child).  Child was sitting down during and after vaccines; RN saw that her eyes were not focusing well.  RN began to physically support patient's head and upper body as child began to experience an episode of syncope (<30 seconds total time).  About 5-10 seconds after she lost consciousness, she had some jerking/twitching of her arms/head and stiffening of her arms (10-15 seconds).  Shortly after that she began to regain consciousness, while still supported by RN and mother.  After episode passed, Mother continued to support child while RN retrieved cold packs to cool her down.  Upon return, child was standing; Mom was supporting her as she dry heaved twice into waste can (no vomit later seen in trash can).  Nurse helped patient sit down by waste can while cold packs were applied to her neck and upper chest.  Nurse offered apple juice and peanut butter crackers, which patient accepted.  No hx of syncope noted in chart or on health screening (an alert was added to chart).  Child continued to recover and was able to leave.  Instructed Mom to support her to the car.  Told child if she feels dizzy/woozy/sick to lie down and to stay hydrated.  Called Mother back same day at 5:47pm to see how child was doing.  Mother said she was doing fine.  Reminded her to keep child hydrated and call if she has questions/concerns.
HISTORY: None stated or noted in chart.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 8 to 9 hours after receiving the vaccination-at 8 pm or so- I began to notice that I was feeling more achy and sore all over.  I began to feel chilled and feverish.  I eventually went to bed around midnight, but found I could not sleep because I was so tender, sore and achy in every joint of my body.  My muscles were sore and I was chilled and shaking.  I began to notice a headache as well.  I ended up taking a Tylenol with 1/8 gr. coedine just to help me sleep, but it only helped calmed down the aches for a couple of hours then I reawakened with all symptoms continuing.  I did not rest much that night.  The next day, 9/18, I found I had absolutely no energy, no appetite and continued to be miserable with body aches, joint pains and a mild headache.  I was only able to drink hot tea the entire day and either sat around the couch or laid down in bed as I had no ability to concentrate to read, work on computer or even do dishes.  I did not have any issues with cough, stuffy nose or sore throat, nor difficulty breathing or rash.  I did note that my injection arm was sore and was noticeably inflamed with  redness and some swelling of an area the size of my hand.  I rested the entire day and only drank liquids.  I slept better on Fri. nite but I did take another dose of pain meds to help the aches.  On Sat. am, I awoke feeling  like a Mack truck hit me.  very tired, weak, achy and sore, but not as severe as on Fri.  I spent the day resting  and was able to eat a fried egg and toast besides tea.  I went to bed that evening and awoke on Sun. 9/ 18, feeling as if I had made it over the worse and was on the way to my normal health.  I am currently feeling much better as my energy and appetite is returning and the aches and painful joints and fever is no longer bothering me.
CUR_ILL: No other acute illness at time of vaccination
PRIOR_VAX: With first dose of Shingrix, I did develope a CASE of Shingles and this was also reported to this agency

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient reported itching around ankles about 5-7 hours after the vaccine was given. She had the expected symptoms of body aches and low grade fever. On 9/15/2020 (one day after vaccine) she developed a rash of both lower extremities which she described as "little blisters" and continued to have itching. She saw me in the urgent care on 9/18/2020 and she had a vesicular rash of bilateral upper and lower extremities with sparing of the face and trunk. She continued to have intense itching, but at the time of visit she had no other symptoms; no fever, sore throat, headache, myalgia, cough, shortness of breath, loss of taste/smell. She felt completely well aside from the itching of rash. She states that she had chicken pox/Varicella at age 32. The rash was vesicular, but there was no erythema of skin (the typical Varicella rash is described as a dew drop on a rose petal). I spoke with her today (9/20/2020) and the rash continues to be just on the arms and legs. She has a few more lesions, but no lesions of face or trunk. Still itching, but no fever. NO other symptoms.
LAB_DATA: She plans to follow up in 2 days. I will order HIV, RPR as well as varicella/zoster antibody tests. Her Primary Care Physician was unable to see her and getting appointments with PCP's has been a challenge during the COVID-19 pandemic.
CUR_ILL: No other illness at time of vaccine or one month prior.

On 09/08/2020 I attended an appointment in the Internal Medicine Department for a yearly physical. Per the recommendations I received an injection in my right deltoid of the PPSV23 (Pneumococcal Polysaccharide Vaccine). When I received the injection it hurt more than any other shot that I have ever had, It really made my arm jolt when I received it. Throughout the day my arm got increasingly weak and extremely painful. By the the end of the evening it was constant extreme sharp pain in my shoulder without even moving it. I slept one hour that night due to the pain. By the next morning I could not physically lift my arm up past waist level and the pain continued. Wednesday 9/9 I called the Dr. back and informed them of the issue, they scheduled me for an appointment for that Friday on 9/10 which I attended. At that time they told me to take ibuprofen (as I had been), and if it wasn't better to make another follow up appointment. My arm was re-gaining some strength very slowly but the pain has continued. Last week Thurs 9/17 I scheduled another appointment for follow up with Dr. due to the continued pain and weakness (I can now only lift my arm to chest level, no higher). He gave me a prescription cream for Diclofenac Sodium Topical Gel (which my cost was $26.90 ) The insert for this medication specifically states "It is not known if diclofenac sodium topical gel is safe and effective if used on your spine, hips, or shoulders." Why would I be prescribed a medication for this if this for my shoulder if this is how the insert reads? I was told to follow up again on Monday 9/21/2020 if not better. I am planning on doing this.

herpes zoster; This initial spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation, referring to a patient of unknown age and gender. No information was provided regarding medical history, concurrent conditions, or concomitant medications. On or about 31-OCT-2013, the patient was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for the long-term prevention of shingles and/or zoster-related conditions (strength, dose, route of administration, anatomical location, lot#, and expiration date were not reported). At the time of vaccination, the patient relied on the warning label affixed to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), and the information relayed through the patient's healthcare provider that zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) was effective in preventing shingles on a permanent basis and did not carry any significant risk of adverse effects, which induced the patient to be vaccinated. Alternatively, on or about 31-OCT-2013, the patient's healthcare providers included but not limited to a healthcare provider, relied on the warning label affixed to the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, believed that it was effective in preventing shingles on a long-term or permanent basis that it did not carry any significant risks of adverse effects. On an unknown date, reported as subsequent to the vaccination, the patient was treated for herpes zoster. As a direct and proximate result of the patient's use of the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, the patient had and would continue suffered ongoing injuries, including but not limited to: mental and physical pain and suffering; medical care and treatment for these injuries; significant medical and related expenses as a result of these injuries, including but not limited to medical losses and costs include care for hospitalization, physician care, monitoring, treatment, medications, and supplies; diminished capacity for the enjoyment of life; diminished quality of life; increased risk of premature death, aggravation of preexisting conditions and activation of latent conditions; and other losses and damages; and will continue to suffer such losses, and damages in the future. The outcome of herpes zoster was not recovered. The reporter considered herpes zoster to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).

herpes zoster, damage to her optic nerve; permanent loss of vision in right eye; This initial spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation, referring to a patient of unknown age and gender. No information was provided regarding medical history, concurrent conditions, or concomitant medications. On or about 14-SEP-2017, the patient was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster) (strength, dose, route of administration, anatomical location, lot#, and expiration date were not reported). On an unknown date, reported as after received zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, suffered from herpes zoster, damage to her optic nerve resulting in permanent loss of vision in her right eye (ophthalmic herpes zoster and blindness unilateral). As a result of these symptoms, patient was seen and treated by healthcare providers. As direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, patient had resulted in physical limitations did not present prior to used the vaccine. Patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of patient condition. Patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffered, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. Patient had suffered and incurred damages, included medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of ophthalmic herpes zoster and blindness unilateral was not recovered. The reporter considered ophthalmic herpes zoster and blindness unilateral to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).  Upon internal review, ophthalmic herpes zoster and blindness were determined to be medically significant events.

As a result of her receipt of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) , the pt has been caused to suffer severe personal injuries, pain, suffering, and emotional distress, as well as to incur substantial economic damages.
