The pt has lost past earnings and has suffered a loss of earning capacity. The pt  has suffered and would continue to suffer economic loss, and has otherwise been physically, emotionally and economically injured. The pt's injuries and damages ware permanent and would continue into the future. The pt sought actual and punitive damages from the Company as alleged herein. the pt demanded judgment against Company for compensatory, treble, and punitive damages, together with interest, costs of suit, attorneys' fees, and all such other relief as the Court deems proper. The outcome of the events was reported as not recovered. The causality was related.  The events of chicken pox and/or shingles were considered to be disabling.

Pregnancy in 2018 resulted in live birth.  Received Tdap shot during that pregnancy with no adverse reactions. For this  current pregnancy, due date is 11/11/2020.   On September 2, 2020, I received the Tdap Vaccine given at my 30 week prenatal visit. CMA administered vaccine. Discussed receiving the shot in the dominant arm as using the arm could help decrease discomfort/pain due to vaccine. Shot was given in upper right deltoid. I remember thinking the shot was administered high compared to any IM shots received before.  Within 2-3 hours, there was general soreness noted in upper extremity around injection site. Pain level 2-3 out of 10.  By the evening, the pain had increased significantly with pain radiating deep within shoulder. I remember describing the pain to my family as though my shoulder was ?out of socket?. Couldn?t lean/sleep on right side that night or perform many activities of daily living due to pain when reaching across my body. Pain 6-7 out of 10.  By the next day,  the pain continued to increase.  Pain radiated in upper shoulder/deltoid area. Continued to be unable to sleep on my right side (making it extremely difficult to sleep at all as pregnancy makes me unable to sleep on back or stomach), take off my bra, reach overhead, wrap towel around myself, put my daughter in her car seat. At rest, pain averaged 6-7 out of 10. When moving arm, especially at end range, pain was 8 out of 10. Continued to wait it out as I was told pain/discomfort could last for a couple days.  On 9/8 I reached out to Dr. as the pain had continued and felt "wrong." Doctor recommended scheduling with primary care doctor or going to urgent care as the pain should have been decreasing by that time.  Also prescribed Tylenol. Scheduled appointment with primary care physician on 9/15 and began taking Tylenol for pain management with very little change in pain levels. Warm showers would provide temporary relief. Discontinued Tylenol due to little to no change in pain levels. Night time was the worst as the pain made it difficult to sleep because of pain/ache/burning sensation in affected right shoulder. And I feel uncomfortable taking medication during pregnancy when it isn?t making a difference. Over the next few days, pain began to subside and I was able to complete self-care tasks independently again, but still with pain. Though continued to have difficulty picking up my toddler and sleeping. Pain 2 out of 10. 5 out of 10 if slept on. Would wake myself up at night from pain of lying on right arm.  09/11/2020 was a ROUGH night. Could not get rid of ache, keeping me up a majority of the night.   On 09/15/2020, I went to see primary physician. Physician states she believes pain is due to poor administration of vaccine, placement ?too high?. And has resulted in acute myofascial pain (per physician note). During appointment, doctor reports that her diagnosis is inflammation secondary to incorrect placement of injection which is causing impingement of nerve, explaining the pain experienced at end range of certain movements. Physician performed basic ROM with me, abduction/adduction and external/internal rotation. Only applied weight/pressure on front ROM. Did not perform any functional assessments. I verbalized pain at end ranges of external rotation and overhead movements. Physician reports that she expects the issue to resolve within weeks/a month or so. Advised ice and Tylenol for pain management. When I asked about testing/radiology of any kind, she had no recommendations at this time. Physician states that ultrasound would not show any symptoms. Doctor advises to continue to keep her and my OB doctors in loop if pain continues.  By 09/16/2020, pain was back to 2 out of 10.  On 09/17/2020 had 32 week prenatal visit with Dr. Discussed pain since receiving tdap shot at 30 week visit. Doctor extremely apologetic but also unable to recommend any other forms of medication for pain relief at this time due to pregnant state. Advised to continue to follow up at subsequent appointments if pain continues. Another night of aching throughout the right arm. The following morning, pain radiated into forearm and towards wrist. General aching 2/3 out of 10. Consistent ache/tension in shoulder throughout day. On 09/18/2020, I dropped a bottle of creamer, which busted on the floor, when right arm ?caught? and sharp pain surprised me. At rest, arm continues to feel heavy and as though it has been overused, even though I have been using it less. As of 09/20/2020, there?s a constant ache in my shoulder during the day ? continues to keep me awake at night.  As of today, 9/22, ache/pain in arm continues. Can perform more activities of daily living as compared to those first few days following the shot but cannot complete without pain.
LAB_DATA: None requested by physician. Reports that ultrasound would not show anything. No other tests/radiology recommended.
OTHER_MEDS: prenatal vitamin, stool softener, magnesium, low dose aspirin (81 mg), probiotic

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Foetal exposure during pregnancy; Low birth weight of 2160 g; This observational study case was received on 14-Sep-2020 from other health professional and concerned a female neonate subject. The neonate's mother was 28-year-old, female pregnant subject, of body weight 117.5 lbs, height 62 inches and body mass index (BMI) 21.5 enrolled in, a prospective observational safety study.  The neonate's mother's current medical conditions included dichorionic diatomic twin pregnancy. The neonate's mother's concomitant medications included Prenatal (unspecified vitamins and minerals) for pregnancy.  The neonate's mother had no previous pregnancies. The neonate's mother had no maternal or paternal history with major congenital malformations (MCMs) and had no history of offspring with MCM. The neonate's mother did not use tobacco or alcohol during pregnancy.  The neonate's mother's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 22-Dec-2019. The mother's estimated date of delivery (EDD) and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) were reported as 27-Sep-2020. The type of pregnancy was multiple, twin pregnancy.  On 18-Feb-2020, at approximately 8 weeks of gestation (calculated per LMP), the neonate's mother was vaccinated with Afluria QIV (Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV) [Influenza vaccine; dose, route of administration, anatomical location: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for an influenza immunisation. The batch number reported was P100126099.  On the same day, the ultrasound revealed no MCM and dichorionic diatomic twin pregnancy was confirmed.  On 18-Mar-2020, 14-Apr-2020, 06-May-2020, 03-Jun-2020 and 01-Jul-2020, the ultrasound revealed no MCM.  at gestational age of 37 weeks (as reported), mother vaginally delivered two live birth female neonates. The characteristics of the first neonate included birth weight: 2160 grams, body length: 45.7 cm and head circumference: 31.5 cm. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) scores at one minute was 8, at five minutes was 9 and at 10 minutes no data was provided. No MCM was identified at birth.   The outcome of the event 'low birth weight baby' was not reported.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment to Afluria QIV.  The event of 'low birth weight baby' was considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus's Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  This case is linked to case number 202004473 (corresponding mother case) and 202004475 (corresponding twin case).  Company comment: The neonate's mother was vaccinated with the suspect product, Afluria QIV (explicitly coded as �Foetal exposure during pregnancy'). Reportedly, six months and 19 days after vaccination, the mother vaginally delivered two female neonates. The one neonate's birth weight was low (2160 g). Chronology is unsuggestive. Causality was highly confounded by twin pregnancy. No information regarding neonate's mother medical history was provided. Considering all the above mentioned, causal relationship between the suspect product and the event of low birth weight baby is assessed as not related. Foetal exposure during pregnancy is not related per company's conventions.; Sender's Comments: The neonate's mother was vaccinated with the suspect product, Afluria QIV (explicitly coded as �Foetal exposure during pregnancy'). The neonate's mother's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 22-Dec-2019, estimated date of delivery (EDD) and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) were both reported as 27-Sep-2020. The type of pregnancy was multiple (twin pregnancy). The neonates' mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  On 18-Feb-2020, at gestational age of eight weeks (calculated per LMP), the neonate's mother was vaccinated with Afluria QIV (Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV) [Influenza vaccine; dose, route of administration, anatomical location: not reported] (explicitly coded as �Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunization. The batch number was P100126099.  On the same day, the ultrasound revealed that there were no MCM and confirmed dichorionic diatomic twin pregnancy.  On 18-Mar-2020, 14-Apr-2020, 06-May-2020, 03-Jun-2020 and 01-Jul-2020, the ultrasound revealed that there were no MCM.  at gestational age of 37 weeks (as reported), the mother vaginally delivered two female neonates. The neonate's birth weight was 2220 g, body length was 47 cm and head circumference was 32 cm. APGAR (appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration) score at one minute was 8, at five minutes was 9 and no data were reported at 10 minutes. No pregnancy complications were noted. No MCM was identified at birth.  The outcome of the event 'low birth weight baby' was not reported.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment to Afluria QIV.  The event of 'low birth weight baby' was considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus's Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  This case is linked to cases 202004473 (corresponding mother case) and 202004474 (corresponding twin case). I know it is a relatively new vaccine and I saw from a literature review that heart arrhythmias were ntoed as unsolicited events by patients when the vaccine was being tested, but apparently no follow up was done. If it had not felt better I would have called the doctor today 04/27/2020. Since the pharmacist had warned me of possible side effects, I waited to see if it would pass, which it did. Later in the afternoon on 04/25/2020 after receiving the vaccine, I became very tired and whole body ached, I slept quite a bit in the afternoon. My arm was super sore which I expected, but is still pretty sore today as of 04/27/2020. I did move my arm around as instructed, but that is not really a concern, I also on 04/25/2020 experienced tightness in chest and coughing. By 04/26/2020, the tightness in chest, coughing and body aches were worse. I ran a slight fever of 99.8 degrees, usually my temperature is 97.6 to 98. I ended up wearing a mask, it seemed to help with the coughing. I took some Tylenol and Niquil cough medicine and I was able to sleep several hours in the afternoon and then a good 8 hours that night. The next morning the symptoms subsided with just a minor cough left. Note also, this was my second dose, I did not have these side effects on the first dose, I remember my arm was sore a few days and I may have slept a bit. The pharmacist did say that the second dose would be more full and I may experience more side effects. This is not a complaint, I just merely wanted to pass on what I experienced so it may be helpful to others.

Extreme pain as shot was given, swelling, extremely hot and extreme itching even though I took antihistamines starting 24 hours before injection to mitigate reaction. Very uncomfortable to sleep that night due to the pain and swelling, headache, shivering (very chilled) and irregular heartbeat. . The next morning I was in more pain in my arm the hive was 3" wide, 5" long and 3/4-1" high, I continued to take antihistamines, applied topical antihistamine and numbing ointments. Applied ice. By the afternoon I had a small hive on my face and 3 inside my mouth along with numbness, I had to immediately evacuate my bowels. Fever of 99.2. Very tired, I started needing naps and could hardly make myself get up from the nap. On the 26th I had extreme pain in my left little finger and could not use it. Ibuprofen did not help much. I did not have joint pain on this finger or hand before the injection It is now 7 days after the injection and I am still very tired. The injection site is still red, but not as swollen or itching. I am still fatigued and finger joint still hurts. Up until the injection I felt terrific and had plenty of energy, did not need daily naps, nor did I have hives or any other health issues.I have not been ill. This has been awful. It is not quite noon and I need to go lay down.

New packaging for GSK vaccines is very similar. I am specifically reporting the similarities between the hepatitis B vaccine (Engerix-B NDC 58160-8200-52) and tdap (Boostrix NDC 58160-842-52). The packaging is nearly identical with a slight variation in the shade of green used. Both medications require refrigeration. We have had to remove Tdap from the automated dispensing cabinet in out obstetric unit due the similar packaging and concern over a newborn being given tdap instead of the hepB vaccine.

Was given Tdap vaccine, right arm. Age 60. Within hours was experiencing high fever 103.4. Muscle, joint pain, despair. Couldn't work for the next two days. Continued high fever. Reached out to my doctors and was told to take Tylenol which I had been and that this is not a common side effects for adults. I've suffered horribly these past few days. My right arm is useless. And I've lost over 2 thousand dollars in wages. I'm qoories that I don't know what else could be in store for me on the future. This vaccine is the newly released latex free version of the TdAP by Sanofi.

At around 4PM PST, Monday, July 20th, I received my second vaccine dose of Shingrix 50MCG at a Pharmacy. I had received my first dose on 01/29/20. With my first dose I had no memorable reaction. With this second dose I had a significant reaction, though not life-threatening. After dinner, I had very bad pain, redness, and swelling at the injection site. It was also very hot to the touch. It was so bad, I could barely lift my harm, if my husband just lightly put his finger on the site, it was very painful. (I have very high pain threshold. I did not use any pain medication with both my natural childbirths.) That night I was not feeling well. Kind of nauseous, fevery, a heavy-feeling everywhere. My arm hurt and I took 2 Aleve tablets. I went up to bed around 10 pm and fell asleep with a mild headache. As the hours passed the mild headache turned into a bad headache and throughout the night I had very fitful sleep. Around 6AM on Tuesday, I asked that my husband bring me 2 Excedrin Migraine tablets. I then slept until around 6PM. When I got up, my whole body ached. I went back to be after eating dinner. I took Aleve again. I slept until Wednesday morning though intermittently awoke because of the arm pain. On Wednesday morning, I felt a lot better but was exhausted. Slept on and off the entire day. On Thursday (today) I woke up feeling pretty normal (except for the sore arm at the injection site) and expected to be able to get on with the day. But again, I was very exhausted and was not very productive. Tonight, the injection site still hurts and is warm to the touch. Please feel free to call if you have any additional questions.
OTHER_MEDS: 20grams Nexium, once a day, for acid-reflux, 187mgs Effexor for depression, 40mg Raloxofine, once a day, for protection from breast cancer recurrence.  Centrex Silver vitamins

At the time of reporting, the patient had not recovered from pain in extremity and myalgia and the causal relationship between pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) and the events was unknown.

shingles; Information has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation, concerning a female patient (pt) of unknown age. The pt's medical history, concurrent conditions and concomitant medications were not reported.   In or around 21-OCT-2017, the pt was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose of preventing shingles (herpes zoster) (dose, route of administration, anatomical location, lot number and expiration date were not reported).   On an unspecified date (reported as "shortly after receiving the vaccine"), the pt suffered a bad case of shingles. It was reported that as a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt's symptoms resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the product. The pt also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition and sustained severe, serious, progressive and permanent personal and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury.   By the time of reporting, the patient was considered to be not recovered from the event. Moreover, the event was considered to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).   Upon internal review, the reported event was considered to be disabling.

bad reaction; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of adverse reaction in a female patient who received Flu unspecified (Flu vaccine) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received Flu vaccine. On an unknown date, unknown after receiving Flu vaccine, the patient experienced adverse reaction (serious criteria hospitalization). On an unknown date, the outcome of the adverse reaction was unknown.   The reporter considered the adverse reaction to be related to Flu vaccine.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of bad reaction, in a female patient of unspecified age, who was vaccinated with unspecified flu vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. This case corresponds to Participant reported in this literature article. The patient was a part of study that aimed to understand how the vaccine decision-making process differed between parents with a child diagnosed with autism and parents with a child that did not have autism. Interviews were conducted in September-December 2018 with 24 racially and demographically diverse parents of children at two clinics serving patients, one of which only serves families of children with autism. [In this study, 24 parent participants were interviewed. The majority were female (92%), and aged 40-49 years (46%). Fourteen parent participants had children with autism interviewed (ASD), and the remaining ten had neurotypical children]. The patient was at least at least 18 years of age and currently had a child who had ASD. No information on patient medical or family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was reported. On an unspecified date, the patient had unspecified Flu vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age at vaccination was not reported.  On an unknown date, an unspecified time after vaccination, the patient had really bad experience with the flu vaccine to the point where the patient was hospitalized for a week after one time. The patient reported to have a really bad reaction. After that, patient had never given her child a flu vaccine, neither one of them. The case was considered as serious due to hospitalization. Treatment was unknown. Outcome was not provided. The authors stated "From our results, parents of a child with autism were more likely to consider the idea that vaccines were linked to autism in their decision-making process, and were less likely to be influenced by personalized recommendations from the child's health care provider. In our study, we found that concerns about vaccines, the parent provider relationship, and risk perception were most salient".

Cytomegalovirus viremia; Fever; Chills; Night sweat; Lethargy; Headache; Myalgia; Nausea; Anorexia; left-sided pleuritic chest pain; multiple episodes of watery, non-bloody diarrhea; contracted gallbladder; mild surrounding inflammatory changes (suggestive of colitis).; Leukopenia; Thrombocytopenia; liver function abnormality; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of cytomegalovirus viremia in a 50-year-old female patient who received Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2017-2018 season) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included hypertension, polycystic kidney, autosomal dominant, end stage renal disease ((on hemodialysis) underwent a renal transplant (initial transplant) from a living unrelated donor in June 2016), inflammatory reaction ((allograft rejection, infection) included donor-specific antibody mediated rejection), apheresis (for inflammatory disease) and epstein-barr virus infection. Previously administered products included anti-thymocyte globulin, methylprednisolone, IVIG and rituximab. Concurrent medical conditions included polycystic liver disease and polycystic kidney. Concomitant products included sulfamethoxazole + trimethoprim (Sulfamethoxazole-Trimethoprim).   In November 2017, the patient received Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2017-2018 season. On an unknown date, 8 days after receiving Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2017-2018 season, the patient experienced cytomegalovirus viremia (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), fever (serious criteria hospitalization), chills (serious criteria hospitalization), night sweat (serious criteria hospitalization), lethargy (serious criteria hospitalization), headache (serious criteria hospitalization), myalgia (serious criteria hospitalization), nausea (serious criteria hospitalization), anorexia (serious criteria hospitalization), pleuritic pain (serious criteria hospitalization), diarrhea (serious criteria hospitalization), gallbladder disorder (serious criteria hospitalization), colitis (serious criteria hospitalization), leukopenia (serious criteria GSK medically significant), thrombocytopenia (serious criteria GSK medically significant) and hepatic function abnormal. The patient was treated with prednisone, mycophenolate mofetil and tacrolimus. On an unknown date, the outcome of the cytomegalovirus viremia was recovered/resolved and the outcome of the fever, chills, night sweat, lethargy, headache, myalgia, nausea, anorexia, pleuritic pain, diarrhea, gallbladder disorder, colitis, leukopenia, thrombocytopenia and hepatic function abnormal were unknown.   The reporter considered the cytomegalovirus viremia, fever, chills, night sweat, lethargy, headache, myalgia, nausea, anorexia, pleuritic pain, diarrhea, gallbladder disorder, colitis, leukopenia, thrombocytopenia and hepatic function abnormal to be related to Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2017-2018 season.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of cytomegalovirus viremia in a 50-years old female patient, who was vaccinated with unspecified influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. This case corresponds to first patient reported in this literature article. The patient had past medical history of hypertension, autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease and end-stage renal disease (on hemodialysis) underwent a renal transplant (initial transplant) from a living unrelated donor in June 2016. The Donor CMV status was CMV seropositive and the recipient CMV status was CMV seronegative. Induction immunosuppressive regimen included anti-thymocyte globulin, methylprednisolone and intravenous immune-globulin (IVIG). Recent inflammatory disease processes (allograft rejection, infection) included donor-specific antibody mediated rejection. The patient had an episode of antibody-mediated rejection. Time period between transplant and inflammatory disease process was 4 months. Treatments for inflammatory disease processes included IVIG, rituximab and apheresis. Duration of inflammatory disease process was 1 month. The patient had no prior episodes of CMV reactivation. Primary/secondary CMV prophylaxis included off CMV prophylaxis at the time of disease presentation. The patient had no recent increase in maintenance immunosuppressive regimen. Time period between transplant and presentation was 17 months. No information on patient's family history was provided. On an unspecified date in November 2017, the patient received unspecified influenza vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided) at the outpatient transplant nephrology clinic. The age of vaccination was not provided. On an unspecified date, 8 days after the vaccination, the patient presented to next appointment with complaints of fever with chills, night sweats, lethargy, headaches, myalgias, nausea, anorexia, left-sided pleuritic chest pain and multiple episodes of watery, non-bloody diarrhea. The patient was directed to the emergency department for further evaluation. Prophylactic medications at the time of presentation included sulfamethoxazole-trimethoprim (SMX-TMP) single-strength (SS) 1-tablet oral (PO) every twenty-four hours (QD). The patient denied sick contacts, recent travel, medication changes or medication non-compliance. At the time of admission, the patient was on prednisone 5 mg PO (oral) QD, mycophenolate mofetil (MMF) 360 mg PO QID, tacrolimus 0.5 mg PO BID. The patient's vitals on admission were significant for temperature 101.7 F, heart rate 100/minute, blood pressure 118/79 mm Hg, respirations 18/minute and oxygen saturation 98% on room air. Physical exam revealed no acute abnormalities. Admission labs were significant for white blood cell (WBC) 2,070/cubic mm [normal range (N): 3,800-10,500/cubic mm], absolute neutrophil count (ANC) 1,865/cubic mm [N: 1,800-7,400/cubic mm], lymphocyte count 500/cubic mm [N: 1,000-3,300/cubic mm], platelets 108,000/cubic mm [N: 150,000-400,00/cubic mm], aspartate transaminase (AST) 81 U/l [N: 10-40 U/l], alanine transaminase (ALT) 87 U/l [N: 10-45 U/l], alkaline phosphatase (ALP) 137 U/l [N: 40-120 U/l] and normal renal function. Electrocardiogram revealed sinus rhythm with no acute changes. Chest radiography and computed tomography (CT) ruled out the presence of pneumonia. Abdominal ultrasound showed polycystic liver and kidneys, contracted gallbladder with negative sonographic Murphy's sign. Computed tomography (CT) of the abdomen and pelvis confirmed polycystic liver and kidneys, as well as mural thickening of ascending colon with mild surrounding inflammatory changes (suggestive of colitis). Urinalysis was not suggestive of infection. Respiratory viral panel multiplex test was negative. Clostridium difficile toxin test was negative. Stool cultures were negative. Stool microscopy was negative for ova and parasites. Urine cultures revealed Escherichia coli (10,000-49,000 CFU/ml) combined with normal urogenital flora. Blood cultures revealed no growth. Testing for acute hepatitis A, B and C viruses was negative. Epstein-Barr virus serology revealed prior infection. BK virus DNA, Parvovirus B19 DNA and adenovirus DNA were not detected by specific polymerase chain reaction (PCR) tests. Infectious diseases service was consulted. Given the presence of leukopenia, thrombocytopenia, transaminitis and multi-systemic symptoms, there was concern for an ongoing viral process. The patient was started on valganciclovir 900 mg PO BID for presumed CMV disease, with intravenous fluid support. The E. coli in the urine was thought to be a colonization and the patient was successfully monitored off antibiotics. The patient continued to have persistent fevers and diarrhea, with worsening leukopenia (lowest WBC count 1700/cubic mm with lowest ANC 800/cubic mm), thrombocytopenia (nadir 86,000/cubic mm) and liver function abnormalities (AST 139 U/l, ALT 135 U/l, ALP 167 U/l). Given the persistent symptoms and worsening laboratory parameters, MMF was discontinued. Serum CMV PCR testing revealed 154,697 IU/ml (5.19 log10 IU/ml) [lower limit of assay detection 60 IU/ml (1.78 log10 IU/ml)]. Gastroenterology service was consulted for worsening liver function abnormalities and it was attributed the clinical picture to systemic CMV infection. The patient had clinical improvement, with improving CMV PCR tests [504 IU/ml (2.70 log10 IU/ml)] after 12 days of antiviral therapy. The patient was discharged on the twelfth day of hospital stay, with recovery of WBC count to 5,600/cubic mm and platelets 147,000/cubic mm. The patient was followed up by in the outpatient transplant nephrology and infectious diseases clinics. CMV PCR was negative 60 days after initiation of antiviral therapy and the patient was restarted on a lower dose of MMF. After the second negative CMV PCR a week later, MMF dose was increased and valganciclovir was decreased to prophylactic dosing. The patient received valganciclovir for a total of 87 days. The outcome was control of CMV viremia and recovery of cell counts. Graft outcome was stable allograft function. This case has been considered as serious due to hospitalization.  The author commented, "There are multiple risk factors linked to CMV viremia and disease in solid organ transplant recipients (SOTRs) and after hematopoietic stem cell transplant. These include older age, female sex, blood group A, decreased creatinine clearance, allograft impairment, CMV serostatus prior to transplant (donor seropositive-recipient seronegative OR recipient seropositive), transplantation type, use of T-cell depleted stem cell grafts, use of anti-thymocyte globulin before transplant, and occurrence of graft-versus-host disease (GvHD). Vaccination has not been previously reported as a risk factor for CMV viremia. There is a paucity of data on the effects of influenza vaccination leading to viremia in solid organ transplant recipients. Thus, we reviewed the data available in human immunodeficiency virus (HIV)-infected patients, another subset of immunocompromised patients. The research on the effect of influenza virus on HIV replication has produced conflicting results. Some studies have shown that influenza vaccination results in increased HIV replication (and subsequently increased viremia) in patients with uncontrolled or partially controlled viral replication. Other studies have shown that vaccination did not result in increased HIV replication. In some transplant recipients, influenza-like illness has been reported after vaccination. SOTRs are maintained in a state of prolonged immunosuppression after transplant. Thus, there is a possibility that influenza vaccination may lead to transient increase in CMV viral load and subsequent viremia (similar to the transient viremia seen in HIV patients). Both patients had a temporal association of onset of CMV viremia with administration of the influenza vaccine. They were older females at high risk of CMV reactivation (donor CMV seropositive/recipient CMV seronegative). Second Patient was on CMV prophylaxis, while second patient was not receiving valganciclovir (per our institutional protocol of CMV prophylaxis until six months post-transplant). They reported compliance with their home medications, with no recent increases in their maintenance immunosuppression. First Patient had an episode of antibody-mediated rejection, while second patient had an upper respiratory bacterial infection in the preceding months - these resolved completely with appropriate therapy. They had no concurrent inflammatory disease processes at the time of vaccination. Lab testing demonstrated high CMV DNA levels with concomitant leukopenia, neutropenia and lymphopenia. There were no additional factors identified to have contributed to CMV viremia. The CMV viremia was severe enough to warrant therapeutic antiviral therapy and changes in their immunosuppression regimen. We thus believe that CMV viremia resulted from the prior vaccination in our patients. One meta-analysis concluded that the influenza vaccine was associated with statistically significant protection against influenza-like illness in immunocompromised patients, including SOTRs. Through this case report, we wish to highlight the finding of CMV viremia occurring after influenza vaccination, with no other identified triggers. Further research and accumulation of cases is needed to investigate the strength of this association, to determine the mechanisms that resulted in CMV viremia and to recognize the risk factors leading to progression from viremia to clinically relevant CMV disease." The author concluded, "Vaccination may lead to transient viral replication in immunocompromised patients, such as HIV-infected patients (likely due to genetic and immune-mediated mechanisms). Similarly, we believe that influenza vaccination led to transient CMV viremia and CMV disease in our renal transplant recipients on potent immunosuppressive therapies. Further research is needed to assess the strength of this correlation, the mechanisms causing viremia and the risk of progression to clinical disease. Until then, clinicians must continue vaccination of SOTRs per the guidelines, but must also remember to enquire about recent vaccination when evaluating SOTRs with new onset CMV viremia." This article corresponding to this case is not available for regulatory submission due to copyright restriction. This is 1 of the 2 valid cases reported in the same literature article.; Sender's Comments:  US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2020GSK190048:Same reporter

I administered a high dose flu vaccine to a patient this morning around 11:59am. The patient does have a history of prior stroke. The patient's wife just called to report that she believes he may have had some sort of TIA event after the shot. She stated he had symptoms of numbness in his left arm, slurred speech, and confusion. She stated she understood the importance of seeking emergent medical care within the first hour of symptoms; however, when I asked her if she had her husband evaluated she stated that she was "headed that way earlier" but felt like he had improved so she took him home and got him something to eat. I strongly advised that she seek emergent medical care due to the symptoms he was having. She stated he is napping. I advised her that I felt very strongly that he should seek immediate medical care. She stated she understood. I followed up with the patient's wife about an hour later. She stated that she woke the patient up and she believes he is okay now. I reiterated that I strongly believe she needs to seek emergent medical care (call EMS, take him to the emergency room, etc). Wife reports that patient has had ~3 similar events this year already, one as recent as August 2020. She reports she has previously called EMS and they have evaluated him and held him for observation. She stated again that she does not believe emergent medical care is necessary. She stated she understood that I advised her to seek emergency medical care; however, she does not feel it is necessary given his history of similar episodes.
OTHER_MEDS: Patient does not fill his medications at our pharmacy so do not have access to his complete list of medications.

she received her shingrix vaccine 9/14/2020. At the time of administration, she complained of a burning sensation. Then later that day and for several days afterwards, she could not move her arm. Pain was unrelieved by OTC tylenol. She could move her arm after several days, but general pain still was there even as of today. She developed a large bruise at the injection site. I believe the vaccine was administered too high up on the deltoid. The injection should be in the deltoid, 2-3 fingers below the acromion process. The bruise was 2 fingers at the acromonion. So it was not below the finger space required. She showed pharmacy the bruise on 9/22/20, which was 8 days post injection.

On or about 12-AUG-2016, the patient was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (strength, dose, route, lot# and expiration date unknown) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). After receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered from herpes zoster, post herpetic neuralgia, Bell's palsy and tremors. As a result of these symptoms, the patient was seen and treated by medical providers. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient's symptoms have resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the vaccine. The patient also experiences mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of the condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient has suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the events herpes zoster, post herpetic neuralgia, Bell's palsy and tremors was considered to be not recovered and causal relationship was assessed as related. Swollen arm at injection site (left arm).  Stiff neck, chills, body aches, sleepiness, can't lift arm higher than chest.   Very tired but couldn't sleep. Body aches continue.  Slept as much as possible, but couldn't turn over.  Feeling very depressed the next morning.  Slightly dizzy and sleepy. Somewhat better the next morning, but still not feeling well.  I'm in good health, very fit, bike 6-10 miles a day. Did not contact my doctor.

Day 2 arm was very red,  hot, swollen, and hurt. It felt like my arm had been a punching bag. I could barely raise my arm. The next day the arm was swollen and the fluid started to drop down towards my elbow. Still very red but less sore. Returned to clinic to let them see what had happened. She suggested Zyrtec during the day and Benadryl at night. Following day (Day 3 of symptoms, the fluid has drained below the elbow. Arm still read on the back side.
LAB_DATA: Returned to clinic on 9/23 to have nurse at Clinic look at it and advise steps to take. She first thought to give me antibiotics. She called her supervisor who said to put me on antihistamines.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: An employee flu clinic was conducted on September 23 for the employees at the School by the Health Department staff.  This employee was given her injection approximately at 11:45 a.m.  The Health Nurse was made aware of the adverse event at 8:30a.m. on September 24, 2020.  The employee stated "I will be following up with my doctor today, but I believe that I had a severe allergic reaction with symptoms that included swelling/itching eyes, coughing, tightness of the chest, shortness of breath, fluid in the lungs, and feeling faint. I received the shot at about 11:45am, and started feeling symptoms around 1:30/2:00. I didn't put two and two together to realize that it was a reaction to the shot until much later in the night. I was able to go home, take a nebulizer treatment and Benadryl and started to feel better, a few hours later the symptoms were gone completely."  Case was interviewed at 9:00 a.m. by PHN on 9/24 and reported "feeling better" "still a bit itchy" and "will follow up with PCP today"  When asked if 911 was called yesterday when s/s appeared, case reported "No." It was advised in the future to call 911 or have someone call 911 as this is a life-threatening emergency.
CUR_ILL: Common cold a couple weeks ago

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Severe muscle aches and pain.  Using Tylenol to alleviate, but has not completely stopped symptoms
OTHER_MEDS: None, but did have flu shot at the same time

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Friday September 18th at around 7:00 am the location the patient started to experience both shooting and sore throbbing pain from the arm on which she was given the vaccine. She applied a heating pad and has been applying a heating pad the area. She only took ibuprofen two 200 mg tablets every 8 hours. As of right now the pain has subsided to an extent. Not completely. She is experiencing a rash diagnosed by her doctor as shingles.
LAB_DATA: Yesterday 9/24/2020 her doctor diagnosed her as having shingles through physical examination.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: pt developed rash within 24 hours of rcv'ing the vaccine.  rash started on chest and progressed to chest, abdomen, back, top of buttocks, neck and chin.  no rash on face, no resp issues or sob.  mother advised office on 9/23/20 when she noted the rash on pts chin.  mother advised to give benadryl
Stomach problems

I experienced Marked swelling from the left shoulder to below the elbow and about 85-90% circumferentially. The injection site was in my left upper arm. This lasted 4-5 days and I did visit my doctor's office as well as the pharmacy regarding the swelling. I used benadryl, ice, and extra strength tylenol for the discomfort. In December, I went to an orthopedic clinic regarding the residual pain and weakness in that arm. Further studies included x-rays, PT, MRI of shoulder due to loss of posterior muscle of the left shoulder, and referral to a Dr. of Physical Medicine & Rehabilitation. He requested another MRI of the neck, then specific PT orders.
LAB_DATA: X-rays 12/18/2019, PT x 2 visits without help and there they discovered loss of the left shoulder muscle. MRI 1/13/2020 left shoulder and MRI 1/29/2020 of neck area Different therapist per Request of Physical Medicine and Rehab Dr. 2/3-10/2020 x 4 visits....then Covid hit. Suggested exercises at home continues still.
OTHER_MEDS: Bisoprolol, Simvastatin, PreNatal Vitamin, Vitamin D, Baby Aspirin, Premarin Cream
HISTORY: HTN controlled, High cholesterol controlled, Arthritis

first dose and second dose little over 30 days apart; Felt like the pharmacist hit a nerve; pain / injection site upon administration / first dose /  then it was just sore; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of pain in arm in a 63-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis. On an unknown date, immediately after receiving Shingrix and not applicable after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced pain in arm, drug dose administration interval too short and wrong injection technique. On an unknown date, the outcome of the pain in arm was recovered/resolved and the outcome of the drug dose administration interval too short and wrong injection technique were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the pain in arm to be related to Shingrix.  Additional information was provided as follows: The patient experienced pain in arm after the 1st dose of Shingrix, which lasted for a day and then it was just sore for 3-4 days. The patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix earlier than the recommended schedule, which led to shortening of vaccination schedule. The ptient felt that the pharmacist had hit a nerve, which led to wrong injection technique. No reactions were reported for the 2nd dose of Shingrix. The reporter consented to follow up. The case was considered as medication error with harm.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was given immunizations after he and his mother completed the consent form.  Approximately 12 minutes later  we heard a crash sound some form the exam room and we entered the room to find the patient on the floor.  He was alert, disoriented momentarily but was able to tell me his name, where he was and who I was right away. We helped him to the chair and called his mom into the room. She was in her car due  to the Covid Pandemic. He was pale and complained of nausea. He did not vomit. His vital signs were assessed and found to have low blood pressure and heart rate.  He drank juice and we reassessed 10 mins later and he had normal blood pressure and heart rate and his color returned to normal. He was able to talk and laugh. We discharged him home. We followed up by phone at 24 hours and 48 hours after the event and his mother reported he is doing well. with no new concerns or symptoms.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Administered HPV and influenza vaccine at 9:00 AM. Patient had immediate reaction upon administration of influenza and gardasil vaccine. Presented first with difficulty breathing then mild facial swelling and mild right arm swelling occurred shortly after. Patient was instructed to lay flat on the bed, take her mask off,  and use deep breaths. Instructed mom to stay with patient. Went into the hallway and grabbed Dr. immediately to come in and assess patient. Dr. instructed me to then obtain epinephrine. Spoke with staff, another nurse, about dosage needed. Drew up 0.5 mL of epinephrine per instructions on box. Lot # 335174 and Exp # 03/2021. Took epinephrine and a pulse/pulse oximetry meter into the room. Obtained patient's oxygen saturation at 98% and pulse at 72 bpm at 9:15 AM. Administered dose of epinephrine into patient's left deltoid at 9:18 AM per Dr.'s instructions. Patient laid flat again and was monitored for 15 minutes after injection. Patient's oxygen saturation was 99% and pulse was 80 at 9:30 AM. Patient feeling better at that time and showing no signs of distress.  No further doses of epinephrine needed or given per Dr. Patient dismissed and advised to contact us or seek emergency services if symptoms reappear. Patient also given a steroid by Dr. for home use. Spoke with staff, nursing manager, about excess epinephrine. Discarded remainder of epinephrine down the sink.

Herpes Zoster ophthalmicus; Corneal Stromal inflammation/necrotizing stromal keratitis; neurotrophic ulcer and a metaherpetic ulcer; pain; photophobia; corneal thinning; cornea was diffusely edematous; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of ophthalmic herpes zoster in a 78-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included amblyopia and ophthalmic herpes zoster (left-sided 20 years ago but was unable to provide documentation of her clinical presentation). Previously administered products included Shingrix (1st dose received on an unspecified date). Concurrent medical conditions included corneal decompensation (chronic in the eye secondary to forceps injury at birth).   On an unknown date, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. On an unknown date, 1 week after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced ophthalmic herpes zoster (serious criteria GSK medically significant), keratitis, eye ulcer, pain, photophobia, corneal thinning and corneal edema. The patient was treated with valaciclovir hydrochloride (Valacyclovir), moxifloxacin hydrochloride (Moxifloxacin), ciprofloxacin (Ciprofloxacine) and erythromycin. On an unknown date, the outcome of the ophthalmic herpes zoster, keratitis, eye ulcer, pain, photophobia, corneal thinning and corneal edema were Recovered/Resolved.   The reporter considered the ophthalmic herpes zoster, keratitis, eye ulcer, pain, photophobia, corneal thinning and corneal edema to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of Herpes Zoster ophthalmicus reactivation in a 78-years old female patient, who was vaccinated with Shingrix (GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis.  The patient had a history of amblyopia and chronic corneal decompensation in this eye secondary to forceps injury at birth. The patient also had a history of left-sided Herpes Zoster ophthalmicus (HZO) 20 years ago but was unable to provide documentation of her clinical presentation. No information on patient's family history, concurrent condition or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, the patient received 2 doses of Shingrix (administration route and site unspecified; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided. On an unspecified date, a week after second dose of Shingrix, the patient reported pain and photophobia that started 1 month before presentation. The patient was referred for progressive in her left eye. The patient had been prescribed erythromycin ointment and ciprofloxacin drops by her outside ophthalmologist without improvement. Visual acuity was counting fingers at 3 ft in the affected eye, and intraocular pressure was 15 mm Hg. Corneal sensation was markedly reduced relative to the contralateral eye. On slit lamp examination, the patient's cornea had a temporal paracentral epithelial defect 1.5x2.0 mm in size with 40% thinning of the underlying stroma. Stromal inflammation was noted around the area of thinning, suggestive of necrotizing stromal keratitis. The surrounding cornea was diffusely edematous. The anterior chamber was quiet. Dilated fundus examination was normal. The right eye had 20/20 visual acuity and unremarkable examination. Given the timing of events, recurrent HZO keratitis after Shingrix vaccination was considered the most probable diagnosis. Other differential diagnoses included a neurotrophic ulcer and a metaherpetic ulcer. The patient was started on oral valacyclovir 1000 mg 3 times daily, topical erythromycin ointment every 4 hours, and hourly preservative-free artificial tears. Three days later, the epithelial defect and thinning persisted. A bandage contact lens was placed, and the patient was started on topical moxifloxacin drops 4 times a day. At 1 week, the bandage contact lens was replaced with self-retained cryopreserved amniotic membrane ring (Prokera; Bio-Tissue) to promote epithelialization. One week later, the Prokera ring was removed. The thinned area had epithelialized with no evidence of further stromal melt. Two months after presentation, the patient reported no new recurrences, and her examination appeared stable. The author commented, "Although risk of HZO reactivation after Shingrix is likely exceedingly low, clinicians should report such rare AEs to improve understanding of which patients are at greatest risk. Histopathological studies have demonstrated persistence of VZV DNA in the human cornea up to 8 years after clinical onset of HZO, suggesting that the virus can reside in the corneal stroma and precipitate recurrent HZO in some patients. In the case of HZO reactivation after vaccination, an increase in cell-mediated immunity can trigger an immune response to VZV in the stroma, leading to stromal keratitis. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has no specific guidelines regarding vaccination in patients with previous HZO. Vaccination among age-eligible patients with previous HZO is encouraged unless the patient is having an active episode or flare-up. Once the infection is resolved, there is no specific wait time until vaccination is considered safe. In contrast, antivirals can be continued after Shingrix because the vaccine contains a glycoprotein and not an attenuated live virus, warranting further investigation for its role in preventing HZ in others locations in these patients. Limitations of this case include lack of microbiological testing, including cultures and PCR, to confirm the diagnosis of HZO. In addition, the clinical manifestation of the initial HZO is unknown due to missing previous records." The author concluded, "HZO reactivation after recombinant zoster vaccination is uncommon but possible. Ophthalmologists should remain aware of potential risks of zoster vaccination and take special precautions in patients with HZO history.

A contactable consumer (patient) reported that a 73-year-old female patient of an unspecified age received pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) (PREVNAR 13, NDC: 0005-1971-01), via an unspecified route of administration on 20Sep2020 at 0.5 ml single (half a milliliter prefilled syringe) for pneumonia vaccine. Caller received the pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) injection yesterday afternoon. She didn't know for sure but she started having a reaction. She had never had this reaction to anything. She started itching a lot. The itching wasn't too horrible being awake, but once she went to bed it was worse. Within in an hour she woke up scratching everywhere, mainly her arms. She even had little cuts from scratching. She got up and took a hot bath too. She also was feeling chills. She was cold and itched. That was why she thought getting in the hot bath would help. She also tried taking diphenhydramine hydrochloride (BENADRYL). She thought maybe it would help. It wasn't as bad after that, but she couldn't go back to sleep. She would try to lie down, but she would scratch. She was up most of the night. She doesn't know. She was still feeling itchy. When she was awake the itching was not so horrible. It was like it was coming from the inside and coming out of her. Her legs itch, her feet, and the soles of her feet. She did have a lot of allergies. She did call and check with Pfizer before getting this to make sure it didn't have Formaldehyde, Quaternium-15, or phenols in it. They are her worst allergies. It didn't have those in it so she decided to get it. She didn't know what it could be. There may be another allergy she was not aware of. She was a chemist until she retired, and she had some strange allergies. She has never had this type of reaction with her other allergies. Usually those are breathing allergies. The itching and chills started an hour after the vaccine. It had improved some. Now it was mostly in her hands, arms, and upper legs, before it was everywhere. After the bath, she had a cream that was from Dermatologist a while ago. It was Triamtinolone acetonide steroid cream 0.1%, she used that as well. She put that on the places that were itching. She doesn't know if it was the same lot of what she actually got. The lot wasn't listed on her papers. She has never had a pneumonia shot. She has had some itching in her hands before this, but nothing like this. The hands were giving her a little trouble before. She had been using that steroid cream periodically. So he doesn't know she got it. SYMPTOM_TEXT: her left arm was really sore and really hurt/got the same pain on the other arm/pain in her upper legs; she could not even lift her arms; muscles were inflamed; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient). A 74-year-old female patient received pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) (PREVNAR 13), via an unspecified route of administration in left arm on an unspecified date of 2020 at single dose for getting older/pneumonia vaccine. Medical history included ongoing osteoporosis. There were no concomitant medications. The patient went in to get the pneumonia vaccine because she was older and the doctor wanted her to get one. She reported had a terrible reaction that has changed her life. Then she was on prednisone for who knows how long. The reason for the call was that she was looking for any information on this reaction occurring and to find out a list of ingredients for the product. She was not sure the date the product was administered but thought the shot was given in either the latter part of Aug2020 or early Sep2020. A couple hours later her left arm was really sore and really hurt but she thought it was like a tenuis shot, how that hurts. Then she got the same pain on the other arm where she got no shot and the pain began to spread throughout both biceps. The next day, there was pain in her upper legs. The pain was there when she woke up every morning and the pain was worse every day. It got to the point she could not even lift her arms. She took paracetamol (TYLENOL), trying this for a couple day and it would made it, after about 1.5 hours, where she could get out of bed and move her arms. She finally called the doctor and was told that the doctor would give her prednisone but wanted her to get lab work first. The weekend came and she went to urgent care where she was given a methylprednisolone (MEDROL DOSEPAK). The caller informed her doctor who instructed her that was fine but she was to go to the ER and get labs done. After the lab work came back, she was told it was ok to get the prednisone and use it. Within 7 hours of starting the product, the pain was better and by day 6 the pain was gone so she stopped the product. Then 2 weeks later the pain came back and got worse. She went to a rheumatologist who put her back on the prednisone, she was taking 15mg. The doctor tried to taper her off and she got down to 1 prednisone pill. When she went to a new rheumatologist she was told to stop in 3 days, the prednisone but after stopping, within 3 days the pain came back. Now she is living on prednisone and can't function without it. she had been going through test to figure out what was causing this but it all started with this pneumonia vaccine, she was fine before. The caller was looking for information on the ingredients and if this information was available to the public. She had done research online and found other people have had issues. The caller explained she had no information on these patients specifically nor did she have and product details such as NDC, Lot, or Expiry for product used. The problem was that she had severe osteoporosis and prednisone makes bones more brittle. That was why she seeing a rheumatologist, for the osteoporosis. The prednisone is in a pharmacy bottle. Unknown number on the bottle: 54502. She had a lot of test done and they were still coming in, for inflammation since that was what the doctors are saying is the problem. She got some last week and some were coming in. The doctors explained to her that her muscles were inflamed. She was supposed to see the rheumatologist at the end of the week for the interpretation of what he thought was going on. The caller also stated she hadn't gotten a flu shot. The outcome of 'she could not even lift her arms' was recovered, while the other events were not recovered.  No follow-up attempts are needed. No further information is expected.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient came in stating he needed to receive a Shingles vaccine and that he had been advised to get vaccinated during a visit to MD. Proir to administration pharmacist reviewed with the patient vaccine regiment and side effects, then administered. On the patient's way out, the pharmacist reiterated that he would want to come back within 2-6 months for the completion of the course (shot #2). It was at this point that the patient stated that he had had at least 1 shingrix vaccine in the past and just figured he was due for another. The pharmacist researched and discovered that the patient had indeed received 2 previous shingles shots on 11/14/19 & 2/9/20. At this point the pharmacist contacted GSK to see if there was any data on 3 vaccines. GSK said that while they do not recommend more than 2 shots, that they had done studies on a 3 shot regimen in immuno-compromised patients. In pertaining to side effects, GSK stated that side effects that were reported were the same as after shot 1 & 2 (pain at injection site, lethargy, fatigue) with no serious or long term effects. This information was communicated to the patient. MD also informed
Right shoulder pain, and decreased range of motion.  SIRV injury.

HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Brittle bone disease ((5 fractures in 4 years)); Peripheral neuropathy

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Vasovagal reaction immediately following vaccine administration. Patient lost consciousness for approximately 10 seconds after receiving vaccines and regained consciousness. Patient was sitting in chair while having shots administered and did not obtain any secondary injuries. Patient was monitored in clinic for 30 minutes with vital signs being taken. Patient recovered well and did not report any pain, dizziness or lightheadedness.

Suppressed appetite; Diarrhea; Nauseous; Stomach pain; Little indigestion; Spontaneous report received 31JUL2020.  A female consumer reported that she experienced little indigestion (PT: Dyspepsia), nausea (PT: Nausea), diarrhea (PT: Diarrhoea), stomach pain (PT: Abdominal pain upper), suppressed appetite (PT: Decreased appetite), following immunization with Vivotif. The consumer took first two doses of Vivotif on 25JUL2020 and 27JUL2020. On 27JUL2020, she realized that she had a stomach pain. On 29JUL2020, she took third dose of Vivotif and on the same day, she reported that the stomach pain got worse. On 30JUL2020, she felt nauseous, her appetite was suppressed, and she didn't eat anything, and she had diarrhea. On 31JUL2020, she took last dose of Vivotif. Additionally, she stated that she just had a little indigestion left. She had no vomiting.  She stated that she did not receive any treatment for the reported events. Action taken with Vivotif with respect to the reported events was dose not changed. She had recovered from the event "nausea" and the events of "diarrhea", "stomach pain" and "suppressed appetite" were almost resolved. The outcome of the event "little indigestion" was resolving at the time of report.  Moreover, she reported that she has had acid reflux for the past couple of months.  Concomitant medication included omeprazole (20 mg; once a day)  Company Comment: A consumer had little indigestion (dyspepsia), nausea, diarrhoea, stomach pain (abdominal pain upper), suppressed appetite (decreased appetite) after taking two doses of Vivotif. In response to the events, consumer continued taking the remaining two doses of Vivotif. After a few days of completing Vivotif, nausea has resolved, abdominal pain upper, decreased appetite, diarrhoea were almost resolved and she still had little indigestion left. This consumer has a history of acid reflux for a few months before starting vivotif. Considering the case information, and potential of vivotif to cause nausea, diarrhoea, abdominal pain upper, decreased appetite, the causality of all these events is assessed as possible (confounded by underlying acid reflux condition). The causality of dyspepsia is assessed as possible (role of vivotif cannot be ruled out and confounded by underlying acid reflux condition).; Sender's Comments: A consumer had little indigestion (dyspepsia), nausea, diarrhoea, stomach pain (abdominal pain upper), suppressed appetite (decreased appetite) after taking two doses of Vivotif. In response to the events, consumer continued taking the remaining two doses of Vivotif. After a few days of completing Vivotif, nausea has resolved, abdominal pain upper, decreased appetite, diarrhoea were almost resolved and she still had little indigestion left. This consumer has a history of acid reflux for a few months before starting vivotif. Considering the case information, and potential of vivotif to cause nausea, diarrhoea, abdominal pain upper, decreased appetite, the causality of all these events is assessed as possible (confounded by underlying acid reflux). The causality of dyspepsia is assessed possible (role of vivotif cannot be ruled out and confounded by underlying acid reflux).

Pt who received both anthrax #2 and primary SPV on the same day (11/7/05). Approximately 12 days later, he noticed he was having chest pain while out on the town with friends. He decided to go home and go to bed, thinking he had over exerted himself in the previous days. He woke up during the night with increasing chest pain (10/10) and SOB secondary to chest pain and was sent to be seen at the local hospital. A complete work up was done and he was diagnosed as having coronary artery spasm. He was hospitalized for 4 days and placed on quarters for 4 more days after discharge. He was sent home on nifedipine and isosorbide. He was then placed on a profile and returned to the states in March of 2006 for follow up. Since the original episode he has had 2 more episodes of CP which he did not seek attention for the first time, but on 5/20/06 he got evaluated at the cardiac work up was normal. He was evaluated by a cardiologist on 5/06 and all test results normal. The nifedipine and isosorbide were stopped at that time.

I had both doses /  had two cases of shingles / in August, and / in September/ Suspected vaccination failure; shingles / in September / on my lower back; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of suspected vaccination failure in a 77-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included shingles (once every couple months). Concurrent medical conditions included stress.   In May 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. In August 2020, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. In September 2020, between 4 and 5 months after receiving Shingrix and between 1 and 2 months after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria GSK medically significant) and shingles. On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure and shingles were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the vaccination failure and shingles to be related to Shingrix and Shingrix.  Additional information was provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported, but could be 77 or 78 years old. The patient had both doses, one in May and then the second three months after the first dose and had two cases of shingles occur. One last month in August, and now one this month in September, and patient was wondering if she should report this to the pharmacy where she got vaccination, or to her doctor; she was under the understanding that the vaccine would prevent her from getting the shingles, but she still getting shingles. The patient had a history of shingles, stating if she was under a lot of stress she used to get shingles maybe once every couple months, and it would just be slight breakout might be the size of a dime, nickel, or quarter, on my lower back. It had been happening off and on for the past 40 years. Consumer gave consent to contact her pharmacy and her physician, though limited contact information was available at the time of call. Premature delivery at 36.4 weeks of gestation; Herpes type 2; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; Acid reflux; This is an observational study case, received on 07-Aug-2019 from other health professional and concerned a 20-year-old, pregnant, female subject of body weight 97 lbs, height 60 inches and body mass index (BMI) 18.9, enrolled in, a prospective observational safety study.   The subject's past medical history included bacterial vaginosis (from 07-Sep-2018 to 16-Sep-2018). The subject's concurrent condition included muscle spasms. The subject's concomitant medications included Prenatal vitamins (mineral nos, vitamins nos) for pregnancy, Metrogel (metronidazole) for bacterial vaginosis and ciclopirox for muscle spasms.   The subject's obstetrical history noted that the subject had no previous pregnancies. The subject did not have a history of offspring with major congenital malformations (MCMs). Also, the subject had no maternal or paternal history with MCMs. The subject did not use alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy. The subject used cigarettes during pregnancy (one pack per day).   The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 01-Mar-2018. Estimated delivery date (EDD) and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) were reported as 06-Dec-2018. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 30-Aug-2018, spinal muscular atrophy test and cystic fibrosis mutation analysis revealed no MCMs.   On 10-Sep-2018, ultrasound revealed no MCM.   On 08-Oct-2018, at gestational age of 31 weeks (calculated per LMP), the subject was vaccinated with Flucelvax QIVc (Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD) [influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration and anatomical location: not reported) (explicitly coded as �vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation. The batch number reported was 252664.   On the same day, after receiving Flucelvax QIVc, the subject developed acid reflux and started treatment with Zantac (ranitidine hydrochloride), at a dose of one tablet administered via oral route, once per day.   On 22-Oct-2018, a toxoplasmosis, rubella, cytomegalovirus, herpes simplex, and HIV (TORCH) panel test and ultrasound revealed no MCMs.    On 26-Oct-2018, 18 days after vaccination, the subject developed herpes type 2. It was not reported whether the subject received any corrective treatment for the event.  On 30-Oct-2018, ultrasound revealed no MCM.   On 11-Nov-2018, at gestational age of 36.4 weeks (as reported), the subject vaginally delivered live birth, male neonate. The neonate's birth weight was 2041 g, head circumference and length were not reported. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity and respiration (APGAR) scores were 8 (one minute) and 9 (five minutes). APGAR score was not reported for 10 minutes. No major congenital malformation was identified at birth.  On 07-Aug-2019, the subject completed the study and the registry was closed as no additional information was expected.   At the time of follow up reporting on 17-Sep-2020, the subject had not recovered from the events of acid reflux and �herpes simplex type II'.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.   The event of �premature delivery' was considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus' Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  This case is linked to 201904364, the corresponding child report.  Non-significant additional information received on 04-Sep-2019 from other health professional: It was confirmed that the events 'herpes simplex' and 'acid reflux' were still ongoing. No change in the narrative.  Additonal information received on 17-Sep-2020 from other health professional: The subject's age was updated from 21 to 20 years. Fetal outcome changed from normal to perinatal complication in pregnancy information. Six laboratory tests coded in laboratory data. Concomitant medications details updated. The event of �premature delivery' was marked as medically significant and the case was upgraded to serious. Stop date added for the events of �premature delivery' and �vaccine exposure during pregnancy'. Outcome changed from �not reported' to �resolved' for �vaccine exposure during pregnancy'. Date of study completion was provided. number removed as reference number. The narrative was amended accordingly.  Company comment: The patient experienced herpes simplex type II 18 days after vaccination and premature delivery 1 month 3 days after vaccination with Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD. The patient also developed gastroesophageal reflux disease on the same day after vaccination with the suspect product, administered at 31 weeks of gestation. Chronology is plausible. Although causality for gastroesophageal reflux disease was highly confounded by pregnancy, causal role of the suspect vaccine cannot be totally excluded and is assessed as unlikely related. (defaults to "related" in the safety database for reporting purposes). The patient's medical history of muscle spasms, and especially tobacco use may have contributed to the event of premature delivery. Causality is assessed as not related. For the event of herpes simplex type II, causality is assessed as not related due to biological implausibility. Vaccine exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company's conventions.; Sender's Comments: The patient experienced herpes simplex type II 18 days after vaccination and premature delivery 1 month 3 days after vaccination with Flu Vaccine Cell Subunit QIV NVD. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Small amount of liquid pooled underneath bandage that may have been part of the dose leaked out of the injection site after administration; Dose was delivered through the bandage; Small amount of liquid pooled underneath bandage that may have been part of the dose leaked out of the injection site after administration; This spontaneous case was received on 17-Sep-2020 from pharmacist via Agency (reference number: SEQW20-01911) and concerned an 82-year-old, male patient.  The patient had no relevant medical history and was not taking any concomitant medications.   On 15-Sep-2020, the patient was vaccinated with Fluad Quadrivalent (influenza vaccine, inactivated influenza virus surface antigen (subunit), egg-derived, mf59, dose: less than 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular and anatomical location: left deltoid) for protection against seasonal influenza. It was reported that the pharmacist had placed a 3M Injection Safe Barrier Bandage and dose was delivered through the bandage [explicitly coded as �Wrong technique in product usage process']. The batch number reported was 279781, and expiry date: 12-May-2021.   On the same day, later that night, after receiving Fluad Quadrivalent, the patient removed the bandage and discovered a small amount of liquid pooled underneath the bandage. The pharmacist was concerned that the liquid may have been part of the dose and it might have somehow leaked out of the injection site after administration [explicitly coded as �Incomplete dose administered']. No corrective treatment was given to the patient.   At the time of initial reporting on 17-Sep-2020, the outcome for the event of �vaccination site extravasation' was not reported.   The reporter assessed the case as serious due to medically significance.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment.  Company comment: The patient developed vaccination site extravasation on the same day after vaccination with the suspect product, Fluad Quadrivalent. Chronology is suggestive. Reportedly, the dose was delivered through the bandage and small amount of liquid pooled underneath bandage that may have been part of the dose leaked out of the injection site after administration [explicitly coded as �Wrong technique in product usage process' and �Incomplete dose administered']. Causal relationship for vaccination site extravasation is assessed as possibly related. (defaults to "related" in the safety database for reporting purposes). The patient received influenza high dose quadrivalent vaccine on 9/3/2020.  He woke up 09/18/2020 at 4:00 AM with the inability to stand.  He was completely normal on the evening before he went to bed (21-22:00).  He fell a few times because he could not lock his legs.  He denied numbness in the feet.  He came to the ED 9/20/2020 and wanted to be discharged home with pain medications and close monitoring, of which he was able to walk with a walker. The patient was admitted to Hospital on 9/21/2020 with sudden onset leg weakness and numbness in the hands. The numbness was involving the inner surface of the hands and slightly in the forearm.  He did not think he is weak in the arms.  He denied any recent trauma.  He had a fall a few days ago, bruising his knees- after the onset of leg weakness. The patient also complained of a transient episode of severe leg and low back pain that started 9/20/2020 and resolved with narcotics. He also complained of a two day history of severe neck pain, radiating to the back of the head, and between the scapular region. The pain was sudden in onset and it spontaneously resolved.  The pain occurred three days before he developed weakness in the legs. Neurology consulted and diagnosed the patient with Guillain-Barr� syndrome (GBS). The patient was given 25g of 10% immune globulin IV on 9/21/2020 at 20:33. The patient experienced hypertension that may have been exacerbated by IVIG volume, so treatment was changed to plasma exchange (PLEX) once every other day for a total of 5 treatments over 10 days. Today on 9/25/2020, the patient continues to have weakness in his legs.  He is having trouble swallowing and coughing.  He is receiving the second PLEX session. He still remains hospitalized on 9/25/2020.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had shingles in the early 1990's .  I consulted with a nurse, who is a friend, about the shingles vaccination, and she recommended I still take it. I told her about my previous episode with shingles. (This morning I checked with web site, which states it unlikely I would again contract shingles. Perhaps I should have consulted with that before getting the vaccination.)  Within a couple hours of the vaccine I felt stiffness in my left arm where the vaccination was administered. Around 7:00PM, I began to feel flush, and hot. I felt my forehead and did not detect a fever. I did not feel like I had symptoms of the flu. My head turned reddish. This continued throughout the evening.   I was functioning: I am the primary caregiver for my 100 year old Mom, and tended to her as I usually would. I cooked dinner,  set the table, after dinner I helped her to bed, and then I did the dishes. The hotness and some stiffness continued. I also felt a slight disorientation, and weakness. I usually shower before going to bed, but I thought this was not a good idea. I was losing strength and concentration.   I went to bed around 11:15PM. During the night I had some slight sweating, but again, this did not feel like the flu. During the night the hotness remained, and some stiffness. As early morning approached the hotness had mostly dissipated. I did sleep in because I was tired, and it was a day off for me. I did my usual morning exercises and stretching, thinking those may speed recovery. I think it helped.  I made breakfast for my Mom and myself, and as of now 12:25PM, I am felling much better, but there is some residual weakness, but not the hotness nor flushing.  I am of mind to not get the second, follow-up vaccine.
