My mom, age 84, is currently hospitalized for a thoracic surgery to drain fluid from her right lung. This is related to having a chronic heart condition, including a mechanical mitral valve, but she is still active at her age.  She does live on her own in her own home and does the bookkeeping/ bill-paying so she is still living an active life.  She admitted to the hospital last week on Wednesday Sept 16, 2020. Her surgery took place on Sept. 17.  The night before, on the 16th, she was given a flu shot which I was told was made by  Glaxo Smith Kline "Fluzone Quad" lot B7473  MDC 58160-885-41  exp 6/30/21.  I believe this may be a stronger quad vaccine, using recombinent DNA, with three or four times more hemagglutinin antigen versus standard dose quad activated vaccine, with more reports of adverse reactions in the elderly than normal.  One of my mom?s nurses said her own mother was sick for a day and half after getting her flu shot recently. My mom?s reaction has been severely swollen and black and blue arm including her hand. She complained of pain with the arm during the night before her surgery.  Immediately after her thoracic surgery, her first complaint was the pain in her ?flu shot arm.? She complained she never slept the night of her flu shot due to pain. She complained of headache, back ache, fatigue and weakness. The surgery outcome was bad and she required it to be redone which occurred on 9/24/2020.  I became very concerned when I showed pictures of my mom?s arm to a co-worker (also a nurse) who said her dad?s arm looked just like that after he got a flu shot.  He then started to have fever, weakness, change in level of consciousness and was dead in 2 weeks. Allergy to flu shot was listed as cause of death on his death certificate.  He was doing well before that.  My mom is on chronic blood thinners (coumadin at home and heparin now in the hospital) which the hospital is citing as the reason for the bruising to her arm-- but that does not explain the swelling, pain and other symptoms. The bruising is excessive and not something ever experienced before when she did NOT have a flu shot while on heparin.  She has never had a reaction like this to the flu shot before. I feel her immune response may very well have affected the surgical outcome in which she was left with a full liter of gelatin like blood in the region of the lungs, requiring a second surgery.  My mother only took the shot because it was suggested by the hospital.  I feel this product should NOT be recommended for use immediately prior to surgery.  My mother was seen by a vascular surgeon as a result of the large, hard hematoma to the vaccination injection site. The arm was needed for lab work and IVs (other arm is post mastectomy from many years ago)  but ultimately the flu shot arm could not be used due to compromised condition. It remains darkly bruised from shoulder to finger tips, wrapped with a pressure dressing, swollen and painful. My mother's hemoglobin fell dramatically, at least partially related to this arm, and her ultimate outcome is still uncertain.
OTHER_MEDS: Lasix, Ramapril, Lovenox, tylenol, zolpidem, benedryl
CUR_ILL: In hospital to treat pleural effusion.
HISTORY: Mechanical mitral heart valve,  atrial fib/pacemaker, hypertension

Patient presented to ED on 9-14-2020 after reportedly 8 days of symptoms including fatigue , fevers, loss of speech. CT and MRI of brain showed ADEM (acute disseminated encephalomyelitis). Patient was admitted and discharged on 9-21-2020
LAB_DATA: Patient's clinical picture continued to decline concerningly within the first 12h on the floor, and an extensive workup was initiated, including tests for tick- and mosquito-borne illnesses, a UDS, and encephalitis/meningitis panel. Blood, urine and CSF cultures were obtained. A head CT was obtained and showed evidence of ADEM, which was subsequently confirmed on MRI. Neurology was then consulted and recommended treating with high dose steroids as well as IVIG due to severity of illness. He was also given diazepam for comfort due to increasing rigidity and Parkinsonian symptoms. Due to multiple bug bites and inability to rule out tick exposure at the lake, doxycycline was started on admission, but was discontinued on 9/18 as ADEM was deemed to be the most likely cause of his symptoms and he started having bradycardia with occasional dropped beats. Due to this rhythm abnormality, EKG was obtained and initial read showed bradycardia with sinus arrhythmia with potential LV hypertrophy (final read still pending at time of discharge). His HR and rhythm did return to normal as he continued to improve. On the morning following his second dose of IVIG, patient was markedly improved - he was eating solid foods, speaking a few words and less rigid on exam. After 5 days of IV steroids, he was transitioned to PO with plan for a 5 week taper. He continued to make daily improvement and on the day of discharge, he was starting to take a few steps again.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient was a 17 year old female there with her family (her parents and two sisters). About 5 minutes after administration, her sister alerted me to grab some alcohol prep pads to put under the patient's nose and she (and her parents) informed me that she faints after she receives vaccines. I alerted the technicians to call a code white over the intercom, and used the ammonia inhalant to revive the patient (she was unconscious in her mother's arms). The technicians grabbed the patient a chair and she was seated and asked questions about her surroundings until management arrived. Management brought her water, orange juice, and ice and our team fanned her with air. The event lasted approximately 20-30 minutes around 5:30pm, and her parents were appreciative of our attentiveness. After the patient was fully conscious, I informed her family that I would call them this evening to check-in. At 6:50pm, I spoke with the father and he informed me that the patient was doing well. No injuries were reported.
PRIOR_VAX: Faints after vaccines

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient bled at time of vaccine just a small amount not enough to fill inject safe bandage. Bleeding stopped before he left. He was concerned that since he bled perhaps the entire dose did not enter body as it should. He said he did not have any problems and did not bleed alot but I told him more than likely all the medication stayed in since it went in the muscle but it would be a good question to find out about since it is a series of vaccines I wanted to make sure he had complete coverage. I contacted and they referred me to the CDC. CDC referenced doses not properly administered as the category it would be and they stated that the dose should be repeated. The CDC stated that for Twinrix if the full dose was not properly administered the dose should be repeated and there is no wait time to do it whereas if it had been a live vaccine the patient would have to wait 4 weeks. The patient came in on 9/24/20 and a repeated 2nd dose was administered. Patient vaccination was uneventful.

She is allergic to PNEUMOVAX 23 vaccine; Tingling; Numbness; Flushed face; This spontaneous report was received from a company representative, reporting on herself, a 61 year old female patient. The patient's concomitant medications included rosuvastatin calcium(CRESTOR), famotidine(PEPCID), montelukast sodium(SINGULAIR) and fexofenadine hydrochloride(ALLEGRA). The patient's pertinent medical history included anaphylaxis shock in January 2020, the cause was unknown, but might have been the intravenous (IV) dye, azithromycin (Z-PAK) or ceftriaxone (ROCEPHIN). The patient underwent a computed tomography (CT) scan.  On 16-JUN-2020 the patient was vaccinated with a dose of pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent)(PNEUMOVAX23), intramuscular for vaccination (dose, frequency, anatomical location, lot number and expiration date were not provided). On the same day, within 20 minutes after she received the vaccines, she noticed tingling (paraesthesia), numbness (hypoaesthesia) and a flushed face. She was still in the provider's office when the reaction occurred. The provider gave her fexofenadine (ALLEGRA) and was sent home. The patient reported she cleared up the same day.  On 22-SEP-2020, her provider did a "challenge test" on her and confirmed she was allergic to pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent)(PNEUMOVAX23) vaccine. Other laboratory diagnostics/studies performed were mediator test blood draw and complete blood count (CBC).  The outcome of paraesthesia, flushing and hypoaesthesia was reported as resolved. The outcome of allergy to vaccine was unknown. The causal relationship between therapy with Pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent)(PNEUMOVAX23) and paraesthesia, flushing and hypoaesthesia was not provided. The reporter considered allergy to vaccine to be related to Pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent)(PNEUMOVAX23).
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Anaphylactic shock (the cause is unknown, Could have been the IV dye Z-pak or Rocephin.); Computerised tomogram

Additional details were provided as follows: The reporter was patient herself. The patient was hard of hearing thus it was a bit difficult for communication with her. The lot number details were not asked to the patient as she was elderly. The patient received the vaccine in her upper arm and within 7 hours she became severely ill. The patient mentioned that she was bed-ridden and felt like she had a bad case of the flu and that her muscles were extremely weak and a;so that she was shaking/shivering uncontrollably for at least 12, possibly 24 hours; such that she fell out of bed. The patient also had a huge headache and had horrible diarrhea for 24 hours. She had nausea and stomach cramping and mentioned that her symptoms were so severe that she could not get out of bed. She further said that she went to the bathroom a lot and needed help to walk to the bathroom. She had become dehydrated because it was hard to drink due to the nausea. It was also hard to breathe for her but she did convey that as she had pre-existing sinus problems, so she indicated that she often had trouble breathing. The symptoms lasted for 3 to 4 days. She stated that she almost went to the hospital because her symptoms were so awful/debilitating. She started to feel "human" again by the weekend, on Saturday and had not seen her physician but she did call him and he had advised her not to get the second shot of the Shingrix series. She said that she felt fine then.  She also conveyed that she has had other immunizations before but never had an issue like that and also said that flu shot did not phase her out and further said she did not have fever or vomitting. The reporter consented to follow-up. The reporter provided her personal email address but did not have a personal fax number. I wanted to let you know I had a very unusual and adverse reaction to the flu shot.  I received it Friday Sept. 25 about 2:45pm in an outdoor drive thru.  I was not feeling badly that evening but could not go to sleep (that is unusual for me on a Friday). I fFell asleep about midnight and at 3am work up with a massive case of chills.  Shivering so hard the next day I knew I strained muscles.   I woke up Sat. at about 7am feeling terrible.  I took my temperature and it was 101 and stayed that way all day. I had a terrible headache, nausea joint ache and body ache.  The rest of the day I kept napping 2-3 times and ate bread and crackers.  I took Tylenol and by late evening my temp was a little less than 100.  I felt the symptoms at that time did not warrant a visit to a doctor, however had they not gotten better in 24 hours I would make that decision to go to a Dr.    I slept well Sat. night and Sunday am my temp was 99 and is still 99 at 10:30am on Sunday 27th.    I have been taking the flu shots (yes I know each year the compositions changes) for 25-30 annually. I have had very minor reactions sore arm, elevated temp but this was debilitating.  Back to normal temp 98.4 by Sunday evening.

Thoughts of what would happen if killed himself; Feelings of desperation; General feeling of being off; This spontaneous case was reported on 17-Sep-2020 from pharmacist to agency (reference number: SEQW20-01893) and concerned a 38-year-old, male patient.  The patient's concurrent conditions included type 1 diabetes. The patient's past medication included Afluria Quad last year without a problem. The patient's concomitant medications included Basaglar (insulin glargine) and Novolog (insulin aspart) for type 1 diabetes.  On 15-Sep-2020 in the morning, the patient was vaccinated with Afluria Quadrivalent [influenza vaccine, dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration, anatomical location: not reported] for influenza prophylaxis. The batch number reported was P100242860 and expiry date 30-Jun-2021.  On the same day in the evening, after receiving Afluria Quadrivalent, the patient started having feeling of desperation and thinking what would happen if he killed himself. It was reported that the patient is usually a very jovial person and normally does not have this thoughts. The patient was not feeling the urge to do it but was thinking what would happen if he killed himself. Additionally, the patient felt general feeling of being off and questioned if the vaccine could cause a systemic reaction or if this could be an interaction since he has recently changed therapy with Basaglar (insulin glargine) and Novolog (insulin aspart) for type 1 diabetes.   At the time of initial reporting on 17-Sep-2020, the patient was recovering from the events. The patient stated he was feeling better but not recovered yet.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.  The reporter assessed the case as serious.  Company comment: The patient developed suicidal ideation, feeling of despair and feeling abnormal on the same day after vaccination with the suspect product, Afluria Quadrivalent. Chronology is plausible. Medical history of diabetes type 1 and use of Novolog (a rapid-acting insulin) confound causality. Fluctuations in blood glucose can result in rapid mood changes, including low mood and irritability. Considering all above mentioned, causal relationship for all events is assessed as not related.; Sender's Comments: The patient developed suicidal ideation, feeling of despair and feeling abnormal on the same day after vaccination with the suspect product, Afluria Quadrivalent. Chronology is plausible. Medical history of diabetes type 1 and use of Novolog (a rapid-acting insulin) confound causality. Fluctuations in blood glucose can result in rapid mood changes, including low mood and irritability. Considering all above mentioned, causal relationship for all events is assessed as not related.

Patient noted on vaccine administration record, a previous reaction after vaccine and she stated her mother told her to "to always bring a companion for vaccinations". I asked her to further expand on her reaction and if this was her first shot, she explained she may faint and this was her first flu shot. I requested she sit for the vaccine and stay seated for about 15 mins or more after so I can monitor her. I gave her flu shot and she seemed fine but within 2-3 mins she asked her friend for water because she was feeling odd, in which her friend swiftly went to store for ice water. When i came around the counter to observe her she had fainted in a seated position over the consultation counter, eyes rolled back and unresponsive. I immediately called 911 to explain the situation and while on phone with 911 she regained consciousness and  I asked if she wanted to go to hospital via ambulance. She declined, stating she was coming back and reassuring me she was going to be okay. I hung up with 911, she drank the water and I fanned her with clipboard. She sat for an additional 30 mins until she was okay, I continously asked if she was feeling better and to contact us if she had any concerns.
PRIOR_VAX: unknown

shingles; Information has been received from a lawyer and a patient of unknown age and gender regarding a case in litigation. At the time of the patient's vaccination, the patient relied on the warning label affixed to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), and the information relayed through patient's healthcare provider(s) that zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) was effective in preventing shingles on a permanent basis and did not carry any significant risk of adverse effects, which induced the patient to be vaccinated. SYMPTOM_TEXT: She received Gardasil 9 vaccine on 9/17/20, felt typical soreness in her left upper arm for the next 3 days, but on the 4th day, she developed "severe pain" in her left lateral upper arm. She is an avid athlete, but a few days prior to vaccination, she threw out her back and was taking a break from her usual work-out. On 9/21/20, she did lift a heavy desk up some stairs, and her severe pain started some time after this activity. She presented urgently to hospital on 9/26 and was advised to increase ibuprofen to 800mg PO TID with food.  The pain is located "right on the deltoid attachment and feels like stabbing into the bone," not like a muscle strain. The pain radiates down into her left fingers and she struggles to lift her left arm above 90 degrees. She feels the pain has stabilized now, but it's adversely affecting her life. Denies swelling, bruising, or erythema of left shoulder or upper arm, and there is no worsening of pain when she palpates the left upper arm. She can't lift weights or sleep through the night due to the pain. This lack of sleep "is frustrating as a grad student." It wakes her up around 5am despite taking Advil q6 hours and Acetaminophen qHS. The pain is the worst in the early mornings. Advil does reduce her pain, but doesn't eliminate it, and unfortunately, it's now upsetting her stomach.
LAB_DATA: Examined in clinic on 9/26/20 - reassured and told to increase ibuprofen Examined in clinic on 9/28/20 - ordered humerus xray (normal) and US rotator cuff (not completed yet)
HISTORY: Hx of abnormal Pap smear BMI 29

A 65-years-old female patient received pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) (PREVNAR 13), intramuscular on 20May2019 at single dose in a low part of her right arm for immunisation.  Medical history included ongoing mild asthma, allergies to all kinds of trees and dogs and rodents, and two kinds of dust mites, and everything but cats since 2003, a cough and scratchy throat and her eyes would get affected, sick with the sinus issues, fatigue. The patient had developed a lipoma on her arm at the injection site of a pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) injection that was also described as a severe swelling the size of half of a golf ball and her skin felt harder in that area, about 4 months ago she noticed that the area around the lipoma had a yellowish old bruise-like color. The patient had bruise-like discoloration of the skin in the site of administration as a side effect for receiving pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein), she believed that she received the vaccine inappropriately in a low part of her right arm. Caller states that the nurse who gave it to her, gave it lower than the caller would have given it. She had several allergies, the fact that this lipoma did not go away made her depressed. Her physician told her that this might be a reaction to the preservatives of the vaccine and the patient thought there was a chance she was allergic to one of the preservatives in the vaccine. She also wanted to know if this lipoma was ever going to go away. she is so upset and very disturbed, because it makes her arm look deformed. Caller got the injection, and in about 10 days, she could see that arm, it didn't get red, it just got big like a bulge, and in 10 days she was calling her doctor, and he was seeing her again and said that it looked like a lipoma. Caller states that her doctor told her to give it a month, and so the caller went back in a month, and the caller was sent for an ultrasound and right when she took her jacket off, the doctor said that he could see right away that swelling on her right arm. Caller stated that they ultrasounded her left arm too, to be able to compare the two, and the ultrasound revealed that it was a lipoma and there was no cancer cells at the time. But caller states that what was troublesome, was that she kept hoping it would go down, and go away, but it was like harder tissue. Caller states that she was just so upset and mad at herself. Caller stated that her doctor told her that this was extremely rare, but anything that was rare, the caller got it. Caller stated that humidity affects her, and she has issues from it, but nothing major. Caller stated that she ate organic and did everything good for her heath, and if she had known this would have happened, she would not have gotten it. Caller stated that she did not take flu shots anymore. Caller states that she was not going to get the second pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) shot either. Caller stated that she used to take the flu shot when she was teaching, because she was around kids and was always sick with the sinus issues and strep from the kids. Caller stated that she was much healthier since she retired, cause she had been doing some sub-ing and she had tremendous side effects from going in to those buildings. Caller states that she would test it to try and figure out which buildings bothered her, and she would get a cough and scratchy throat and her eyes would get affected, and she couldn't read a story to the kids before the buses came, so she had to quit that job. Caller confirmed that she had asthma and allergies prior to ever receiving the Prevnar 13 vaccine. Caller stated that her doctors were all relieved when she decided she was done. Caller stated that her doctors said that as she got older, she shouldn't keep pushing it. And caller stated that she was totally (14Sep2020) done with it now, especially with COVID. Caller states that the doctor was going to just give her a pat on the back, and tell her that she is going to have to live with it or have surgery. Caller stated that this whole thing made her upset because she felt there was like no recourse, and she cannot get the bulge to go away. Caller had tried ice and hot packs and nothing works. I woke up feeling flu-like symptoms but without a cough or nasal symptom. My left arm was very swollen, hot, hard sore, and had some red areas on the bicep and tricep area, a couple spots about 2 inches in diameter. I had a fever varying within 100.5-101.7 and severe fatigue and weakness.   The reason I am writing is that I started having difficulty breathing. No wheezing, cough, pain, congestion BUT I felt that I need to exert a lot of effort to breath and take very deep breaths. I put on a finger oxygen saturation measuring device. It consistently read below 90%, getting as low as 78%. With conscious effort of breathing deeply, I could get it back up to 99%, but natural breathing had it drop below 90%. This lasted hours. The device is a Bodimetrics pulse/oxymeter that I have been using for years and have worn for many hours and never saw readings like this. I bought the device for exercise. I put on a new finger probe and got the same readings. After several hours, my readings returned to normal. this wasn't an instrument error, I think my oxygen dropped and it was related to symptoms and fever in an apparent reaction to Shingrix. My fever and most symptoms were gone after a day, but weakness persisted a few days, then I recovered.
LAB_DATA: None. I did not seek medical help.

Cytomegalovirus viremia; leukopenia; non-bloody, foul-smelling diarrhea; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of cytomegalovirus viremia in a 62-year-old female patient who received Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season) for prophylaxis.  The patient's past medical history included endometriosis, chronic kidney disease (received a deceased donor kidney transplant in 1998 that failed in March 2018 and was subsequently on hemodialysis) and upper respiratory tract infection. Previously administered products included anti-inflammatory drug with an associated reaction of chronic kidney disease, anti-thymocyte globulin, methylprednisolone and amoxicillin. Concurrent medical conditions included hypertension. Concomitant products included sulphamethoxazole, trimethoprim (Sulfamethoxazole + Trimethoprim) and valganciclovir.   In September 2019, the patient received Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season. On an unknown date, 7 days after receiving Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season and an unknown time after starting Sulfamethoxazole + Trimethoprim, the patient experienced cytomegalovirus viremia (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), leukopenia (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant) and diarrhea. The patient was treated with tacrolimus, prednisone, mycophenolate mofetil (Mmf), ganciclovir, letermovir and filgrastim. On an unknown date, the outcome of the cytomegalovirus viremia, leukopenia and diarrhea were unknown.   The reporter considered the cytomegalovirus viremia, leukopenia and diarrhea to be related to Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of cytomegalovirus viremia in a 62-years old female patient, who was vaccinated with unspecified influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. This case corresponds to patient-2 reported in this literature article. The patient had past medical history of endometriosis, hypertension, chronic kidney disease (likely from anti-inflammatory drug use for management of endometriosis) was being followed in the transplant nephrology clinic. The patient received a deceased donor kidney transplant in 1998 that failed in March 2018 and was subsequently on hemodialysis. The patient received a second renal transplant (re-transplant) from a deceased unrelated donor in June 2019. The Donor CMV status was CMV seropositive and the recipient CMV status was CMV seronegative. Induction immunosuppressive regimen included anti-thymocyte globulin, and methylprednisolone. Recent inflammatory disease processes (allograft rejection, infection) included upper respiratory infection. [The patient had an upper respiratory bacterial infection in the preceding months - these resolved completely with appropriate therapy].  Time period between transplant and inflammatory disease process was 1 month. Treatments for inflammatory disease processes included amoxicillin. Duration of inflammatory disease process was 1 week. The patient had no prior episodes of CMV reactivation. The patient was taking primary CMV prophylaxis. The patient had no recent increase in maintenance immunosuppressive regimen. Time period between transplant and presentation was 3 months. No information on patient's family history was provided. On an unspecified date at the end of September 2019, the patient received unspecified influenza vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided. On an unspecified date, 7 days (a week) after the vaccination, the patient's routine outpatient labs performed, and the patient was noted to have detectable CMV viral levels [4,983 IU/ml (3.70 log10 IU/ml)] without any symptoms. Prophylactic medications at the time of presentation included sulfamethoxazole-trimethoprim (SMX-TMP) single-strength (SS) 1 tablet oral (PO) every forty-eight hours (QOD) and Valganciclovir 450 mg every twenty-four hours (QD). The levels continued to rise over the course of two months [214,823 IU/ml (5.33 log10 IU/ml)] [lower limit of assay detection 60 IU/ml (1.78 log10 IU/ml)], with no improvement after switching from valganciclovir 450 mg QD to valganciclovir 900 mg QD. The patient was noted to have worsening leukopenia (WBC 1,260/cubic mm), so the patient was admitted for further management. On admission, the patient reported multiple episodes of non-bloody, foul-smelling diarrhea. The patient denied sick contacts, recent travel, medication changes or medication non-compliance. The patient's home medications consisted of tacrolimus ER 8 mg QD, prednisone 5 mg QD, MMF 1000 mg BID, sulfamethoxazole-trimethoprim single-strength tablet QOD, valganciclovir 450 mg QD. The patient was hemodynamically stable on examination. Physical examination revealed no abnormalities. Admission labs revealed WBC count 1,480/cubic mm (ANC 950/cubic mm and lymphocyte count 270/cubic mm [N: 1,000-3,300/cubic mm]), hemoglobin 11.1 g/dl (N: 13-17 g/dL), blood urea nitrogen (BUN) 20 mg/dL [N: 7-23 mg/dL], creatinine 1.53 mg/dl [N: 0.50-1.30 mg/dL], ALP 124 U/l. Chest radiograph revealed clear lungs. BK virus and Parvovirus B19 DNA PCR tests were negative. MMF and valganciclovir was held on admission. Infectious diseases service was consulted and the patient was started on renally-dosed intravenous (IV) ganciclovir (2.5 mg/kg QD) and letermovir 480 mg QD PO. Given the lack of response to outpatient valganciclovir therapy, a sample was sent for CMV resistance testing. With improvement in her creatinine clearance, the ganciclovir dosing was subsequently adjusted. WBC nadir during the hospital stay was 1,450/cubic mm (ANC 780/cubic mm), with subsequent recovery due to intravenous antivirals and one dose of filgrastim. CMV resistance tests revealed the presence of two different populations of virus - wild type and a strain exhibiting resistance at M460V and C603W (two out of seven mutations conferring resistance to ganciclovir). No resistance was noted to cidofovir or foscarnet. The patient was discharged on IV ganciclovir and oral letermovir. The final duration of therapy would be determined by outpatient follow-up with infectious diseases and transplant nephrology. The patient was to continue tacrolimus ER 3 mg QD PO and prednisone 5 mg QD PO at home. The outcome was control of CMV viremia and recovery of cell counts. Graft outcome was stable allograft function. This case has been considered as serious due to hospitalization.  The author commented, "There are multiple risk factors linked to CMV viremia and disease in solid organ transplant recipients (SOTRs) and after hematopoietic stem cell transplant. These include older age, female sex, blood group A, decreased creatinine clearance, allograft impairment, CMV serostatus prior to transplant (donor seropositive-recipient seronegative OR recipient seropositive), transplantation type, use of T-cell depleted stem cell grafts, use of anti-thymocyte globulin before transplant, and occurrence of graft-versus-host disease (GvHD). Vaccination has not been previously reported as a risk factor for CMV viremia. There is a paucity of data on the effects of influenza vaccination leading to viremia in solid organ transplant recipients. Thus, we reviewed the data available in human immunodeficiency virus (HIV)-infected patients, another subset of immunocompromised patients. The research on the effect of influenza virus on HIV replication has produced conflicting results. Some studies have shown that influenza vaccination results in increased HIV replication (and subsequently increased viremia) in patients with uncontrolled or partially controlled viral replication. Other studies have shown that vaccination did not result in increased HIV replication. In some transplant recipients, influenza-like illness has been reported after vaccination. SOTRs are maintained in a state of prolonged immunosuppression after transplant. Thus, there is a possibility that influenza vaccination may lead to transient increase in CMV viral load and subsequent viremia (similar to the transient viremia seen in HIV patients). Both patients had a temporal association of onset of CMV viremia with administration of the influenza vaccine. They were older females at high risk of CMV reactivation (donor CMV seropositive/recipient CMV seronegative). Patient 2 was on CMV prophylaxis, while patient 2 was not receiving valganciclovir (per our institutional protocol of CMV prophylaxis until six months post-transplant). They reported compliance with their home medications, with no recent increases in their maintenance immunosuppression. Patient 1 had an episode of antibody-mediated rejection, while patient 2 had an upper respiratory bacterial infection in the preceding months - these resolved completely with appropriate therapy. They had no concurrent inflammatory disease processes at the time of vaccination. Lab testing demonstrated high CMV DNA levels with concomitant leukopenia, neutropenia and lymphopenia. There were no additional factors identified to have contributed to CMV viremia. The CMV viremia was severe enough to warrant therapeutic antiviral therapy and changes in their immunosuppression regimen. We thus believe that CMV viremia resulted from the prior vaccination in our patients. One meta-analysis concluded that the influenza vaccine was associated with statistically significant protection against influenza-like illness in immunocompromised patients, including SOTRs. Through this case report, we wish to highlight the finding of CMV viremia occurring after influenza vaccination, with no other identified triggers. Further research and accumulation of cases is needed to investigate the strength of this association, to determine the mechanisms that resulted in CMV viremia and to recognize the risk factors leading to progression from viremia to clinically relevant CMV disease." The author concluded, "Vaccination may lead to transient viral replication in immunocompromised patients, such as HIV-infected patients (likely due to genetic and immune-mediated mechanisms). Similarly, we believe that influenza vaccination led to transient CMV viremia and CMV disease in our renal transplant recipients on potent immunosuppressive therapies. Further research is needed to assess the strength of this correlation, the mechanisms causing viremia and the risk of progression to clinical disease. Until then, clinicians must continue vaccination of SOTRs per the guidelines, but must also remember to enquire about recent vaccination when evaluating SOTRs with new onset CMV viremia." anaphylactic shock; Headache; Pain behind the right eye; Swollen joints; Weakness; Body rash; This case was reported by a pharmacist via call center representative and described the occurrence of anaphylactic shock in a 59-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) (batch number K735H, expiry date 20th September 2022) for prophylaxis. On an unknown date, less than 3 months after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced anaphylactic shock (serious criteria GSK medically significant and life threatening), headache (serious criteria life threatening), pain behind eyes (serious criteria life threatening), swollen joints (serious criteria life threatening), weakness (serious criteria life threatening) and generalized rash (serious criteria life threatening). The patient was treated with corticosteroid nos (Corticoids). On an unknown date, the outcome of the anaphylactic shock was unknown and the outcome of the headache, pain behind eyes, swollen joints, weakness and generalized rash were not recovered/not resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the anaphylactic shock, headache, pain behind eyes, swollen joints, weakness and generalized rash to be related to Shingrix. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt presented today for a flu immunization. She is accompanied by her mother and two younger brothers. All three received the Fluzone quadrivalent vaccine (NDC 49281-0633-15; LOT: UJ457AA; EXP: 6/30/21) provided by the program. She was seated. � Four minutes after administration pt stated "I don't feel good" and became unconscious. She then began seizing w/posturing and convulsions. RN was in the rm, called for assistance, and began seizure management. MD came into the room within 30 seconds and assisted with management. EMS was called. � Pt was tonic-clonic for ~45 seconds, and post-ictal for ~10 minutes. RN and MD stayed with the pt until she left via ambulance to hospital. � EMS obtained a BP of 93/56, BG of 84. Pt was A&Ox4 when EMS arrived. She only complained of fatigue. � Pt was able to walk unassisted to the ambulance and left the clinic in good condition.

Around 8 minutes after injections were given, patient stated she started having tingling in her mouth. Her primary care provider is located next door to the pharmacy. Pharmacist recommended her to be evaluated by provider. Pharmacy technician verified patient arrived and was being evaluated. Pharmacist attempted to call provider but was unable to get in contact over phone. Pharmacist was only pharmacist in building, so she could not leave the building. Pharmacy technician reported back that the patient was evaluated by primary care provider and her heart rate & oxygen levels were good. Provider recommended she come to the pharmacy and take 50mg of Benadryl and stay in the pharmacy for 30 minutes. Patient stated she started to feel light headed so she was recommended by pharmacy staff to go to the emergency room.  Pharmacist contacted local ER to notify patient was on her way, however, the provider saw her again and after some further discussion with the patient, he stated he believed it to be an anxiety driven reaction instead of an allergic reaction. Pharmacist also evaluated the patient and decided to go ahead and have patient take Benadryl and stay to be further evaluated at the pharmacy for a minimum of 30 minutes. Provider and patient agreed. Patient did not go to the emergency room. Patient took the Benadryl and came into the pharmacy for further evaluation. Pharmacist frequently checked status of patient. She stated after about ten minutes following Benadryl dose that the tingling was better but not completely gone. Twenty minutes following this, the provider came back over and evaluated the patient again. He listened to check for wheezing, which was not present. At this time, the patient reported to the pharmacist that the tingling in the mouth was gone. She did state that she had pain in the right arm at the injection site. The provider and pharmacist agreed that this was due from the injection itself. He cleared her to go home, but reminded patient to go to the ER if symptoms come back or if new symptoms appear. Pharmacist also added for her to contact the pharmacist if there are any changes or if she had any questions.  Patient's total evaluation time from injection to when she left with caregiver was almost 60 minutes. Patient went home with a caregiver.  Pharmacist contacted patient two hours following to check her status. She stated she still feels drowsy and her right arm is still sore. Pharmacist stated the drowsiness is a side effect of Benadryl and the soreness can happen due to getting an injection. Pharmacist will contact patient tomorrow to check on her status.
OTHER_MEDS: Olanzapine 20mg, Fluoxetine 60mg, Clonazepam 1mg (as needed), Cyclobenzapine 10mg (as needed)

She told me she wasn't in pain and this had happened to her before when she received a pneumonia vaccine. she had an infection; her arm was swollen; her arm was red; her arm was very painful; had a temperature of 99 degrees; couldn't move her arm for a couple of days; Information has been received from a 67 years old female patient referring to herself. The patient's concomitant medications included antibiotic, gliponide for heart rhythms and raloxifene hydrochloride (EVISTA) for bone density. The patient also received a flu shot and a pneumonia shot on the same day with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23).  On approximately 16-SEP-2020 (reported as about a week ago), the patient was vaccinated with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) (dose/frequency 1 (unit not provided), route of administration: injection; strength, lot # and expiration date were unknown) because she worked in healthcare and wanted to be careful with not getting sick, and wanted to keep her immune system strong.      On an unknown date in September 2020 (reported as last week), the patient had an extreme reaction to the vaccine. The patient had an infection and her arm was swollen and red, very painful, had a temperature of 99 degrees, and could not move her arm for a couple of days. The patient stated the pain and swelling was from the injection site all the way down to her wrist. The patient had to go to urgent care because of the side effects she was experiencing worsened, and while she was admitted they gave her an antibiotic to help with the reaction. The patient was wanting to know if there was certain ingredients in the vaccine that would be an indication that this was an allergic reaction or if it could have been cellulitis. All the events recovered in September 2020. The causality between all the events and pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) was assessed as related.
CUR_ILL: Allergic reaction to antibiotics; Arrhythmia; Bone density abnormal; Sulfonamide allergy

shingles rash on her buttocks and side of leg that was extremely painful; This initial spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a female patient of unknown age. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX),  she sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), Plaintiff has suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages.

Information was received on 17AUG2020 and 24AUG2020 from an Investigator.   A 55-year-old male developed satellite lesions after the administration of the open study drug (ACAM2000).  On 03AUG2020, the subject received the dose of the study drug. The subject reported that the scab from the inoculation site came off on 14AUG2020, and two other blisters also appeared later in the day. The site formed a new scab which appeared to have been removed. The two new blisters also appeared to have been popped up and their tops removed. The new blister � inch to the left of the initial site formed a scab. The blister 1/8 inch to the right of the initial site was slightly wet. No other information was provided at the time of the initial report.  Outcome: The outcome of the event was ongoing at the time of report.   The action taken with study drug was none.   The Investigator assessed the event satellite lesions as grade 1 (mild) and related to therapy with study drug.  Company Comment. In agreement with the investigator's assessment. Satellite lesion are considered when the lesions are located within 2.5  cm (1 in) of the vaccination site.  Despite it is not described in the label, this kind of complication are very common and considered listed. Satellite lesions are not required submission to the FDA.  Case will be kept in the database although it is from clinical trial and is not serious  Follow-up information was received on 08SEP2020: The follow-up information included update in outcome and SAE end date as described in the above narrative.  Outcome: The outcome of the event was reported as resolved on 30AUG2020.  Company Comment (18SEP2020): After review of the f/u information, the Company's assessment is unchanged with the event considered related to the study drug.; Sender's Comments: In agreement with the investigator's assessment. The patients were given FLUBLOK QUADRIVALENT rather than the intended FLUZONE QUADRIVALENT, no AE; Initial information was received on 15-Sep-2020 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case.  This case involves 140 patients who were given INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE [FLUBLOK QIV] rather than the intended INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B VACCINE [FLUZONE QUADRIVALENT] (wrong product administered).  Medical history, medical treatment(s), vaccination(s), concomitant medications and family history were not provided.   Between 08-Sep-2020 to 10-Sep-2020, the patients received a 0.5 ml dose of suspect INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE (lot QFAA2002, expiry date: 18-May-2021, strength: standard) once via intramuscular route in unknown administration site for prophylactic vaccination.  It was a case of an actual medication error due to wrong vaccine administered.  The nurse reports that the medical center ordered flu vaccines for both patients and staff. Both Flublok and Fluzone Quadrivalent were ordered. The plan was to administer the Fluzone Quadrivalent to staff and some patients and Flublok to other patients. But when flu vaccine administration began on 08-Sep-2020, Flublok was given to staff rather than the intended Fluzone. The discrepancy was discovered on 10-Sep-2020, when it was noted that the lot of the vaccine being administered was different from the one on pre-filled-out release forms for those vaccines. Between 08-Sep-2020 to 10-Sep-2020, 140 staff members (out of 3400 team members) had received the Flublok instead of the intended Fluzone.   At the time of report, the patients had no adverse event (AE) symptoms.  This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holder's compliance with the requirements set out in Directive 2001/83/EC and Module VI of the Good Pharmacovigilance Practices. The classification as a medical error is in no way intended, nor should it be interpreted or construed as an allegation or claim made by the marketing authorization holder that any third party has contributed to or is to be held liable for the occurrence of this medication error.

Patient fainted. Was quickly brought back to conscious and stabilized.

I did receive a Quadrivalent Flu shot vaccine though I have not been able to confirm which exact variety it was so I choose the first flu vaccine type in item 17 above.  This was my first time getting the flu vaccine ever, so the nurse administering had me wait an extra 20mins after the injecting to make sure I had no adverse side effects. I felt fine immediately after and throughout that day.  Being that I had virtually no symptoms I actually forgotten that I had been given a shot until later that night when my arm felt sore and I thought massaging it would help alleviate the soreness. After realizing that my soreness was actually the remnants of pain from the injection site, I stopped.   Though even after stopping I felt the pain in my arm slowly permeate to my other joints and made me feel very uncomfortable. Thinking that it might just be my body needing food/water since I hadn't had anything since noon. After making my way towards my kitchen it was only until I made it to the bottom of stairs that I knew something was off and I felt like I was going to faint.  It was pretty much a slow train wreck in that at first I was forced to sit down because I was light headed and dizzy, then my vision started closing in and I could hear the tea kettle whistle in my ear as I slowly lied down and momentarily passed out. Maybe only a minute or so later I was back up though still reeling from the experience. Broke out into a cold sweat thereafter but that is where most of the symptoms subsided and I was able to get up, talk coherently, and see things in front of me clearly .  The whole episode took maybe 15-20 mins. Though the uneasiness/slight joint pains remained with me until I went to bed that night at 10PM.
LAB_DATA: I choose not to seek medical attention but do plan on following up with a telemedicine visit.
ALLERGIES: Have had allergic reactions to drinks heavy with dyes, but have never confirmed what.

Neck swelling at dinner, feeling of swelling over entire left side by the end of the evening.  Severe pain.  I'd been told reaction may be minor, lasting 24-48 hours, nothing like what ensued.  By that evening I was unable to move or lift my head.  My husband had to hold my head and accompany me in order for me to get out of bed and go to the bathroom.  Pain severe.  Notified primary care physician.  Nothing I could take that I wasn't already taking.  Slept for 5 days with this pain.  Today, 9 days later, I still have residual neck pain and am unable to drive because of limited neck movement.  My research indicates I never should have been given this vaccine, having had RA, and telling the nurse this.  I even asked her why I needed the vaccine if I've had shingles as well as chicken pox, and she said there's a debate about that.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 12 hours after the injections (about 3 a.m.) , i developed a severe headache - behind my ear, shivering, and of course site injection pain.   This continued for several hours even after ibuprofen.  By that night at 8:30 p.m. (approximately 29 hours after the injection), my face started to swell.  When I woke the next morning, my face was extremely swollen - around my eyes - and hot to the touch.   I reported to my physician.  Went to the physician.  Obviously an allergic reaction - had an injection of steriods, taking ibuprofen and antihistamines.  As I report this, approximately 72 hours after injection, my face and periorbital area is still extremely swollen and slightly painful and still a headache.

Felt bad / malaise / how horrible she felt; Pain in her (right) shoulder; Arm was sore; Not feeling good in her head; not able to work; Intramuscular formulation administered by other route; Low energy; Vision has changed/deteriorated in 2 weeks; Cataracts atrelated / increasing size of cataracts; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of vision abnormal aggravated in a 54-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included INFLUENZA VIRUS VACCINE INACTIVATED (FLUZONE VACCINE) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included influenza (had flu twice) and shingles. Concurrent medical conditions included iron decreased, overweight, cataract (for 20-25 years), sinus disorder, vision decreased (patient's vision had gotten a lot worse since last year from the reporting date and her glasses were not helped) and contact lens wearer (patient wearing rigid gas permeable contact lenses).   On 17th August 2020 17:00, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On 17th August 2020, the patient received FLUZONE VACCINE. In August 2020, 2 weeks after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced vision abnormal aggravated (serious criteria GSK medically significant), cataract aggravated (serious criteria GSK medically significant), malaise, shoulder pain, energy decreased, pain in arm, feeling bad and activities of daily living impaired. On 17th August 2020, the patient experienced intramuscular formulation administered by other route. The patient was treated with ophthalmologicals (nos). Shingrix was discontinued. In September 2020, the outcome of the malaise, shoulder pain, pain in arm, feeling bad and activities of daily living impaired were recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the vision abnormal aggravated, cataract aggravated and energy decreased were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the intramuscular formulation administered by other route was unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the vision abnormal aggravated, cataract aggravated, malaise, shoulder pain, energy decreased, pain in arm, feeling bad and activities of daily living impaired to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient had reported the events for herself. The patient's (family history) grandmother had a history of ischemic stroke. The patient did not eat meat. The patient received 1st dose at pharmacy in right deltoid and she indicated that she would not be getting the second dose of the series. The patient was not sure if vaccine was given intramuscularly or not and she said she did not feel the injection as it was happened but about 24 hours later her right arm was sore. The patient received the Fluzone shot on the same day in her left arm and she was unable to find the Shingrix lot number on the paperwork but did provide the pharmacy's contact information, patient said that she felt bad for a week after receiving the Shingrix shot. The patient's symptoms started 24 hours after the shot and she said she had pain in her (right) shoulder and had malaise but was different from the flu.  The patient was not currently employed but stated that she did not think she would have been able to work due to how horrible she felt. It was 5 to 7 days before patient felt better from the reporting date. The reporter wanted to found out if Shingrix could cause change in vision, as per package Insert: optic ischemic neuropathy was reported in 3 subjects (0.02 percent) who received Shingrix (all within 50 days after vaccination) and 0 subjects who received placebo; available information was insufficient to determine a causal relationship with Shingrix. The reporter would like someone from GlaxoSmithKline to contact her new eye doctor. The reporter would have an appointment with this doctor on October 21, 2020 and she states she was between doctors right now.  The reporter went to an ophthalmologist and spent 400 Dollar there. The patient's vision had gotten a lot worse since last year from the reporting date and her glasses were not helped.  The patient had bad vision, vision had decreased, right eye was much worse, vision loss was continued to change, vision had changed/deteriorated in 2 weeks.  The reporter could not see out of her new glasses on the right side and vision loss was continued. The patent was 54 years old and healthy and she used to exercise for 1.5 hours per day but she had not been able to do that since the Shingrix shot due to low energy. The patient did blood work on the day of vaccination and the blood work showed that she had low iron. The patient did not felt good in her head and was unsure if the cause was sinuses or side effect from Shingrix vaccine that was also assiciated with previously reported vision changes. The patient's eye doctor informed consumer that the cataracts atrelated and are no longer dots or specs and they had became bigger than dots.  The reporter unsure if increased size of cataracts associated with Shingrix or not. The reporter wanted someone to contact her MD. SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 09/25/2020 at around 745pm, patient felt queasy after given two vaccines (Flublok and Boostrix) and fainted on the bench and hit his left side of the head. This was the first time the patient had received the flu vaccine.  Prior to administering the vaccine, patient was informed of the adverse effects of the vaccine. While discussing the adverse effects of the vaccine, patient did claim that he always gets queasy when getting a vaccine and or blood drawn.  After providing the vaccine, he started sweating and a couple minutes later fell over while seated on the bench and his left side of the head.  After being awoken, the patient was conscious and was able to  verbally speak.   At that time, he sat on the floor and was able to remove his mask.  Apparently, he had vomited and needed the mask removed.  While doing so, he also grabbed his phone and was able to text his friend. He was able to reach out to a friend who arrived several minutes later. Paramedics arrived and evaluated the patient to be okay.  Patient didn't want to go the emergency room.  As soon as his friend arrived, he was a lot better and complained of a headache.  His friend asked if there was a nearby urgent care.  I recommended nearby facility since they are opened 7 days a week.  On Wednesday  09/30/20 patient followed up with pharmacy.  Patient was seen by Urgent Care and CT scan and EKG were normal.  There was also no bleeding.  According to urgent care, his blood pressure had dropped causing him to faint.
LAB_DATA: CT scan and EKG (dates unknown) normal per patient

Patient states she tolerated the injection fine, then that evening went to a fitness class.  After the fitness class she was doing her usual stretching where she laid on the floor, crossed her arms across her body at the elbows and held the pose to stretch her back. She states she always does this stretch after her class.  When she released her stretch she immediately felt pain in the arm she had her injection in.  Pain that shot down to her wrist and then up to and through her shoulder, neck, and to her head.  She continued to feel this pain all night, it was not relieved by OTC NSAIDS and it kept her from sleeping.  She called the pharmacy the next day as her arm was still hurting, to the extent that she said she "couldn't do anything with it".  She states she has never had any adverse reaction to any other vaccine.  She is not one of our regular patients, but she did include on her VAR she had received a "regular flu shot" in the past 4 to 8 weeks.  It sounded like she went to a vigorous fitness class, but she said this was her normal class, and normal amount of physical exertion. she called to ask if she should contact her physician, and was told she could and should if the pain did not resolve with self-treatment, but it is unknown at this time whether she has sought out treatment.

Accidentally left Vivotif unrefrigerated for three days and then took two doses of unrefrigerated Vivotif on consecutive days; Accidentally left Vivotif unrefrigerated for three days and then took two doses of unrefrigerated Vivotif on consecutive days; Spontaneous report received on 24AUG2020.  Based on the information obtained from the female consumer two individual case safety reports 20000452SP (wife) and 20000453SP (husband) were created and cross-linked in the database.  The female consumer reported that she "accidentally left Vivotif unrefrigerated for three days and then took two doses of unrefrigerated Vivotif on consecutive days" (PT: Product storage error/Inappropriate schedule of product administration). She was receiving Vivotif (lot number: 3003320 and expiry date: Nov 2020) for immunization. She stated that Vivotif was left unrefrigerated for three days (Tuesday to Friday) at 72-degree Fahrenheit. She put back Vivotif in the refrigerator on Friday. Later, she took two unrefrigerated doses of Vivotif on consecutive days that was on 22AUG2020 and 23AUG2020, respectively. Action taken with Vivotif with respect to the reported events was not applicable. The outcome of the reported events was unknown.  Company Comment: A consumer accidentally left Vivotif unrefrigerated for three days and then took two doses of unrefrigerated Vivotif on consecutive days (product storage error, inappropriate schedule of product administration). Vivotif should always be stored in the refrigerator at the recommended temperatures and should be taken every other day. The causality of product storage error, and inappropriate schedule of product administration is assessed as not applicable to Vivotif due to the nature of the events which were due to human error.; Sender's Comments: A consumer accidentally left Vivotif unrefrigerated for three days and then took two doses of unrefrigerated Vivotif on consecutive days (product storage error, inappropriate schedule of product administration). The causality of product storage error, and inappropriate schedule of product administration is assessed as not applicable to Vivotif due to the nature of the events which were due to human error.

multiple, severe outbreaks of shingles across his body, including his face, which resulted in his eyes being swollen shut; multiple, severe outbreaks of shingles across his body, including his face, which resulted in his eyes being swollen shut; This spontaneous report has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a male patient of unknown age. The patient's concurrent conditions, medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. On or around 06-NOV-2012, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine (dose, route of administration, anatomical location, lot # and expiry date were not provided) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). On an unknown date, shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered multiple, severe outbreaks of shingles across his body, including his face, which resulted in his eyes being swollen shut. These injuries were caused by zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient's symptoms resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the vaccine. He also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of his condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence, he suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result, the patient suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the events was considered to be not recovered. The reporter considered the events to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).  The reporter determined the events to be disabling.  Upon internal review, the event of herpes zoster ophthalmicus was considered to be medically significant.

Patient came to employee health for flu vaccine. Patient states she has had a flu vaccine before and has not had any previous reaction. She denies having COVID or being exposed to COVID. Patient received vaccine and approximately 5 minutes later she complained of lightheadedness and dizziness. I had her sit down in a chair. About 15 minutes later, I had her try to stand up and walk along the hallway, using the wall for stability. She was able to get up and walk, but felt wobbly whenever she took her hand off the wall and took a few steps. She sat back down and was told to keep waiting it out to see if it gets better. About 45 minutes after the flu shot, I gave her a bottle of water. 1 hour and 15 minutes after the shot we had her try to get up and walk again, and she still used the wall for stability. Still feeling dizzy. 1 hour and 20 minutes after flu shot, she said she is feeling a little bit better. She drank her whole bottle of water, and at 1130, her supervisor told her to go ahead and go home since she has to stand for her whole shift and is not able to stand for the whole shift.   After complaining of initial symptoms, patient did note that she had episodes of vomiting on 9/28, which she says is possible food poisoning since the fridge has not been working correctly lately. NOTE:   Pharmacy received and gave 2020/2021 flu vaccine.  I was not given lot numbers or manufacturer.  1.  Two hours after shot, I had SLE rash and redness on my cheeks.  2. Within 4 hours after shot, I had hard, swollen red face tissue like hot frostbite near the SLE rash on my cheek. 3.  Within 24 hours after shot, my entire face was bright red, and my skin was clammy, but my temp stayed 98 F. 4.  I had painful headaches with pressure. 5.   Also within 24 hours, and for 2 days, I was vomiting and could not keep water or food down, and had some diarrhea.  I did NOT have any stomach pain, and had no other flu symptoms. 6.  Third Day after shot:   I woke up with pain in my right thigh that wouldn't go away, with a red rash that has been consistent in the past of x-rayed and diagnosed blood clots.  I again felt clammy and nauseated.  I treated with an extra aspirin, as my primary care was out today, and my Rheumatologist does not have time.  I was reluctant to go to ER for blood clot xray, as taking a chance on the blood clot was less of a threat than contracting COVID-19, given the spike in outbreaks.  Up through the day before the flu shot I had no symptoms and, as mentioned my immune system has been incredibly strong for the past 4 years.  I work full-time, and run 20 miles a week, including the night before the flu shot.  I have not had any of these symptoms for 4 years, before I was put on Plaquenil.  Because of the SLE rash, and red hard tissue 2 hours after the flu shot, and also because of the apparent blood clot, these are all indicators of a SLE flare-up for me that I have not had for 4 years.  Because of this, I believe that SLE, and APS secondary to SLE patients need to be cautioned on the flu virus.   There are about 100,000 SLE patients in this country, and 1/3 have APS secondary to SLE.  If those other SLE patients are not as healthy as I have been, if they have a SLE flare to the 2020/2021 flu vaccine like I did, they may have life-threatening organ damage/failure that would force them to seek ER.  If so, open beds is about nil right now.  Also, those other SLE (with APS) patients may not survive being in the hospital if they contract COVID-19 there.  It is also worth mentioning that I have never had a SLE flare with a flu shot before.  Although it may not matter, I also received a TB shot and booster 2/2020 with no adverse side affects.
OTHER_MEDS: Plaquenil, Enalapril, Multivitamin, Baby Aspirin (81 mg)
CUR_ILL: Not in flare up with SLE, and lab work has come back in remission of SLE for 4 years, including August 2020.  SLE and APS controlled by Plaquenil.
HISTORY: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), Antiphospholipid Syndrome (APS) Secondary to SLE, Reynaud's,

Patient and pharmacist discussed history of fainting with blood draws and vaccines in the patient's past, as well as family history of fainting in similar situations, and patient still wanted to receive vaccination. In preparation, patient purchased fruit drink to have for after administration and brought her husband with her in case of any fainting. Patient was walked through each step of the flu shot and process and was instructed to tell the pharmacist if she felt faint at any point during or after administration. Patient consented and received the flu vaccine with no incident. Pharmacist then instructed patient to remain seated as long as necessary in the chair and to notify the pharmacist as soon as she started feeling dizziness or feeling faint. Patient remained seated with her husband positioned right in front of her, drinking fruit juice. As pharmacist was walking out to check on patient, patient fainted and fell forward from the chair. Her husband attempted to catch her but patient slid off the chair and hit her head on floor in front of the pharmacy. Husband gently turned patient over and patient became conscious. Pharmacist noticed some blood and as husband moved patient's hair out of her face, pharmacist noted a small cut on the upper right side of patient's forhead. Pharmacist received husband's consent to called 911 and proceeded to call for an ambulance. Pharmacist also provided patient with gauze pads to apply pressure to the cut so patient would not bleed. Patient remained on the floor until EMTs arrived at the pharmacy, and patient was taken out of pharmacy on a wheelchair.
LAB_DATA: Patient has not checked back in with pharmacy yet, but patient's husband returned shortly after escorting the patient to the ambulance to update pharmacist that patient was feeling better. Pharmacist will touch base again with patient tomorrow for follow up.

I administered the vaccine at approximately 2:30pm. Patient stood up and fainted after taking a few steps. Her mother caught her, and we provided a chair to sit in. No head injury occurred. Water and Gatorade were provide immediately. The patient did not report any trouble breathing or present signs of anaphylaxis. She had a pale and clammy appearance, and described a brief loss of vision before the fall. The patient reported not having any water since previous night, and the only fluid was a yogurt drink after breakfast. Once she started feeling relief from the fluids, I took her blood pressure reading at 2:44pm, which was low (105/71). We continued to monitor her for signs of an allergic reaction, and took another blood pressure reading at 2:57pm (108/68). She stood up at 3:00pm, and we had her walk around the store to make sure she did not still feel faint. She left the store shortly after. Patient was also given a granola bar as well since she reported not having anything to eat today other than a yogurt drink for breakfast. She ate that in between blood pressure checks. I followed up with the patient at 5:00pm. She was doing fine and felt better after eating shortly after leaving the store.

A few hours after injection into my right deltoid muscle, my arm hurt so much I could not lift it. About 24 hours later, I had severe muscle and joint pains and developed a low-grade fever of 99 degrees (which normally would be insignificant, but my baseline temperature is typically about 96.8). I was exhausted, switched from hot to cold rapidly, and was in substantial pain throughout my entire body. My chronic vestibular symptoms (mainly dizziness) were exacerbated, and on day 3 I developed mild vertigo and had trouble with balance. My heart rate, which is normally tachycardic, became moreso - my heart rate is typically in the 80s lying down and 115 standing up; after the vaccine, it was 110 lying down and 150 standing up. My blood pressure lowed to 110/60. It is now four days since the injection; I spent most of the day unable to keep my eyes open. Muscle and joint pain is mostly gone, and my fever is back down to 98 degrees.
OTHER_MEDS: Percocet, Nortriptyline, Imitrex, Klonopin, Testosterone, Pregnenalone, DHEA, Finasteride, Flonase, Medical Marijuana, Levsin, Compazine, Flexeril, Nystatin, Ibuprofen, Diazepam, Aimovig, Melatonin, Vitamin D, Magnesium Malate, Psyllium Hus

I received the seasonal influenza vaccine from my employer while at work on the early morning of November 20, 2019. Later that night I developed moderate abdominal pain, decreased appetite, and bloating that persisted for several days.  On November 23, 2019 I went to urgent care, had labs drawn, and was sent home. On the morning of November 24 I received a call from the urgent care center regarding my lab-work, instructing me to go to the emergency department because my labs revealed pancreatitis. I went to the emergency department as instructed and was diagnosed with acute pancreatitis. Since November of 2019 I have had ongoing issues with abdominal pain and flare-ups of pancreatitis.
LAB_DATA: November 23 - Urgent Care: Elevated lipase (1620) November 24 - Emergency Department: Elevated lipase (1830), CT Scan revealed pancreatic inflammation March 16: abdominal pain, lipase elevated (575), CRP elevated April 20: MRCP  done - showed main pancreatic duct changes, fluid around the lungs, splenomegaly

After 3 minutes patient was assisted to sitting position but states she was beginning to feel nauseous and was assisted to laying position again. After 3 minutes patient's friend brought water and a granola bar and patient was assisted to a sitting position. Patient stated she had not eaten anything that day. After eating and drinking patient sat for another 10 minutes and did not complain of any additional symptoms.

Urgent care sent me to the ER where I had another covid-19 test, blood work, head ct, chest xray and urinalysis.  All come back negative. Went home and slept for about 5 days straight, fever finally broke, double vision went away, but still had extreme nausea, muscle aches and fatigued very easily. Slowly getting better a month later, have lost between 15-20 pounds. Don't have much of an appetite, some muscle aches and fatigue still happening, but every day is a little bit better.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After the patient received both vaccines, he turned white and became sweaty. The wife said he passed out, but I did not witness that event. He kept closing his eyes, so I brought him a bottle of water, a cool paper towel for his forehead, and suckers to keep him active. I talked to him constantly and made him continue answering my questions. I checked his blood pressure and it was initially 74/58. I called the store manager and he helped me observe the patient. The patient said the flu shot didn't bother him, but it was the shingles vaccine. His wife was there and was helping us keep him coherent. I checked his blood pressure two more times and it was 81/62, then 105/68. I did not want them to leave until his blood pressure increased further, but he insisted he felt better and that they had somewhere to go. The color did return to his face and he was able to hold a lengthy conversation with the store manager. He remained in the same chair the majority of the time, and was then transferred to a wheel chair. The store manager wheeled him to his vehicle. The whole incident took about 60 minutes.
LAB_DATA: Blood pressure initial: 74/58 81/62 105/68 This was over a span of 60 minutes
PRIOR_VAX: After the event, the wife stated he always passes out during immunizations. This was not indicated on his Immunization Consent F

Fever, chills, aches, loss of appetite, severe pain and redness on right arm.  Symptoms of fever, chills and loss of appetite lasted from date of vaccine until 10/3/2020. Fatigue and aches is still present. Hives and swelling showed up on my right arm on 10/2/2020. Hives presented as stripes and by 10/3/2020 had combine into one large hive/rash on arm. A week or so after the vaccination, patient started with a rash on the top of his feet, it quickly spread to his forehead. Then about each day thereafter it spread like wildfire and into red raised bumps. His soft skin turned into what felt like a heavy grain sandpaper. He was crying all of the time, couldn't sleep, itched like crazy and seemed to be in pain. He also developed a fever for multiple days. The rash covered his entire body, even his groin area. This very adverse reaction looked exactly like measles and lasted three and a half weeks. It was absolutely horrid for a baby and parents to go through.
LAB_DATA: No one took any labs or tests or swabs etc. Every single doctor kept saying they didn't know what was going on and no one would admit it was the vaccine! I took him back to clinic, to Hospital ER, to another Hospital ER and finally to a naturopath. The Naturopath was the only one who has the decency and knowledge to say it looks and feels like measles and is from the live vaccine. She made up a topical cream and some supplements to help his little body expel the virus and he finally started to clear up a day later, which took an additional week to get back to normal. The rash on his head literally lasted another 3 months! Although it was much less noticeable, it was still there, it was so long I thought it was going to be permanent.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: feeling tired; feeling of melancholy was described as a feeling of rejection / escalated following both injections.; stomach issues / as a feeling of / being hungover / though she didn't drink alcohol; feeling of rejection; The blood in the stool presented after the 1st dose; stomach issues / described as a feeling of motion sickness; loose stool; headache; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of blood in stool in a 60-year-old female patient who received SHINGRIX for prophylaxis.   On 30th July 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of SHINGRIX. On 31st July 2020, 1 days after receiving SHINGRIX, the patient experienced headache. In August 2020, the patient experienced blood in stool (serious criteria GSK medically significant), motion sickness and loose stools. On an unknown date, the patient experienced tiredness, feeling blue, hangover effect and feelings of worthlessness. On an unknown date, the outcome of the blood in stool was unknown and the outcome of the headache, tiredness, feeling blue, hangover effect, motion sickness, loose stools and feelings of worthlessness were recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the blood in stool, headache, tiredness, feeling blue, hangover effect, motion sickness, loose stools and feelings of worthlessness to be related to SHINGRIX.  Additional details were provided as follows: The received SHINGRIX in left arm.  The patient experienced the same symptoms. The headache and feeling tired presented the day after the vaccination. A feeling of melancholy was described as a feeling of rejection. She was supposed to see her doctor for a physical and then was told she would not see her doctor but would receive the vaccine by a nurse. It left her feeling rejected and that feeling escalated following both injections. The stomach issues were described as a feeling of motion sickness or being hungover even though she didn't drink alcohol. The blood in the stool presented after the 1st dose only. The loose stool presented after both.  The stomach issues presented 2 to 3 days following both vaccines.  The reporter consent to follow up. healthy 2 m.o. who presented 10/1 with emesis, fever, and bloody diarrhea.   had emesis of every bottle he had that was NBNB. He was seen by his PCP who gave a script for AUS and told mom to present to ED if course worsened. He was then febrile to Tmax 100.6 rectally and began having bloody diarrhea so mom took him to ED.   At  hopsital his workup was notable for rotavirus positive and an abdominal ultrasound showing RLQ intussusception. He was transferred to for further workup.  In the ED here, he remained afebrile. Lactate was 1.5. He was ordered for cefoxitin but this was discontinued before he received it. He received a lactated ringers bolus and was started on mIVF with d5 normal saline.  US intestines with thickening of the wall of the cecum and the terminal ileum and edema and thickening of the ileocecal valve are which in transverse plane resembles appearance of a small intussusception. There is no ileocolic intussusception at the time of the examination.  He transitioned off IV fluids and discharged home 10/3.
LAB_DATA: Lactate 1.5  10/2 US Intestines: FINDINGS:  There is thickening of the wall of the cecum and the terminal ileum and  edema and thickening of the ileocecal valve are which in transverse plane  resembles appearance of a small intussusception. There is no ileocolic  intussusception at the time of the  examination.   Small amount of ascites in the right upper quadrant or right lower  quadrant. Multiple lymph nodes (series 32) seen throughout the abdomen.  Incidentally visualized bladder is unremarkable. Incidentally visualized  liver and right kidney are unremarkable.   IMPRESSION:  No ileocolic intussusception at the time of the ultrasound examination.  Thickening of the cecum and terminal ileum wall and the ileocecal valve  and may reflect sequelae of viral infection or prior and spontaneously  reduced intussusception (which is very unusual at this young age).

elevated liver enzymes; pancreatitis; severe epigastric pain; severe pain in her lumbar and sacral region; inflammatory arthritis; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of pancreatitis in a 61-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.
