On 6th February 2020, 2 days after receiving Shingrix and not applicable after starting Amoxicillin, the patient experienced sacral pain and inflammatory arthritis. On an unknown date, the patient experienced pancreatitis (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), elevated liver enzymes (serious criteria hospitalization) and epigastric pain. The patient was treated with ibuprofen (Advil). The action taken with Amoxicillin was unknown. The action taken with Tylenol #3 was unknown. On an unknown date, the outcome of the pancreatitis and inflammatory arthritis were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the elevated liver enzymes, sacral pain and epigastric pain were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the pancreatitis, elevated liver enzymes, sacral pain, inflammatory arthritis and epigastric pain to be related to Shingrix. It was unknown if the reporter considered the pancreatitis, elevated liver enzymes and epigastric pain to be related to Amoxicillin.  Additional details were reported as follows : The patient received Shingrix vaccine in her right deltoid intramuscularly and about two days later she had severe pain in her lumbar and sacral region, more towards the right compared to the left, and was diagnosed with inflammatory arthritis of the lumbar and sacral region by an orthopedic doctor. The patient was on Advil for her pain 600 mg every 6 hours. The orthopedic doctor prescribed Tylenol #3. The patient was having sinus infection and was on amoxicillin. So she took amoxicillin and one dose of Tylenol # 3 and after 2 hours customer started to experience severe epigastric pain and she was hospitalized with pancreatitis for 2 days with elevated liver enzymes and the pancreatitis resolved in 2 days. The inflammatory arthritis resolved in 3 days. The patient's had past medical history of herpes simplex and was on valacyclovir and did not know if she experienced the inflammatory arthritis because she had a diagnosis of herpes simplex. The patient did not receive second dose of the Shingrix vaccine yet. The reporter consented to follow up.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Imm rec'd 9/23/2020.  Called office on 9/25 complaining of fever of 102.5 and vomiting. Advised to go to ED where dx with Left arm cellulitis and admitted
LAB_DATA: ED notes Hospital Course:  � Patient received flu vaccine and pneumococcal vaccine 2 days prior to presentation.  About 36-48 hours after injection started having fever redness swelling to left arm.  She also had increased pain tenderness to that area.  Patient was given ceftriaxone and Cleocin, IV fluids, admitted to medical floor for suspicion of cellulitis to left arm.  Patient has significant leukocytosis 29,000, no febrile episodes during hospital stay.  Labs were monitored along with vital signs remained hemodynamically stable. � Blood cultures obtained negative prior to discharge, urine culture showed mixed organism colic on his a shin.  Patient's arm did improve with IV antibiotics.  Patient does have chronic kidney disease with creatinine roughly 1.5.  She was given hydration during the hospital stay and creatinine 1.3 prior to discharge. � Patient had improvement to cellulitis to left arm with decrease erythema warmth tenderness and induration. White count improved to 17000 no fever.  Still not sure if true cellulitis versus a marked inflammatory response from the injection.  In any event she is clinically improving with antibiotics and will continue same. � She will see the dose of ceftriaxone prior to discharge and continue with Cleocin as an outpatient 5 days.  She should follow up with PCP next week. �

SYMPTOM_TEXT: During receiving his shots he screamed and cried louder than any other time in the past.  He cried for about 2 hours straight afterwards.   Once home, he complained how bad it was hurting. The swelling increased about every hour on his left arm where the shots were put in.  He could not lift his arm up AT ALL. It was as red as a firetruck, tender to touch and burning hot.  His entire shoulder and upper arm swelled up 3x the normal size.  I brought him back to the Pediatrician office the very next day. The nurse gasped and put her hand over her mouth when she saw his arm. The doctor came in and said this was normal and it happens all the time . He stated to just give him benadryl and Tylenol or ibuprofen for pain. And said if his arm is not better in 2 weeks to bring him back.   He had little to no movement of his left arm for 2 weeks. It also took 2 weeks for the swelling to even START to go down.  Not only that, but he is now traumatized and petrified to go to the doctors since this happened.
LAB_DATA: 10/22/19 seen for injury and given medical advice how to manage.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient had an appointment on September 29, 2020 for administration of the rotavirus vaccine and the flu vaccine. We accidentally performed a full 6-month physical exam that included the administration of the following vaccines: Pediarix, Prevnar, Influenza, and Rotavirus.  The patient, however, had already had his 6 month old physical examination on 08/04/2020 and had also received the Pediarix and Prevnar13 vaccines on that date. Rotavirus and flu vaccines were still pending at that time.  Immediately after the error was discovered (same day - 09/29/2020)  the office manager, proceeded to call the vaccine manufacturers (Pfizer and GSK) to report the incident and ask for recommendations and advice to see what steps to take following the incident. After they received the case, they called back and indicated that they had no reported cases of adverse reactions to a vaccine when an extra dose was accidentally administered. Mother and I have been in contact to discuss possible side effects of the vaccines.  MD VFC and and Health Department were also contacted to report the incident. Patient has been and is currently doing well. No high fever and patient's behavior is normal. There is only a small lump on the injection site.  A formal office incident report has been filed, as well as proactive training measures to ensure incidents such as these do not happen again in the future.
Patient reports red area with firm center that is a little larger than a quarter to injection site. Area is painful with palpation.

CERVICAL LYMPHADENOPATHY; LUPUS; ARTHRALGIA; FEVER; PREGNANCY; This case was reported by a nurse and described the occurrence of lupus in 25-year-old female patient who was vaccinated with hepatitis B vaccine (Engerix-B) for prophylaxis.   The patient's medical history included four previous pregnancies producing four normal, full-term infants.  There was no history of gout, psoriasis, Crohn's disease, or Lyme disease.  Concurrent conditions and medications were not reported.  On 25 March 2003, the patient received her first dose of Engerix-B.  Her last menstrual period began on 02 April 2003, seven days post-immunization.  On 09 April 2003, 15 days post-immunization, the patient presented to the physician with arthralgia and "high" fever.  She also developed cervical lymphadenopathy.  She was seen by a physician, who observed swollen and warm joints (affected joints not specified).  The reporter stated, "It was suspected at one point that the patient had viral meningitis, and she was treated accordingly".  However, treatment was not specified.  The patient was hospitalized twice in April 2003.  It was subsequently determined that the patient was pregnant; date of the positive pregnancy test was not provided.  The events persisted as of 09 June 2003.  The reporting nurse considered the events to be possibly related to Engerix-B administration.  On 03 July 2003, the nurse reported that it was discovered that the patient "is positive for lupus."  The most recent information was received on 11 July 2003.  The pregnancy and lupus were ongoing.  The patient's estimated date of delivery is 11 November 2003.  The reporter stated that the pregnancy is "very high risk" because of lupus.   Upon internal review following correction was performed on 28th September 2020: This case was considered as pregnancy lost to follow up.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Pregnancy (four previous pregnancies producing four normal, full-term infants.)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: scab from the Shingrix injection; nerve pain; can't lay down in bed; whole left arm from her elbow to her shoulder are in pain; whole left arm from her elbow to her shoulder are in pain; whole left arm from her elbow to her shoulder are in pain; she has been sleeping in a recliner chair; needle hit a nerve during the administration/inserted too high or too low or too deep; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of injection site scab in a 65-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Concurrent medical conditions included chronic kidney disease stage 3 and diabetes mellitus.   On 15th July 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular) .5 ml. On 15th July 2020, unknown after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced vaccine administered at inappropriate site. On an unknown date, the patient experienced injection site scab, nerve pain, mobility decreased, pain in arm, shoulder pain, pain in elbow and sleep disturbance. The patient was treated with paracetamol (Tylenol). On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site scab, nerve pain, mobility decreased, pain in arm, shoulder pain, pain in elbow and sleep disturbance were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the vaccine administered at inappropriate site was unknown.   The reporter considered the injection site scab and nerve pain to be related to Shingrix. It was unknown if the reporter considered the mobility decreased, pain in arm, shoulder pain, pain in elbow and sleep disturbance to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were reported as follows: On 15th July 2020, patient received 1st dose of Shingrix 0.5 ml (intramuscularly) in the left deltoid at her pharmacy. Patient stated that ever since then she could not lay down in bed because within 5 to 10 minutes her whole left arm from her elbow to her shoulder was in pain, the pain starts slowly and gradually increases and after an hour of laying down the pain was so intense and sharp that she had been sleeping in a recliner chair instead of a bed. Patient visited her primary care physician and well as an orthopedic doctor and she had X-rays done and an ultrasound done. Physician think that the needle hit a nerve during the administration of the Shingrix vaccine because it was inserted too high or too low or too deep and the patient thinks that it was an error on the part of her pharmacy, which led to vaccine administered at inappropriate site. patient states that they were going to send her for physical therapy because they say this nerve pain could go on for months or even years. Patient stated she had the scab from the Shingrix injection, and it was about 4 to 5 inches below the shoulder line. Patient had been taking therapy with Tylenol, but she says that the Tylenol did not touch the pain.  Patient said physician want to prescribe a different medication for pain, but she had pre-existing conditions (stage 3 kidney disease, diabetes) which prevent her from being able to take certain medications. Patient said that her local pharmacy had reported this adverse event to their corporate office, and it was the corporate office who asked her to contact GSK. On 17th September 2020, patient received flu shot in her right arm and had no problem. Patient said she was scared to get the 2nd Shingrix shot. Patient mentioned that she did not like wearing a mask because they cause her to get a panic attack. The reporter consented to follow-up.

atrial fibrillation; giant cell arteritis/fatigue, weight loss; nerve pain; Information has been received from a lawyer concerning a case in litigation and refers to a patient of an unknown age and gender. No information regarding the patient's medical history, concurrent conditions and concomitant medications was provided. On or about 06-JAN-2014,  the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine (dose, route of administration, vaccination site, lot # and expiry date were not specified) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). On an unknown date, shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, the patient suffered from nerve pain, fatigue, weight loss, atrial fibrillation and was diagnosed with giant cell arteritis. As a direct and proximate result of the Company's defective zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient's symptoms have resulted in physical limitation not present prior to using the Company's product. The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of the patient's condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence of the Company's wrongful conduct, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of the Company's conduct, the patient has suffered and incurred damages, including medical expanses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the events was not recovered. The causality was related.  The events of atrial fibrillation, nerve pain and giant cell arteritis were considered to be disabling.  Upon internal review, the event of atrial fibrillation was considered to be medically significant.

Yesterday, 10/4/20, I went back to the pharmacy and spoke with the pharmacist.   The pharmacist said I should file a complaint, as well as make an apt with my doctor. When I asked if I could speak with the young man you gave me the shot, she said "he is no longer with the pharmacy.      I have made an apt with my doctor and will know more but this is absolutely without any doubt from the shot.     I am 65 on no medications, very healthy, play golf, tennis, ski, hike.    I currently am unable to lift my arm or pull it behind me.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 2 weeks after the second dose, patient started having muscular pain on both sides of her back, light headaches and pressure on both sides of her ribs. Patient had constant dizziness sometimes characterized by a strong spinning sensation. Patient had the need to urinate frequently.  8 weeks later, on May 14th, 2020 the level of pain increased. Patient had stabbing pain around her ribs and upper abdomen. Patient felt inflammation around her upper abdomen. She went to urgent care that night. 2 days later on May 16th, patient went to the ER because pain was severe and her legs were very week. ER conducted a CT scan, blood test, X-ray; doctors did not find ?anything serious?. After this week patient suffered from insomnia. Patient felt organs were heavy causing discomfort and pain when she laid down. Patient had to sleep sitting up in her bed. Patient had muscle spasms around her abdomen.  On June, patient?s headaches were much stronger. Patient started taking muscle relaxants (cyclobenzaprine, 5 mg - 3 tablets per day) which helped decreasing the upper abdominal pain and headaches; Vitamin B (B-Complex 1 tablet per day) and B-12 (3,000 mcg 1 tablet per day). However, patient still had pain around her ribs.  At the end of July patient?s abdominal pain increased. Patient felt inflammation on her upper abdominal area. She could not stand up straight because of her pain in her abdomen.  Patient saw a Neurologist in late July who ordered an MRI of her thoracic spine; the results were normal. Patient saw a neurologist who specializes in chronic virus infections of the nervous system and virus latency in early August. Doctor prescribed Vitamin D, 2000 IU and Valacyclovir 1 g 3 times per day for 14 days in case the Varicella virus was active due to the vaccine. Doctor ordered blood tests of immune function and virology of varicella while patient was taking Valacyclovir. Tests results were normal.  In September, patient saw another neurologist who ordered another blood tests and MRI of her brain and cervical spine. Results were normal.  Patient started to recover in late September. In late December patient saw another Neurologist who specializes in Neuroimmunology. Doctor indicated that symptoms coincided with a condition called transverse myelitis. He indicated that MRIs might look normal with this condition. The way to identify an inflammation of the spinal cord would be through a lumbar puncture and test the spinal cord fluid. Patient was feeling better at that time and did not want to get tested.  Patient recovered by the end of December 9 months after the first symptoms started.
LAB_DATA: Patient saw many doctors while she was suffering from this condition. However, doctors were not familiar with this condition and did not conduct the right tests. MRIs and blood tests ordered were normal.   When patient finally visited a doctor who specializes in neuroimmunology, the doctor indicated that MRIs might look normal with this condition. The way to identify an inflammation of the spinal cord would be through a lumbar puncture and test the spinal cord fluid. Patient was feeling better at that time and did not want to get tested.   Even though there was no test that confirmed that this condition was triggered by the vaccine, patient believes the vaccine was the cause of this condition and for this reason wanted to report it. According to Agency, transverse myelitis may be due to an autoimmune reaction to a viral or bacterial infection. It also indicates that Transverse Myelitis often develops following viral infections such as varicella zoster (the virus that causes chicken pox and shingles), herpes simplex, cytomegalovirus, Epstein-Barr, influenza, echovirus, HIV, hepatitis A, and rubella.
OTHER_MEDS: Synthroid 125 mcg daily Vitamin C 1000 mg daily

PT STATES SITE WAS WARM AND HAS BEEN LIKE THAT AFTER ADMINSTRATION AND ALMOST A WEEK AFTER

Beginning around 1 to 2 hours after the injections, my left shoulder became very sore and felt weak. Painful to the slightest touch or pressure. At bedtime, I was unable to lie on my side (left or right, although left was much more sore). I awoke after about one hour of sleep with a powerful urge to urinate, and then four more times through the night at approximate one hour intervals. Chills and nearly uncontrollable shivering. I felt lethargic and feverish starting that night and for the next 2 days. Also headache and body aches. Fever of 99.4 degrees on Saturday. Symptoms subsided by Sunday afternoon.

4 days of symptoms and counting. Chills, fever, malaise, weakness, joint pain, overall body pain. Chills and fever started four hours after shot was administered. Next day, muscle/joint pain, continued high fever and chills. . My wife, same age, got the same Fluzone Highdose 10 minutes before me at the same location and no symptoms.
PRIOR_VAX: Fluzone Highdose, September 29, 2019

Mistakenly took two doses of Vivotif one after the other on the same night; Spontaneous report received on 16JAN2020.  Based on the information obtained from the nurse two individual case safety reports PVX2020-120 (wife) and PVX2020-121 (husband) were created and cross-linked in the database.  In this case, a female consumer "mistakenly took two doses of Vivotif one after the other on the same night" (PT: Accidental overdose) while being on Vivotif capsule for immunisation. On 15JAN2020, she mistakenly took two capsules of Vivotif. She had taken her own last capsule, and then her husband's last capsule after returning from the restroom as she had forgotten that she already took her last dose. Action taken with Vivotif with respect to the reported event was not applicable. The outcome of the reported event was unknown.  Company Comment: A consumer took her last vivotif dose and then mistakenly took her husband's vivotif dose on the same night (Accidental overdose). Further details on the outcome of the event is limited. Considering the nature of the event, the causality of accidental overdose is assessed as not applicable to vivotif.; Sender's Comments: A consumer took her last vivotif dose and then mistakenly took her husband's vivotif dose on the same night (Accidental overdose). Further details on the outcome of the event is limited. Considering the nature of the event, the causality of accidental overdose is assessed as not applicable to vivotif.

was sick / He was laying in bed; flu like symptoms; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of sickness in a child male patient who received Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2018-2019 season) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2018-2019 season. On an unknown date, less than 4 months after receiving Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2018-2019 season, the patient experienced sickness and flu-like symptoms. On an unknown date, the outcome of the sickness and flu-like symptoms were recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the sickness and flu-like symptoms to be related to Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2018-2019 season.  Additional details were reported as follows: The case was reported by patient's mother. The age at vaccination was not reported. The reporter reported that the patient was sick for 2 days with Flu like symptoms which lasted 36 hours in 2018 after receiving the flu vaccine manufacturer unknown. The patient was lying in the bed saying that he had to went to the hospital. The reporter consented to follow up.

arm swelling; Injection site pain; redness; heat to the touch from her elbow to her shoulder; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of extensive swelling of vaccinated limb in a 67-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (SHINGRIX) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included PNEUMONIA VACCINE for prophylaxis.   On 28th July 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of SHINGRIX and PNEUMONIA VACCINE. On 28th July 2020, less than an hour after receiving SHINGRIX, the patient experienced extensive swelling of vaccinated limb, injection site pain, erythema and feeling hot. The patient was treated with ibuprofen and non-drug therapy (Cold Compress). On 30th July 2020, the outcome of the extensive swelling of vaccinated limb, injection site pain, erythema and feeling hot were recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the extensive swelling of vaccinated limb, injection site pain, erythema and feeling hot to be related to SHINGRIX.  Additional details were reported as follows: The patient received a dose of SHINGRIX and pneumonia vaccine in her left arm on the same day. She stated that she developed injection site pain, arm swelling, redness and heat to the touch from her elbow to her shoulder within one hour of receiving these vaccines.  The symptoms resolved two days later after she treated herself with ibuprofen and cold compresses.  The reporter had no information for the pneumonia vaccine. The reporter consented to follow up.

14 year old patient was given Infanrix instead of Adacel/ NO AE; Initial information received on 21-Sep-2020 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case from a other health professional .  This case involves a 14-years-old female patient who received once dose of DIPHTHERIA VACCINE TOXOID, PERTUSSIS VACCINE ACELLULAR 3-COMPONENT, TETANUS VACCINE TOXOID [INFANRIX] (lot number: G5BE3, expiry date: 25-May-2021, via an unknown route in the left deltoid instead of DIPHTHERIA-2/TETANUS/5 AC PERTUSSIS VACCINE [ADACEL] (lot number, expiry date not reported) (wrong product administered) on 16-Sep-2020 for prophylactic vaccination.  The patient's medical history, past medical treatment, and family history were not provided. There was no history of vaccination prior to this dose.  No concomitant medications or no other vaccines were used.  It was an actual medication error case due to wrong vaccine administered.(latency: same day)  At the time of reporting, no adverse event was reported.  This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holder's compliance with the requirements set out in Directive 2001/83/EC and Module VI of the Good Pharmacovigilance Practices. The classification as a medical error is in no way intended, nor should it be interpreted or construed as an allegation or claim made by the marketing authorization holder that any third party has contributed to or is to be held liable for the occurrence of this medication error.

Previously administered products included Shingrix (1st dose received on 1st October 2019, No adverse reactions reported for this dose).   On 17th August 2020, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. On 17th August 2020, unknown after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced drug dose administration interval too long. In September 2020, the patient experienced neck pain (serious criteria hospitalization), pain in hip (serious criteria hospitalization), buttock pain (serious criteria hospitalization), pain in thigh (serious criteria hospitalization), groin pain (serious criteria hospitalization) and wheelchair user. On 23rd September 2020, the patient experienced rheumatoid arthritis (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant). The patient was treated with analgesic, nos (Pain Killer) and steroids nos (Steroids). On an unknown date, the outcome of the rheumatoid arthritis was not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the neck pain, pain in hip, buttock pain, pain in thigh and groin pain were recovering/resolving and the outcome of the wheelchair user was recovered/resolved and the outcome of the drug dose administration interval too long was unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the rheumatoid arthritis, neck pain, pain in hip, buttock pain, pain in thigh, groin pain and wheelchair user to be related to Shingrix. The patient was treated in the ER several times.  The dates provided were 12th,13th 18th and 19th September 2020.  She received IV fluids, pain killers and steroids during those visits. She was admitted to the hospital for one overnight stay on 23rd September 2020 and was diagnosed with rheumatoid arthritis at that time. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Swelling on neck was hard / swelling size of a large jelly bean and than to a size if thumb in lenght; Neck that was really sore and tender; swollen node moved or another node has become swollen that is located near jawbone or ear; Injection hurt pretty bad; aches/ Body aches and pain; Sore arm; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of injection site pain in a 72-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included breast cancer and fibromyalgia.   On 16th September 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix and the 1st dose of Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season (intramuscular). In September 2020, immediately after receiving Shingrix and Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season, the patient experienced pain in arm. On 16th September 2020, the patient experienced injection site pain and general body pain. On 23rd September 2020, the patient experienced neck swelling, neck pain and enlargement of lymph nodes. The action taken with Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season was unknown. On 20th September 2020, the outcome of the injection site pain, general body pain and pain in arm were recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the neck swelling and neck pain were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the enlargement of lymph nodes was unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the injection site pain, general body pain, pain in arm, neck swelling, neck pain and enlargement of lymph nodes to be related to Shingrix and Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season.  Additional details were reported as follows: The patient's medical history included breast cancer. The patient received 1st dose of Shingrix and an unknown name of the high dose flu shot for seniors for both on left arm. Due to history of breast cancer, it was advised not to receive vaccines on right arm. The patient reported the injection hurt pretty bad and that began to ache that evening, but woke up the next day with severe aches. The patient believed severity might also been attributed to fibromyalgia. The body aches and pain and sore arm completely resolved on 20th September 2020. 7 days after vaccination, there was swelling on left side of neck that was really sore and tender. The patient reported that swelling started off as the size of a larger jelly bean and then expanded to the size of a thumb in length. Initially the swelling on neck was hard but now it had reportedly gotten softer. The patient suspects that the swollen node moved or another node became swollen that was located near jawbone or ear. The patient was concerned due to history od breast cancer and the involvement of two lymph nodes on arm during that battle. The patient reported never developed a fever and not felt bad. The reporter consented to follow up.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Breast cancer; Fibromyalgia

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt vitals stable prior to vaccination. Per father consent form was signed and confirmation was established that patient had never had an allergic reaction or side effect to vaccinations in the past.  Pt was administered vaccines at approximately 11:15, after 10 minutes at about 11:25 patient experienced some nausea, dizziness and lightheadedness. Patient experienced possible vasovagal syncope, Patient was placed in a supine position as she was able to take deep breaths of alcohol pads, patient did not lose consciousness and remained oriented to self, place and time. Patient responded to instructions and Vital signs at time of episode was BP: 100/62 Pulse 69 O2 98%. Pt denies Shortness of breath, chest pain, chest pressure, throat closure, or chest wheezing. Patient progressively improved as she stated dizziness and lightheadedness resolved at approximately 11:40 with 98% 02 and 100 pulse rate. At 1130 the blood pressure was improved at 110/72. Pt improved and was able to drink water and denied any further issues. patient was monitored for over an hour for additional side effects and/or symptoms.
ALLERGIES: Allergic to seafood and pet dander.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received influenza vaccine at different pharmacy locaton Sept 9. Came to Pharmacy for shingles Oct 6th. Technician gave informed consent form to a pharmacist to enter, but did not tell pharmacist it was for a shingles shot. Pharmacist assumed influenza and insurance paid. Pharmacist administering vaccine asked if patient had tolerated flu shots in the past. Patient indicated 'yes,' but did not indicate she was there for a shingles shot. Patient asked about follow up vaccine and pharmacist said not necessary with influenza, which is the point at which the error was noted. Counseled patient regarding duplication and gave correct vaccine (Shingrix) in left arm as well, per patient request. Patient had few symptoms from shot in Sept, unlikely flu this month will give greater symptoms, but counseled that shingles may, as it tends to have stronger local reaction than some other vaccines.

First dose, from 1 hour after vaccine to 24 hours later experienced nausea, headache, body aches, and chills.  No fever.  Body aches were severe enough to prevent sleep all night.  Taking ibuprofen has little effect.  Lifted following afternoon.  Second dose was 10/2/2020 at 1PM.  Reaction started about 10 hours later (11 PM) and lasted about the same amount of time, but was less severe and taking ibuprofen allowed sleep.  Lifted around bedtime the following day (about 24 hours after started.
OTHER_MEDS: Baclofen, Gabapentin, Allegra, calcium, magnesium, vitamin d

Patient at presentation for shot was fine, no breathing issues noted at this time.  Administration in right arm as patient sat in the buggy.  Pharmacist then administer sisters and grandmother's vaccines.  Within five minutes of administration mother cried out he's having an allergic reaction and pulled child the buggy.  Pharmacist instructed them to lay child on ground and grabbed the emergency kit instructing the tech to call 911 and prepared to draw up Benadryl to orally administer to child before other measures were taken.  Child appeared disoriented, no hives no swelling of the tongue noted.  Chest rise was normal and child began speaking.  No Benadryl was administered and child was monitored until EMS arrived.
LAB_DATA: 10/06/20EMS tested BS as 126 to screen for hypoglycemic event.  BP was WNR and Pulse was 95, high likely from the stimulation.  Patient was monitored for a few minutes and water and candy given to comfort him.
CUR_ILL: None noted by mother other than lethargy.  No fever, chills, other symptoms or signs of potential viral infection
HISTORY: None known at this time.  No history of seizures, diabetes or other disorders.
